{"title_page": "Disney Parks, Experiences and Products", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2017}}\n{{use American English|date=March 2017}}\n\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Disney Parks, Experiences and Products, Inc.\n| logo = Disney parks, experiences & products logo.svg\n| former_name = {{ubl|Walt Disney Outdoor Recreation Division (1980\u20131989)|Walt Disney Attractions (1989\u20132008)|Walt Disney Parks and Resorts Worldwide, Inc. (2008\u20132018)|Walt Disney Parks, Experiences and Consumer Products (2018)<ref name=\"cnbc\"/>}}\n| type = Subsidiary<ref name=sbz/>\n| fate = \n| successor = \n| predecessors = {{ubl|Walt Disney Parks and Resorts Worldwide|Disney Consumer Products and Interactive Media}}\n| foundation = {{Start date and age|1971|04|01}}\n| defunct = \n| location_city = [[Lake Buena Vista, Florida]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Company Overview of Walt Disney Parks and Resorts U.S., Inc |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/research/stocks/private/snapshot.asp?privcapId=4159864 |website=Bloomberg}}</ref>\n| location_country = United States\n| key_people = {{ubl|Rebecca Campbell (President, Disneyland Resort)|Michael Colglazier (President, Disney Parks International)|Josh D\u2019Amaro (President, Walt Disney World Resort)|Ken Potrock (President, Consumer Products)}}\n| industry = Consumer products, theme parks, attractions, video games, publishing, recreation, and hospitality\n| services = {{flatlist|\n*Theme parks\n*Hotel lodging\n*Cruises\n*Timeshares\n*Guided tours\n*Travel packages\n*Attraction design\n*Licensing}}\n| parent = [[The Walt Disney Company]]\n| divisions = {{ubl|Disney Parks International|[[Disney Parks, Experiences and Products#Disney Signature Experiences|Disney Signature Experiences]] }}\n| subsid = {{ubl|[[Disney Consumer Products]]|[[Disneyland Resort]]|[[Walt Disney World]]|[[Disney Vacation Club|Disney Vacation Development, Inc.]]|[[Disneyland Paris]]|Disneyland International|[[Walt Disney Imagineering|Walt Disney Imagineering Research & Development, Inc.]]|[[Disney Publishing Worldwide]]|[[The Muppets Studio]]|[[Disney Interactive]]}}\n| module = <!-- Used to embed other templates -->\n| website = {{URL|dpep.disney.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Disney Parks, Experiences and Products, Inc.''', formerly '''Walt Disney Parks and Resorts Worldwide, Inc.''' and informally known as '''Disney Parks''', is one of [[The Walt Disney Company]]'s four major business segments and a subsidiary.<ref name=sbz>{{cite web|title=Detail by Entity Name: Walt Disney Parks and Resorts Worldwide, Inc.|url=http://search.sunbiz.org/Inquiry/CorporationSearch/SearchResultDetail?inquirytype=EntityName&directionType=ForwardList&searchNameOrder=WALTDISNEYPARKSRESORTSWORLDWID%20F090000012040&aggregateId=forp-f09000001204-dfbb7cc6-7dee-4d8b-bbef-3244c551d808&searchTerm=Walt%20Disney%20Parks%20and%20Resorts%20Worldwide&listNameOrder=WALTDISNEYPARKSRESORTSWORLDWID%20F090000012040|website=SunBiz.org|publisher=Florida Department of State Division of Corporations|accessdate=October 12, 2015}}</ref> It was founded on April 1, 1971, exactly six months before the opening of [[Magic Kingdom]] at [[Walt Disney World|Walt Disney World Resort]] in [[Bay Lake, Florida|Bay Lake]], [[Florida]] just outside of [[Orlando]], Florida.\n\nOriginally, the company was known as '''Walt Disney Outdoor Recreation Division''' and later as '''Walt Disney Attractions'''. The most recent chairman of Walt Disney Parks and Resorts was [[Bob Chapek]], formerly president of [[Disney Consumer Products]]. Chapek was promoted CEO of the entire Walt Disney Company on February 25, 2020.<ref>https://www.cnbc.com/2020/02/25/who-is-bob-chapek-the-new-ceo-of-disney.html</ref><ref>https://www.latimes.com/entertainment-arts/business/story/2020-02-25/bob-chapek-named-walt-disney-co-ceo-replacing-bob-iger</ref> In 2018, the company's theme parks hosted over 157.3 million guests, making Disney Parks the world's most visited theme park company worldwide,<ref name=\"TEA/AECOM\">{{Cite web|title=TEA/AECOM 2018 Theme Index and Museum Index: The Global Attractions Attendance Report|url=http://www.teaconnect.org/images/files/TEA_235_103719_170601.pdf|publisher=[[Themed Entertainment Association|TEA]]/[[AECOM]]|date=2019|p=5|accessdate=August 25, 2019|archiveurl=http://www.teaconnect.org/images/files/328_572762_190522.pdf|archivedate=June 2, 2019}}</ref> with United Kingdom-based [[Merlin Entertainments]] coming in second at 67 million guests. It is by far Disney's largest business segment according to employee headcount, with approximately 130,000<ref name=\"Barnes\">{{cite news|last1=Barnes|first1=Brooks|title=Thomas Staggs: Disney\u2019s Heir, Apparently|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/04/26/business/media/thomas-staggs-disneys-heir-apparently.html|accessdate=April 26, 2015|work=The New York Times|publisher=The New York Times Company|date=April 26, 2015|location=New York|page=BU1}}</ref> of the company's 180,000 employees as of 2015.<ref name=10K>{{cite web|url=http://thewaltdisneycompany.com/sites/default/files/reports/fy14-form-10k.pdf|title=Form 10-K, U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission, by the Walt Disney Company for the Fiscal Year Ended September 27, 2014|publisher=The Walt Disney Company|accessdate=November 23, 2014|date=November 19, 2014|page=1|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141217131710/http://thewaltdisneycompany.com/sites/default/files/reports/fy14-form-10k.pdf|archivedate=December 17, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> In March 2018, [[Disney Consumer Products|Disney Consumer Products and Interactive Media]] was merged into Parks and Resorts and renamed Disney Parks, Experiences and Products.\n\n==Background==\n{{main|Disneyland, Inc.}}\nIn 1949, [[Ice Capades]] added a Disney segment to its performances. Costumes from those shows were used at the opening of Disneyland in 1955 with some performers hired away for Disney.<ref name=jhm>{{cite news|last1=Korkis|first1=Jim|title=Wednesdays with Wade: 25 years of \"Disney on Ice\"|url=http://jimhillmedia.com/alumni1/b/wade_sampson/archive/2005/09/14/1278.aspx|accessdate=July 30, 2015|work=JimHillMedia|date=September 13, 2005}}</ref>\n\nOriginally, entry into the theme park and travel business was a side project of Walt Disney himself. As the Disneylandia project started to become a reality, [[The Walt Disney Company|Walt Disney Productions]] at Walt's request set up Disneyland, Inc. (DLI) in 1951 and agreed to a design deal in March 1953 with [[Retlaw Enterprises|WED Enterprises (WED)]], [[Walt Disney|Walt]]'s personal corporation, which then included what would now be called [[Walt Disney Imagineering|Disney Imagineering]].<ref name=hwrg>{{cite book|last1=Aberdeen|first1=J. A.|title=Hollywood Renegades|date=2000|publisher=Cobblestone Entertainment|isbn=1-890110-24-8|url=https://archive.org/details/hollywoodrenegad00aber|accessdate=May 5, 2015|chapter=Disneyland|chapter-url=http://www.cobbles.com/simpp_archive/simpp_1954disneyland.htm }}</ref><ref group=CDL>{{cite book|last1=Thomas |first1=Bob |title=Building a Company - Roy O. Disney and the Creation of an Entertainment Empire|date=1998|page=254}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Gabler|first1=Neal|title=Walt Disney \u2013 The Triumph of the American Imagination|date=2006|page=493}}</ref> With the WED concept designs and prospectus for Disneylandia, Roy Disney in September 1953 met with TV networks in a deal for Disney-produced TV show and Disneyland investment. [[American Broadcasting-Paramount Theatres]] (AB-PT) agreed to the Disneyland, Inc. investment.<ref name=hwrg/> Joining AB-PT as Disneyland investors were [[Walt Disney Productions]] (WDP), [[Western Publishing]] and [[Walt Disney]].<ref group=CDL>{{cite book|last1=Thomas|first1=Bob|title=Walt Disney \u2013 An American Original|date=1994|page=222}}</ref> Walt Disney Productions had the option to repurchase the Walt Disney, WED and Western Publishing shares (31%) by May 1, 1959, for $562,500.<ref name=bbd>{{cite news|title=Disneyland Tabs $2.29 Per Capita; See Small Net First Yr.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yB4EAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA69&lpg=PA69&dq=Walt+Disney+Productions+Disneyland,+Inc.+option&source=bl&ots=0NOMFq8DpO&sig=eQQINoEQqlhCBUd2kikDffo7G3U&hl=en&sa=X&ei=qi5JVZ2xF4uYsAWrloCQDw&ved=0CB8Q6AEwATge#v=onepage&q=Walt%20Disney%20Productions%20Disneyland%2C%20Inc.%20option&f=false|accessdate=May 6, 2015|work=Billboard|date=January 28, 1956|page=69}}</ref>\n\nWith a need for the [[Disneyland Hotel (California)|Disneyland Hotel]] nearby and no funding available for Disney to build it, Walt Disney approached [[Jack Wrather]] to build the hotel who agreed.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Kimler|first1=Forest|title=Jack Built More Than a House|url=http://2.bp.blogspot.com/_OYARMoeQUr4/TH_wXKWs_pI/AAAAAAAABnU/XnEcgWwEtwk/s1600/1978+newspaper+2aa.JPG |accessdate=August 28, 2015 |work=Orange County Register|date=September 11, 1978}}</ref>\n\n[[Disneyland]], changed from Disneylandia, was announced in {{dts|1954|4}} by Walt to be opened in {{dts|1955|7}}.<ref group=CDL>Walt Disney, by Jim Fanning, 1994. Page 100.</ref><ref group=CDL>Walt Disney \u2013 Hollywood's Dark Prince, by Marc Eliot, 1993. Page 223.</ref> On {{dts|1955|7|17}}, the Disneyland park opened with five themed \"lands\" containing eighteen attractions with double the expected guests.<ref group=CDL>Walt Disney, by Jim Fanning, 1994. Page 102.</ref> WED owned [[Disneyland Railroad|Santa Fe & Disneyland Railroad]] opened, too.<ref name=lat>{{cite news|last=Peltz|first=James F.|title=The Wonderful World of Disney's Other Firm : Entertainment: Walt Disney created a separate company for his family. Retlaw Enterprises Inc. is now worth hundreds of millions.|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1990-10-02/business/fi-1834_1_walt-disney|accessdate=July 19, 2012|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|date=October 2, 1990}}</ref>\n\nOn June 29, 1957, Disney Production exercised its options to purchase all but AB-PT's common stock outstanding. This allowed WDP to consolidate DLI into its 1957 annual accounting statements adding four months' worth of net profits, $511K.<ref>{{cite news|title=Disneyland Draws 4,200,000; Parent Firm Buys More Stock|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ayEEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA86|accessdate=May 6, 2015|work=Billboard|date=January 13, 1958}}</ref> In June 1960, Walt Disney Productions completed the purchase of AB-PT's share of the company for nearly $7.5 million and its TV contract, and the theme park became a fully owned subsidiary of Walt Disney Productions.<ref group=CDL>{{cite book|last1=Thomas|first1=Bob |title=Walt Disney \u2013 An American Original |date=1994|page=286}}</ref> The first [[Audio-Animatronics|Audio-Animatronic]] attraction, [[Walt Disney's Enchanted Tiki Room]], opened at [[Disneyland]] in 1963.<ref>{{cite book |first=Richard W. |last=Kroon |title=A/V A to Z: An Encyclopedic Dictionary of Media, Entertainment and Other Audiovisual Terms |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HjmNAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA64 |year=2014 |publisher=McFarland |isbn=978-0-7864-5740-3 |page=64}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nBeginning in 1958 with the contracting of Economics Research Associates (ERA) to find a location for another Disney resort, Disney Productions moved beyond a single park. ERA recommended Florida; another study in 1961 named [[Ocala, Florida|Ocala]] or [[Orlando]] in Florida as possible locations. In {{dts|1963|11}}, Walt Disney made a trip to Florida for final site selection.<ref name=p48 group=CDW>Walt Disney \u2013 An American Original, by Bob Thomas, 1994.</ref><sup>:333, 334</sup> In 1962, Disney Productions purchased [[Celebrity Sports Center]] (opened on September 17, 1960, in Denver, Colorado) from its owners, including Walt Disney, [[Art Linkletter]], and [[John Payne (actor)|John Payne]], to use as a staff training center for its second resort.<ref name=d23a>{{cite web|title=Celebrity Sports Center|url=https://d23.com/a-to-z/celebrity-sports-center/|website=D23.com|publisher=The Walt Disney Company|accessdate=October 6, 2015}}</ref> In 1963, Roy made plans to buy from {{convert|5,000|to|10,000|acre}}, which was carried out in 1964, amassing {{convert|27,443|acre}} by {{dts|1965|10}}.<ref group=CDW>Building a Company \u2013 Roy O. Disney and the Creation of an Entertainment Empire, by Bob Thomas, 1998. Pages 278, 279, 281\u2013282.</ref><ref group=CDW name=aao>Walt Disney \u2013 An American Original, by Bob Thomas, 1994. Page 337.</ref> Plans for the Florida project that would eventually become [[Walt Disney World]] were announced to the public in November 1965.<ref group=CDW name=aao/> Legislation forming the [[Reedy Creek Improvement District]] was signed into law by Florida Governor [[Claude R. Kirk, Jr.]] on May 12, 1967, allowing Disney to build the infrastructure for the second park.<ref group=CDW>{{cite book|last1=Thomas |first1=Bob|title=Walt Disney \u2013 An American Original|date=1994|page=357}}</ref> Ground breaking followed for the future Reedy Creek park on May 30.<ref group=CDW>{{cite book|last1=Smith|first1=Dave|last2=Clark|first2=Steven|title=Disney \u2013 The First 100 Years|date=2002|page=103|edition=updated}}</ref> In Roy O. Disney's last act as CEO in 1968, he officially named the second park [[Walt Disney World]].<ref name=p48 group=CDW/><sup>:357</sup>\n\nDisneyland International was incorporated on November 20, 1961.<ref>{{cite web|title=Business Entity Detail: Disneyland International (C0423655; must search on name)|url=http://kepler.sos.ca.gov/|website=California Department of State|accessdate=September 24, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150315010639/http://kepler.sos.ca.gov/|archive-date=March 15, 2015|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The next year, [[The Oriental Land Company]] contacted Disney about building a theme park.<ref name=lat1>{{cite news|title=Disneyland in Tokyo Is a 10-Year Hit|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1994-04-12/business/fi-45190_1_tokyo-disneyland|accessdate=August 20, 2015|work=Los Angeles Times|agency=Associated Press|date=April 12, 1994}}</ref>\n\nIn 1959, the WED-owned [[Disneyland Monorail System|Disneyland-Alweg Monorail System]] was installed at Disneyland.<ref name=lat/><ref name=lat0>{{cite news|title=Disneyland: A Chronology|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1991-05-09/news/mn-2210_1_walt-disney| accessdate=September 23, 2015 |work=Los Angeles Times| date=May 9, 1991}}</ref> Disneyland's first new themed land, New Orleans Square, opened in {{dts|1966}}. Tomorrowland was revamped in 1967 with seven new attractions.<ref name=lat0/> The design and architectural group and the WED Enterprise name was purchased from Walt's corporation, renamed as Retlaw Enterprise.<ref name=lat/>\n\nDisney expanded into attractions at the [[1964 New York World's Fair]] with [[It's a Small World]]<ref name=gma/> and costumed character appearances. When the characters proved a hit at the 1964 World's Fair, Walt wanted another outlet for \"live\" characters; thus, Disneyland put on ''Disney on Parade'', a self-produced live arena show starting in 1969.<ref name=jhm/><ref>{{cite news|title=Live Disney Characters in Traveling Arena Show|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=rDwwAAAAIBAJ&sjid=ySoDAAAAIBAJ&pg=3905%2C4281044|accessdate=July 30, 2015|work=The News and the Eastern Townships Advocate|issue=Vol. 123 No. 45|publisher=E.R. Smith Co. Ltd.|date=September 17, 1970|location=St. Johns, PQ|pages=2, 3}}</ref> Small World and its famous song lasted two years at the fair; it was then moved to Disneyland as an expanded major attraction in 1966 and later duplicated in the other Disney theme parks.<ref name=gma>{{cite news|last1=Shaw Brown|first1=Genevieve|title=It's a Small World: 9 Little-Known Facts|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Travel/disneys-small-world-facts/story?id=22990670|accessdate=August 26, 2015|work=Good Morning America|publisher=ABC News|date=March 21, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 1965, Walt Disney won a bid with the [[US Forest Service]] to develop [[Mineral King]] as a ski resort. The [[Sierra Club]] sued in {{dts|1969|6}} to stop the development, which was granted by the federal district judge. The Forest Service appealed and won at the appeal and the Supreme Court. The Supreme Court ruling left open to the Club the possibility of refiling. In the next round of lawsuits, the same district judge blocked the redevelopment. The injunction and the passage of the [[National Environmental Policy Act]] led to Disney backing out.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.hcn.org/wotr/the-saga-of-mineral-king |title=The saga of Mineral King |date=February 2, 2009 |newspaper=High Country News |accessdate=September 12, 2009}}</ref>\n\n$40 million worth of Walt Disney Productions Convertible [[Debenture]]s were sold in {{dts|1968|1}} to fund Disney World (WDW). The next year in February, an agreement was made with multiple labor unions, in which the unions exchanged the right to strike for regular pay increases during the first building phase.<ref group=CDW>{{cite news|work=U.S. News & World Report|last1=Cooper|first1=M|last2=Friedman|first2=D|title=Empire of the Sun|date=May 28, 1990|page=47}}</ref> By 1971, chairman of the Park Operations Committee and vice president of park operations Dick Nunis was appointed executive vice president of Disneyland and Walt Disney World.<ref>{{cite web|title=Disney Legend: Dick Nunis|url=https://d23.com/walt-disney-legend/dick-nunis/|website=d23|publisher=The Walt Disney Company|accessdate=October 7, 2015}}</ref>\n\n[[Walt Disney World]] began operation on {{dts|1971|10|1}}, with the [[Magic Kingdom]] park at a cost of $400 million. The Magic Kingdom had six themed lands: Main Street, Adventureland, Fantasyland, Frontierland, Liberty Square, and Tomorrowland.<ref group=CDW>{{cite book|title=Birnbaum's Walt Disney World 1997|url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780786881925|url-access=registration|date=1996|publisher=Hearst Business Publishing|page=[https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780786881925/page/15 15]}}</ref> Additionally, Disney's Fort Wilderness Resort campground and two hotels, Disney's Contemporary Resort and Disney's Polynesian Village Resort, also opened.<ref group=CDW>{{cite book| last1=Smith|first1=Dave |title=Disney A to Z \u2013 The Official Encyclopedia| url=https://archive.org/details/disneytozofficia00smit| url-access=registration|date=1996|page=[https://archive.org/details/disneytozofficia00smit/page/103 103], 191,397}}</ref>\n\nDisneyland expanded in 1972 with a seventh themed land, [[Bear Country (Disneyland)|Bear Country]], replacing the Indian Village of Frontierland, and later renamed Critter Country. In 1979, the Disneyland crafts and maintenance union workers went on strike for 15 days, at first, rejecting and then accepting the park's contract.<ref name=lat0/> [[Space Mountain (Disneyland)|Space Mountain]] opens at Disneyland in 1977.<ref name=lat0/>\n\nTwo more hotels opened in 1973 at Walt Disney World: the Golf Resort<ref>{{cite web|title=Disney Inn, The|url=https://d23.com/a-to-z/disney-inn-the/|website=D23: Disney A to Z|publisher=The Walt Disney Company|accessdate=September 23, 2015}}</ref> and the Gold Resort;<ref group=CDW>{{cite book|last1=Smith|first1=Dave|title=Disney A to Z \u2013 The Official Encyclopedia|url=https://archive.org/details/disneytozofficia00smit|url-access=registration|date=1996|page=[https://archive.org/details/disneytozofficia00smit/page/209 209]}}</ref> Disney's Village Resort hotel opened in 1974.{{citation needed|date=September 2015}} Disney opened the Buena Vista Club golf club in Lake Buena Vista on {{dts|1974|11|22}}.<ref name=r228 group=CDW0>{{cite book|last1=Smith|first1=Dave|title=Disney A to Z \u2013 The Official Encyclopedia|url=https://archive.org/details/disneytozofficia00smit|url-access=registration|date=1996}}</ref><sup>:71</sup> [[Disney Springs|Lake Buena Vista Village]], the shopping area, opened on {{dts|1975|3|22}}<ref name=r228 group=CDW0/> and was renamed Walt Disney World Village in 1977.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Smith |first1=Dave |title=Downtown Disney Marketplace |url=https://d23.com/a-to-z/downtown-disney-marketplace/|website=D23: Disney A to Z|publisher=Walt Disney Company|accessdate=September 24, 2015}}</ref><sup>:280</sup> Celebrity Sports Center, Disney World's training center, was sold on March 29, 1979.<ref name=d23a/>\n\nAt Walt Disney World, the Treasure Island nature preserve pens opened on April 8, 1974,<ref name=r501 group=CDW0>Disney A to Z \u2013 The Updated Official Encyclopedia, by Dave Smith, 1998.</ref><sup>:569</sup> renamed Discovery Island in 1977.<ref name=r228 group=CDW0/><sup>:126</sup> On {{dts|1975|7|1}}, the [[WEDway PeopleMover]] opened in the Magic Kingdom's Tomorrowland.<ref group=CDW0>Disney Magazine, Summer 1999. Page 85.</ref> The first water park, [[Disney's River Country|River Country]], opened on {{dts|1976|6|20}} at Disney World.<ref name=r210 group=CDW0>Birnbaum's Walt Disney World 1997, by Hearst Business Publishing, 1996.</ref><sup>:22</sup> [[Epcot|EPCOT]] Center's groundbreaking occurred at Walt Disney World in May 1979.<ref group=CDW0>Walt Disney World, by The Walt Disney Company, 1994?.</ref>\n\nIn 1979, [[Oriental Land]] and Disney agreed to build a Japanese theme park.<ref name=lat1 /> [[Tokyo Disneyland]] opened on {{dts|1983|4|15}} on {{convert|200|acre|sigfig=1}} in [[Urayasu, Chiba]], Japan.<ref name=lat2>{{cite news|last1=Miller|first1=Greg|title=Disney Plans Aquatic Park in Tokyo|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1995-11-08/business/fi-711_1_tokyo-disneysea|accessdate=August 20, 2015|work=Los Angeles Times|date=November 8, 1995}}</ref>\n\n===Walt Disney Outdoor Recreation Division===\nWith the June 3, 1980, retirement of [[Donn Tatum]] as Walt Disney Productions' Chairman and CEO, three divisions were formed, including the Walt Disney Outdoor Recreation Division, of which Nunis was named division president.<ref group=CDW0>The New York Times, [http://kpolsson.com/disnehis/disn1980.htm June 4, 1980]. Page D1.</ref> Disneyland started using [[Company scrip|Disney Dollars]] on May 5, 1987,<ref group=CDL4>Canadian Coin News, July 21, 1987, Volume 25, Number 6. Page 2.</ref>  while Walt Disney World parks started with Epcot on October 2.<ref group=CDW1>Canadian Coin News, October 27, 1987, Volume 25, Number 13. Page 1.</ref> A renegotiated Disneyland Japan royalty agreement in April 1988 by Chief Financial Officer [[Gary L. Wilson]] netted Disney US$723 million in cash in exchange for lower royalty payments.<ref group=CDW0>Forbes, [http://kpolsson.com/disnehis/disn1988.htm March 6, 1989], Volume 143. Page 42.</ref>\n\nThe steam railroad and monorail at Disneyland were purchased from [[Retlaw Enterprises]], formerly WED Enterprises, in 1982.<ref name=lat0/> Bear Country was renamed [[Critter Country]] on November 23, 1988.<ref group=CDL4>'' Disneyland: Then, Now, and Forever'', by Bruce Gordon and Tim O'Day, 2005. Page 99.</ref>\n\n[[Tishman Realty & Construction|Tishman Company]]'s plans for two Walt Disney World hotels were rejected by the new CEO [[Michael Eisner]] on September 30, 1984, marking a change in Disney architecture. New plans for the Dolphin and Swan hotels were submitted by Michael Graves in July 1986;<ref group=CDW1>Building a Dream \u2013 The Art of Disney Architecture, by Beth Dunlop, 1996. Pages 63,66.</ref> ground breaking took place on January 28, 1988.<ref group=CDW1>The New York Times, January 28, 1988. Page C1.</ref> The first non-Disney owned hotel, Pickett Suite Resort, opened in [[Disney Springs|Disney World Village]] on March 15, 1987.<ref group=CDW1>Disney A to Z \u2013 The Official Encyclopedia, by Dave Smith, 1996. Page 387.</ref>\n\nOn June 1, 1982, the Walt Disney World monorail line was extended to EPCOT Center from the Ticket and Transportation Center.<ref name=r228 group=CDW0/><sup>:338</sup> The EPCOT Center theme park opened on October 1, 1982, at a building cost of US$1.2 billion, with two areas, [[Epcot#Future World|Future World]] and [[World Showcase]].<ref group=CDW0>Walt Disney \u2013 Hollywood's Dark Prince, by Marc Eliot, 1993.</ref><sup>:272</sup>\n\nPlans for a Hollywood-style theme park were announced in April 1985 for the Walt Disney World resort at a project cost of US$300 million.<ref group=CDW1>Prince of the Magic Kingdom, by Joe Flower, 1991.</ref> In April 1985, Disney signed a licensing agreement with [[MGM]], giving Disney the right to use the MGM name, logo and movie library for this third park.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Weiss|first1=Werner|title=Disney-MGM Studios: The End of the MGM Name|url=http://www.yesterland.com/mgm-end.html|website=Yesterland.com|publisher=|accessdate=October 7, 2015}} sources:\n*{{cite book|last1=Eisner|first1=Michael|title=Work in Progress|url=https://archive.org/details/workinprogress00eisn_0|url-access=registration|date=1998}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Grover|first1=Ron|title=The Disney Touch|url=https://archive.org/details/disneytouchhowda0000grov|url-access=registration|date=1991}}</ref> Construction of the [[Disney's Hollywood Studios|Disney-MGM Studios]] theme park began in 1986.<ref group=CDW1>Walt Disney World \u2013 20 Magical Years, by the Walt Disney Company, 1991/2?.</ref> Disney-MGM Studios opened on May 1, 1989,<ref group=CDW1>Page D5. The New York Times, May 1, 1989, Volume 138, Number 47857.</ref> along with a Pleasure Island entertainment area;<ref group=CDW1>Birnbaum's Walt Disney World 1997, by Hearst Business Publishing, 1996. Page 18.</ref> its second water park, [[Disney's Typhoon Lagoon]], opened on June 1.<ref group=CDW1>Orlando Attractions, Summer 2009. Page 33.</ref> In 1983, Walt Disney World Village's name was changed to the Disney Village Marketplace.<ref group=CDW1>Disney A to Z \u2013 The Official Encyclopedia, by Dave Smith, 1996. Page 132.</ref> A new themed area, Mickey's Birthdayland, opened in the Magic Kingdom near Fantasyland on June 18, 1988.<ref group=CDW1>Disney A to Z \u2013 The Official Encyclopedia, by Dave Smith, 1996. Page 324.</ref>\n\nIn 1987, Disney and [[Ron Brierley]]'s Industrial Equity (Pacific) Ltd., already a 28% owner of the [[Jack Wrather|Wrather Corporation]], agreed to purchase the remaining Wrather Corporation stock with a 50% share each.<ref name=nyt>{{cite news|last1=Berg|first1=Eric N.|title=Company News; Wrather Accepts $21-a-Share Offer|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1987/09/29/business/company-news-wrather-accepts-21-a-share-offer.html|accessdate=August 27, 2015|work=New York Times|date=September 29, 1987}}</ref><ref name=nyt0>{{cite news|last1=|first1=|title=COMPANY NEWS; Disney Buys Stake|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1988/03/30/business/company-news-disney-buys-stake.html|accessdate=August 27, 2015|work=New York Times|date=March 30, 1988}}</ref> Wrather Corporation owned the [[Disneyland Hotel (California)|Disneyland Hotel]] and operated the [[RMS Queen Mary|Queen Mary]] and [[Hughes H-4 Hercules|Spruce Goose]] tourist attractions.<ref name=nyt/> In March 1988, Disney purchased Industrial Equity's half of Wrather Corporation.<ref name=nyt0/>\n\nIn 1985, [[Premier Cruise Line]] became the licensed partner cruise line with Disney. This allowed Disney characters on their ships and combined cruise, hotel, and theme park packages.<ref name=usat2>{{cite news|last1=Fritscher|first1=Lisa|title=How Disney Cruises Started|url=http://traveltips.usatoday.com/disney-cruises-started-17319.html|accessdate=October 8, 2015|work=USA Today|agency=Demand Media|publisher=Gannett Satellite Information Network, Inc.\n|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180316130947/https://traveltips.usatoday.com/disney-cruises-started-17319.html |archive-date=March 16, 2018}} (use archival url as original info was replaced.)</ref>\n\n===Walt Disney Attractions===\nThe Walt Disney Outdoor Recreation Division was incorporated as Walt Disney Attractions, Inc. on August 10, 1989.<ref>{{cite web|title=Detail by Entity Name: Walt Disney Attractions, Incorporated |url= http://search.sunbiz.org/Inquiry/CorporationSearch/SearchResultDetail?inquirytype=EntityName&directionType=PreviousList&searchNameOrder=WALTDISNEYATTRACTIONS%20P255770&aggregateId=forp-p25577-93b956e8-76e8-42c2-b789-99a8528d7053&searchTerm=Walt%20Disney%20Parks%20and%20Resorts%20Worldwide&listNameOrder=WALTDIESINGASSOCIATES%20K475700 |website=SunBiz.org |publisher=Florida Department of State Division of Corporations|accessdate=October 12, 2015}}</ref> In January 1990, Disney CEO Eisner announced plans to expand both Disneyland (by 20% in 10 years)<ref group=CDC>The New York Times, [http://kpolsson.com/disnehis/disn1990.htm January 13, 1990]. Page 37.</ref> and Walt Disney World (WDW). The plan would have WDW add another theme park and 16 new attractions in Disney-MGM Studios.<ref group=CDW2>The New York Times, January 16, 1990. Page D8.</ref> Disney and [[The Coca-Cola Company]] agreed to a 15-year marketing contract on January 25: Coca-Cola products would be exclusive in Disney theme parks, and Coca-Cola would use some Disney characters in their ads.<ref group=CDC>The New York Times, January 26, 1990. Page D4.</ref> On March 16, 1990, Attractions president Nunis announced a 25-year plan for a {{convert|4400|acre|adj=on}} development in [[Osceola, Florida]], with homes, shopping malls and industrial buildings.<ref group=CDC>The New York Times, [http://kpolsson.com/disnehis/disn1990.htm March 17, 1990]. Page 37.</ref>\n\nIn 1990, the possibility of a West Coast version of Epcot Center was placed in development.<ref group=CDC>Business Week, [http://kpolsson.com/disnehis/disn1990.htm January 29, 2001]. Page 58.</ref> This was announced as [[WestCOT]] in 1991, to be placed at the Disneyland Resort.<ref name=lat0/> On July 31, 1990, a new {{convert|350|acre|adj=on}} ocean-themed park and resort, Port Disney, was announced for Long Beach. Port was to have a cruise-ship terminal, five hotels, restaurants, and shopping areas, costing $2 billion to build.<ref group=CDC>The New York Times, [http://kpolsson.com/disnehis/disn1990jul.htm August 1, 1990]. Page D4.</ref> On December 12, 1991, Disney selected only one California project to go forward with, Disneyland Resort, which was to include the WestCOT Center, hotels, a shopping mall, and a lake. <ref group=CDL5>The New York Times, December 13, 1991. Page D1.</ref> Port Disney was abandoned in March 1992, and Disney canceled its leases on the Queen Mary and Spruce Goose attractions picked up from the Wrather Corporation.<ref group=CDC>The New York Times, [http://kpolsson.com/disnehis/disn1992.htm March 7, 1992]. Page 49.</ref> [[Mickey's Toontown]], a new themed land at Disneyland, opened on January 24, 1993.<ref group=CDL5>Walt Disney \u2013 Hollywood's Dark Prince, by Marc Eliot, 1993. Page 279.</ref> Disney canceled its plans for WestCOT in mid-1995 due to financial issues at [[Disneyland Paris]] and the park's projected high cost. That park was then replaced by plans for the [[Disney California Adventure|California Adventure]] park, hotels, and a retail district.<ref name=wsj>{{cite news|last1=Marr|first1=Merissa|title=Disney's $1 Billion Adventure|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB119257768823361264|accessdate=November 16, 2015|work=The Wall Street Journal|date=October 17, 2007|page=B1}}</ref>\n\nAt Walt Disney World, Mickey's Birthdayland closed on April 22, 1991, then reopened on May 26 as Mickey's Starland.<ref name=r228 group=CDW2>Disney A to Z \u2013 The Official Encyclopedia, by Dave Smith, 1996.</ref><sup>324, 329, 333</sup> In order to expand Disney World on wetland, on April 23, 1993, the company agreed to form an {{convert|8500|acre|adj=on}} wilderness preserve in Florida.<ref group=CDW2>Disney Magazine, Summer 2001. Page 39.</ref> The Disney Inn hotel was leased starting February 1, 1994, by the US Army, then purchased on January 12, 1996, and later renamed Shades of Green.<ref name=r228 group=CDW2/><sup>130</sup> [[Planet Hollywood]] opened a location in Pleasure Island on December 17, 1994.<ref group=CDW1>''The Disney Magazine'', Fall 1995, Volume 30, Number 4. Page 43.</ref> The third water park at Walt Disney World, [[Disney's Blizzard Beach]], opened on April 1, 1995.<ref group=CDW3>Birnbaum's Walt Disney World 1997, by Hearst Business Publishing, 1996. Page 192.</ref> The Magic Kingdom's Tomorrowland was completely refurbished and reopened in June 1995.<ref group=CDW3>Building a Dream \u2013 The Art of Disney Architecture, by Beth Dunlop, 1996. Page 192.</ref> Taking up a corner of the Magic Kingdom parking lot, the [[Walt Disney World Speedway]] opened on November 28, 1995.<ref group=CDW3>[https://d23.com/a-to-z/walt-disney-world-speedway/ Walt Disney World Speedway]. Disney A to Z \u2013 The Updated Official Encyclopedia, by Dave Smith, 1998. Page 597.</ref> In 1996, the [[Disney Institute]] opened on February 9,<ref group=CDW3>Birnbaum's Walt Disney World 1997, by Hearst Business Publishing, 1996. Page 181.</ref> and [[Disney's BoardWalk Resort|Disney's BoardWalk]] opened on July 1.<ref group=CDW3>[https://d23.com/a-to-z/boardwalk/ Boardwalk]. Page 62. (1996). Disney A to Z \u2013 The Official Encyclopedia, by Dave Smith.</ref> The first of the [[World of Disney]] stores opened in the Disney Village Marketplace on October 3.<ref group=CDW3>Smith, Dave. [https://d23.com/a-to-z/world-of-disney/ World of Disney]. Page 62. (1999). Disney A to Z \u2013 The Updated Official Encyclopedia.</ref> The Downtown Disney district opened in November 1997, combining Disney Village Marketplace and Pleasure Island.<ref group=CDW3>Disney Magazine, Spring 1998. Page 31.</ref> A fourth theme park, [[Disney's Animal Kingdom]], opened at Disney World the week of April 20, 1998.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lancaster|first1=Cory|title=Animal Kingdom Throws Star-studded Bash|url=http://articles.orlandosentinel.com/1998-04-20/news/9804190408_1_walt-disney-animal-kingdom-disney-theme|accessdate=November 12, 2015|work=Orlando Sentinel|date=April 20, 1998}}</ref>\n\nThe first [[Disney Vacation Club|Disney Vacation Club Resorts]], Vacation Club Resort, opened on October 1, 1991, and was renamed Disney's Old Key West Resort in January 1996. These vacation club hotels were operated by Disney Vacation Developments, Inc. as vacation [[timeshares]].<ref group=CDW2>The Disney Magazine, Spring 1996, Volume 31, Number 2. Page 18.\n*Disney A to Z \u2013 The Updated Official Encyclopedia, by Dave Smith, 1998. Page 584.</ref> The first off-resort vacation club hotel was Vacation Club Resort, which opened on October 1, 1995, in [[Vero Beach, Florida]].<ref group=CDC>[https://d23.com/a-to-z/vacation-club-resort-vero-beach-florida/ \"Vacation Club Resort, Vero Beach, Florida\"]. Page 584. ''Disney A to Z \u2013 The Updated Official Encyclopedia'', by Dave Smith, 1998. Via [http://kpolsson.com/disnehis/disn1994jul.htm Chronology of Walt Disney Company (End of 1994)].</ref>\n\nIn 1993, Premier Cruises discontinued its partnership with Disney for one with [[Warner Bros.]] After failing to reach agreements with [[Carnival Cruise Line|Carnival]] or [[Royal Caribbean International|Royal Caribbean]], Disney announced in 1994 the formation of its cruise line. The [[Disney Cruise Line]] launched with the Disney Magic ship in 1998 along with its exclusive resort island port of Castaway Cay.<ref name=usat2/>\n\nDisney reportedly had plans to build a park named [[Disney's America]]. The park was to have been located in [[Haymarket, Virginia]]; {{convert|2300|acre}} of property were purchased from Exxon in 1993.<ref group=CDC>[http://kpolsson.com/disnehis/disn1993.htm Work in Progress], by Michael Eisner, 1998. Page 321.</ref> The history-themed park was announced on November 11, 1993. The plans for the {{convert|3000|acre}} called for a {{convert|150|acre|adj=on}} amusement park, a campground, a golf course, {{convert|2|e6sqft|m2}} of office/commercial space, and 2500 homes.<ref group=CDC>The New York Times, [http://kpolsson.com/disnehis/disn1993jul.htm November 12, 1993]. Page A14.</ref> With projections indicating that the park would operate at a loss and with opposition in the press, Disney canceled the project on September 15, 1994.<ref group=CDC>''Disney War'', by James Stewart, 2005. Page 190.</ref>\n\n[[Walt Disney Imagineering]] created [[Disney Fair]], a U.S. traveling attraction, which premiered in September 1996. The fair was poorly attended and was pulled after a few stops. Disney Entertainment Projects (Asia Pacific) Inc., a new Disney Asian Pacific subsidiary, selected a renamed fair called DisneyFest as its first project, taking it to Singapore to open there on October 30, 1997.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Matzer|first1=Marla|title=It Didn't Play in Puyallup, so Disney Tries Singapore|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1997/aug/28/business/fi-26586|accessdate=September 23, 2015|work=Los Angeles Times|date=August 28, 1997}}</ref>\n\nIn November 1995, Disney announced the building of [[Tokyo DisneySea]], to be owned by Oriental along with Tokyo Disneyland.<ref name=lat2/> Oriental and Disney signed the DisneySea licensing agreement in November 1997; the theme park was scheduled to open in 2001 at a cost of $2.6 billion.<ref>{{cite news|title=Disney, Partner to Build New Tokyo Theme Park|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1997/nov/27/business/fi-58134|accessdate=August 20, 2015|work=Los Angeles Times|agency=Associated Press|date=November 27, 1997}}</ref>\n\nIn December 1998, Walt Disney Attractions added [[Euro Disney S.C.A.|Disneyland Paris]], Disney Regional Entertainment and [[Walt Disney Imagineering]] to its portfolio, which already held Disney World, Disney Cruise Line, Disneyland, and Tokyo Disneyland. Chairman Dick Nunis retired at the same time.<ref name=\"os3\">{{cite news|last1=Lancaster|first1=Cory|title=Disney's Nunis To Retire|url=http://articles.orlandosentinel.com/1998-12-12/business/9812111396_1_walt-disney-disney-world-disney-imagineering|accessdate=August 20, 2015|work=Orlando Sentinel|date=December 12, 1998}}</ref> On October 31, 1999, Walt Disney Attractions, Inc. was merged into Walt Disney Attractions, LLC.<ref>{{cite web|title=Merger Sheet|url=http://search.sunbiz.org/Inquiry/CorporationSearch/ConvertTiffToPDF?storagePath=COR\\1999\\1105\\00031850.TIF&documentNumber=P25577|website=SunBiz.org|publisher=State of Florida|accessdate=November 17, 2015|format=tif|date=October 28, 1999}}</ref>\n\nOn June 19, 1998, Disney Regional Entertainment opened its first DisneyQuest, a location-based entertainment venue, at Downtown Disney West Side in Walt Disney World.<ref name=ct>{{cite news|last1=Pecho|first1=Bruce|title=Virtual Reality Rules At Disney's Newest Theme Park|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1998-05-31/travel/9805310289_1_virtual-jungle-cruise-disneyquest-virtual-reality|accessdate=April 18, 2016|work=Chicago Tribune|publisher=Tribune Publishing|date=May 31, 1998}}</ref> The first DisneyQuest outside of a resort was opened in Chicago on June 16, 1999, with plans for more locations worldwide.<ref name=\"ct0\">{{cite news|last1=Bigness|first1=Jon|title=Disney's Daring Concept|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1999-06-16/business/9906160311_1_virtual-jungle-cruise-disney-regional-entertainment-disney-theme-park-experience |accessdate=April 18, 2016 |work=Chicago Tribune|publisher=Tribune Publishing|date=June 16, 1999}}</ref>\n\nIn 1999, plans were announced for a new resort in [[Hong Kong]], [[Hong Kong Disneyland]], as a joint venture, Hong Kong International Theme Parks Ltd., between the Hong Kong Government and Disney Resorts.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Chung|first1=Yulanda|title=Making A Magic Kingdom|url=http://www.cnn.com/ASIANOW/asiaweek/magazine/99/1112/cover1.html|accessdate=April 18, 2016|work=Asiaweek|issue=Volume 25, Number 45.|publisher=CNN|date=November 12, 1999}}</ref> The ''[[Disney Wonder]]'' cruise ship began operation on August 15.<ref name=\"usatoday\">{{cite news|last1=Nefer|first1=Barb|title=Disney Cruise Line History|url=http://traveltips.usatoday.com/disney-cruise-line-history-20748.html|accessdate=April 18, 2016|work=USA Today|agency=Demand Media}}</ref> Disney World's [[Discovery Island (Bay Lake)|Discovery Island]] was closed on April 8, 1999.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Hill|first1=Jim|title=Will pirates soon be returning to Treasure ... er ... Discovery Island?|url=http://jimhillmedia.com/editor_in_chief1/b/jim_hill/archive/2008/06/06/will-pirates-soon-be-returning-to-treasure-er-discovery-island.aspx|accessdate=April 13, 2016|work=Jim Hill Media|date=June 5, 2008}}</ref>\n\n===Disney Destinations===\nWalt Disney Attractions, LLC changed its name to Walt Disney Parks and Resorts, LLC on April 14, 2000, then to Disney Destinations, LLC on April 25, 2006.<ref>{{cite web|title=Events: Name History|url=http://search.sunbiz.org/Inquiry/CorporationSearch/NameHistory?aggregateId=flal-l99000007022-1294f8b4-a7e2-4162-b4d2-08fe03fbfb5c&entityId=L99000007022&CurrentPage=0&SearchTerm=Walt%20Disney%20Parks%20and%20Resorts%20Worldwide&InquiryType=EntityName&inquiryDirectionType=CurrentList&SearchNameOrder=WALTDISNEYATTRACTIONS%20L990000070220&ListNameOrder=WALTDIESINGASSOCIATES%20K475700 |website=SunBiz.org|publisher=State of Florida|accessdate=November 17, 2015}}</ref> [[Tokyo DisneySea]] at [[Tokyo Disney Resort]] opened on September 4, 2001.<ref>{{cite news|title=Disney's New Tokyo Sea-Themed Park Opens|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2001/sep/05/business/fi-42280|accessdate=August 20, 2015|work=Los Angeles Times|agency=|date=September 5, 2001|first=Richard|last=Verrier}}</ref> The Walt Disney Company in selling its Japanese and US chains decided to keep the [[Disney Store]]s in Europe, along with the store in Manhattan, which was converted into a [[World of Disney]] store run by Walt Disney Parks and Resorts in 2004.<ref>{{cite news|last1=McGeehan|first1=Patrick|title=For Disney, the Magic on Fifth Avenue Ends|url=http://cityroom.blogs.nytimes.com/2009/09/23/for-disney-the-magic-on-fifth-avenue-ends/comment-page-1/?_r=0|accessdate=November 12, 2015|work=New York Times|date=September 23, 2009}}</ref>\n\n[[Downtown Disney (Disneyland Resort)|Downtown Disney]] opened at the [[Disneyland Resort]] on January 12, 2001, between Disneyland and the future California Adventure. <ref group=CDC>Pages 23,28. [http://kpolsson.com/disnehis/disn2001.htm Disney Magazine]. Fall 2000. Accessed on April 18, 2016.\n*Page 16. Disney Magazine, Winter 2000\u20132001.</ref> [[Disney California Adventure|Disney California Adventure Park]] opened at the [[Disneyland Resort]] on February 8, 2001, with three major areas: Paradise Pier, Hollywood Pictures Backlot, and the Golden State.<ref name=wsj/> In California Adventure on October 6, 2002, A Bug's Land area opened.<ref group=CDC>http://kpolsson.com/disnehis/disn2002.htm Disney Magazine, Spring 2003, Volume 8, Number 2. Page 29.</ref> Parks and Resorts chairman Jay Rasulo announced at Disney's D23 Expo in Anaheim, California on September 12, 2009, that Walt Disney World's Fantasyland would be overhauled and increased in size by 2013.<ref group=CDC>[http://kpolsson.com/disnehis/disn2009.htm Orlando Attractions], Winter 2010. Page 33.  Accessed on April 18, 2016.</ref> A $1 billion expansion/renovation of [[Disney California Adventure|Disney California Adventure Park]] was announced in 2007 to be completed by 2012.<ref name=lat3>{{cite news|last1=MacDonald|first1=Brady|title=Disney California Adventure: How we got here and what's next |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2012/jun/18/news/la-trb-disney-california-adventure-retrospective-06201217 |accessdate=April 19, 2016|work=Los Angeles Times|date=June 18, 2012}}</ref>\n\n[[Disney's River Country|River Country]] water park closed on September 1, 2001.<ref group=CDC>Disney Twenty-three, Fall 2011, Volume 3, Issue 3.</ref><ref>Orlando Attractions, October 2008, Volume 1, Number 6.</ref> Disney-MGM Studios is renamed [[Disney's Hollywood Studios]] in January 2008.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Mervine|first1=Bob|title=Disney-MGM Studios to be renamed|url=http://www.bizjournals.com/orlando/stories/2007/08/06/daily34.html|accessdate=April 19, 2016|work=Orlando Business Journal|publisher=American City Business Journals|date=August 9, 2007}}</ref> [[Pleasure Island (Walt Disney World Resort)|Pleasure Island]]'s core remaining six nightclubs were closed down in late 2008 to change the area to match the family friendly make-up of the other two sections of [[Disney Springs|Downtown Disney]] at Disney World.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Powers|first1=Scott|title=The party's over at Pleasure Island: Disney to shut down 6 nightclubs|url=http://articles.orlandosentinel.com/2008-06-28/news/disney28_1_pleasure-island-downtown-disney-downtown-orlando|accessdate=April 19, 2016|work=Orlando Sentinel|date=June 28, 2008}}</ref>\n\n[[Walt Disney Studios Park]] opened March 16, 2002, as the second theme park at the renamed [[Disneyland Paris|Disneyland Resort Paris]]. The first park was renamed [[Disneyland Park (Paris)|Disneyland Park]] (DLP.<ref group=CDC>[http://kpolsson.com/disnehis/disn2002.htm Disney Magazine]. Winter 2001\u20132002.  Page 22.\n*Disney Magazine, Spring 2002.  Page 28.\n*Disney Magazine, Winter 2002, Volume 8, Number 1.  Page 54.\n*Stewart, James (2005). ''Disney War''. Page 387.\n*Jody Revenson (editor), 2006. Disney Insider Yearbook 2005 Year in Review. Page 81. Accessed on April 19, 2016.</ref> DLP Paris opened in August 2000 [[Toy Story Land|Toy Story Playland]] with three attractions.<ref name=CDC>[http://kpolsson.com/disnehis/disn2009.htm Orlando Attractions], Fall 2010, Volume 3, Number 4. Page 22. Accessed on April 19, 2016.</ref>\n\nConstruction on Hong Kong Disneyland began on January 12, 2003,<ref>Jody Revenson (editor), 2006. ''[http://kpolsson.com/disnehis/disn2003.htm Disney Insider Yearbook 2005 Year in Review]''. Page 69. Accessed on April 19, 2016.</ref> then opened September 12, 2005.<ref group=CDC>[http://kpolsson.com/disnehis/disn2005.htm Disney Magazine], Summer 2005, Volume 10, Number 3.  Page 33. Accessed on April 19, 2016.\n*Jody Revenson (editor), 2006. Disney Insider Yearbook 2005 Year in Review]''. Page 5.</ref> Groundbreaking occurred at Hong Kong Disneyland in December 2009 for a three land expansion: [[Mystic Point]], [[Grizzly Gulch]], and [[Toy Story Land]].<ref group=CDC>[http://kpolsson.com/disnehis/disn2009.htm Orlando Attractions]. Spring 2010, Volume 3, Number 2. Page 61. Accessed on April 19, 2016.</ref>\n\nIn June 2005, Disney Magic made the first cruise outside of the Caribbean, by moving its port for the summer to Los Angeles with a Mexican Riviera schedule.<ref name=\"usatoday\"/> Disney Cruise Line ordered a new 2 ships class from [[Meyer Werft]] shipyard in Germany by February 22, 2007.<ref name=\"usatoday\"/><ref group=CDC>[http://kpolsson.com/disnehis/disn2007.htm Oars & Ears]. December 2006, Volume 7, Number 9. Page 7. Accessed on April 19, 2016.</ref> The Magic in May 2007 transferred its homeport to Barcelona, Spain, for the lines' first summer Mediterranean itinerary then returned to its permanent port in September.<ref name=\"usatoday\"/>\n\nThe Chicago DisneyQuest location was closed in September 2001.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Elder|first1=Robert K.|title=What went wrong at DisneyQuest? |url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2001-07-16/features/0107160127_1_disneyquest-family-entertainment-entertainment-companies |accessdate=April 18, 2016 |work=Chicago Tribune |publisher=Tribune Publishing |date=July 16, 2001}}</ref> Disney Parks started the [[Adventures by Disney]] tour vacation business in 2005.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Ward|first1=Terry |title=Adventures by Disney: Long weekends, Disney-style |url= http://experience.usatoday.com/weekend/story/my-weekend-experience/2015/02/24/adventures-by-disney-weekend-trips/23950735/ |accessdate=April 19, 2016|work=USA Today |date=February 24, 2015 }}</ref> Disney entered a float, \"The Most Magical Celebration on Earth\", into the 2006 Pasadena [[Rose Parade|Tournament of Roses parade]].<ref group=CDC>Jody Revenson (editor), 2006. [http://kpolsson.com/disnehis/disn2006.htm Disney Insider Yearbook 2005 Year in Review]''. Page 5. Accessed on April 19, 2016.</ref>\n\nIn October 2007, Disney announced plans to build a resort at Ko Olina Resort & Marina in [[Kapolei, Hawaii]], featuring both a hotel and Disney Vacation Club timeshare units. The 800-unit property, named [[Aulani]], opened in 2011 and joined the other resorts not associated with a theme park, such as [[Disney's Hilton Head Island Resort]] in South Carolina.<ref>{{cite news | title=Aloha, Disney | url=http://starbulletin.com/2007/10/04/news/story01.html | work=[[Honolulu Star-Bulletin]] | first=Allison | last=Schaefers | date=October 4, 2007 | accessdate=October 6, 2007}}</ref>\n\nWith the Walt Disney World Millennium Celebration starting on October 1, 2000, sanctioned Disney Pin Trading was started.<ref group=CDC>''[http://kpolsson.com/disnehis/disn1999jul.htm Orlando Attractions]''. Volume 2, Number 1. Page 32. December 2008. Accessed on April 18, 2016.</ref><ref group=CDC>''Eyes & Ears''. Volume 29, Number 38. Page 5.  September 23, 1999. Accessed on April 18, 2016.</ref> In 2001, the [[Themed Entertainment Association]] gave Disney Parks and Resorts the Thea Award for Breakthrough Innovation for the park's FastPass system.<ref group=CDC>Strodder, Chris. (2008). ''[http://kpolsson.com/disnehis/disn2001.htm The Disneyland Encyclopedia]''. Page 166. Accessed on April 19, 2016.</ref>\n\n===Walt Disney Parks and Resorts Worldwide===\nWalt Disney Parks and Resorts Worldwide, Inc. was incorporated on September 29, 2008, <ref name=sbz/> and took over the parks and resorts business segment. Disney Parks and Resorts reorganized in early 2009 which included layoffs in all units due to recession-induced falling attendance. 600 U.S. managers in January were buyout packages. Worldwide Operations was formed under President Al Weiss in 2009. Worldwide Operations would take over various back-office functions previously performed by both Disney World and Disneyland including training, procurement, menu planning, and merchandise development. While its Walt Disney Imagineering subsidiary combined its three development units.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Chmielewski |first1=Dawn C. |title=Disney combines theme park functions in prelude to job cuts |url= http://articles.latimes.com/2009/feb/19/business/fi-disney19 |accessdate=September 22, 2015 |work=Los Angeles Times |date=February 19, 2009}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2009, Disney received approval from the Chinese government to build a [[Shanghai Disneyland|Disneyland resort]] in [[Shanghai]]'s [[Pudong]] district.<ref>{{cite web|title=Shanghai Disneyland Project Gets Approval|url=http://www.bernama.com/bernama/v5/newsworld.php?id=452465|accessdate=June 21, 2012}}</ref> The resort opened on June 16, 2016.<ref name=open>{{cite web|last=Smith|first=Thomas|title=Opening Date Set for Shanghai Disney Resort, Disney\u2019s Newest World-Class Destination|url=http://disneyparks.disney.go.com/blog/2016/01/opening-date-set-for-shanghai-disney-resort-disneys-newest-world-classdestination/|publisher=DisneyParks Blog|accessdate=January 14, 2016|date=January 12, 2016}}</ref>\n\nCalifornia Adventure completed its overhaul in 2012 adding two new lands: [[Cars Land]] and [[Buena Vista Street]]. The overhaul also included a re-themed of several attractions plus a pair of classic dark rides.<ref name=lat3/> In July 2017, it was announced that [[Paradise Pier]] land would be replaced by Pixar Pier,<ref>{{cite news |last1=Pimentel |first1=Joseph |title=D23 Expo: Pixar Pier to replace Paradise Pier at Disney California Adventure |url=https://www.ocregister.com/2017/07/15/d23-expo-pixar-pier-to-replace-paradise-pier-at-disney-california-adventure/ |accessdate=March 20, 2020 |work=Orange County Register |date=July 16, 2017}}</ref> with four neighborhoods, and the remainder not in Pixar Pier would be replaced by Paradise Park. Pixar Pier opened on June 23, 2018.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Wisel |first1=Carlye |title=Pixar Pier Is Finally Open at Disney California Adventure \u2014 Here\u2019s What You Can Expect |url=https://www.travelandleisure.com/trip-ideas/disney-vacations/pixar-pier-opening-info-prices |accessdate=March 20, 2020 |work=Travel + Leisure |date=June 22, 2018 |language=EN}}</ref>\n\n[[Star Wars: Galaxy's Edge|''Star Wars'': Galaxy's Edge]], a {{convert|14|acre|ha|adj=on}} themed land for both [[Disneyland]] and [[Disney's Hollywood Studios]] announced at the [[D23 (Disney)|D23 Expo]] on August 15, 2015.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Pedicini|first1=Sandra |url=http://www.orlandosentinel.com/travel/attractions/the-daily-disney/os-star-wars-disney-hollywood-studios-20150815-story.html|title=Star Wars land coming to Disney's Hollywood Studios|date=August 15, 2015|work=Orlando Sentinel}}</ref> Construction began at both locations on April 14, 2016.<ref name=conbegin>{{cite news|last1=Parker|first1=Ryan|title=Disney Breaks Ground on 'Star Wars' Land in California and Florida|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/disneys-star-wars-land-photos-883997|accessdate=April 14, 2016|work=The Hollywood Reporter|date=April 14, 2016}}</ref> The lands at both parks opened in 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://disneyparks.disney.go.com/blog/2018/05/opening-season-just-announced-for-star-wars-galaxys-edge/|title=Opening Season Just Announced for Star Wars: Galaxy\u2019s Edge|work=Disney Parks Blog|publisher=The Walt Disney Company|accessdate=June 15, 2018|date=May 22, 2018|first=Scott|last=Trowbridge|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe New Fantasyland at Magic Kingdom opened on December 6, 2012. It is the biggest upgrade to the theme park since its opening in 1971.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Sekula|first1=Sarah|title=Disney brings more oomph with New Fantasyland|url=http://www.cnn.com/2012/12/05/travel/disney-new-fantasyland/|accessdate=April 20, 2016|work=CNN.com|publisher=Turner Broadcasting System, Inc.|date=December 10, 2012}}</ref> Announced along with its new Star Wars Land expansion at the D23 Expo on August 15, 2015, Hollywood Studios was slated to have a version of [[Toy Story Land]].<ref>{{cite news| last1=Kubersky|first1=Seth|title=Updated Toy Story Land concept art unveiled at Disney\u2019s Hollywood Studios|url=http://attractionsmagazine.com/updated-toy-story-land-concept-art-unveiled-disneys-hollywood-studios/ | accessdate=April 20, 2016|work=Attractions Magazine|publisher=Dream Together Media, LLC|date=April 4, 2016}}</ref>\n\nHolz became president of New Vacation Operations of Parks & Resorts<ref name=os4>{{cite news|url=http://articles.orlandosentinel.com/2009-02-14/news/dizcruise14_1_disney-cruise-line-disney-declined-mcalpin|title=Familiar face takes Disney Cruise Line helm: Karl Holz|last1=Garcia|first1=Jason|date=February 14, 2009|newspaper=Orlando Sentinel|accessdate=April 9, 2017}}</ref> reporting to [[Al Weiss]], president of worldwide operations for Walt Disney Parks and Resorts.<ref name=os5>{{cite news|last1=Garcia|first1=Jason|title=Disney executive changes: Head of Disney's theme parks makes executive changes|url=http://articles.orlandosentinel.com/2011-07-05/the-daily-disney/os-disney-executive-changes-20110705_1_al-weiss-crofton-resorts-chairman-tom-staggs|accessdate=April 13, 2017|work=Orlando Sentinel|date=July 5, 2011|language=en}}</ref> by April 2008.<ref>{{cite press release | author       = <!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> | title  = Philippe Gas to Assume Top Duties at Euro Disney  | url = http://corporate.disneylandparis.com/CORP/EN/Neutral/Images/uk-2008-04-10-nomination-philippe-gas.pdf | format = PDF | location     =Marne-la-Vall\u00e9e  | publisher    =Euro Disney S.C.A. | date = April 11, 2008 | access-date  = April 14, 2016}}</ref> In February 2009, Holz returned to the presidency of Disney Cruise Line in addition to his continuing as head of New Vacation Operations,<ref name=os4/> which was primarily [[Adventures by Disney]]. As an extension of the \"One Disney\" initiative and the resignation of Weiss, Disney Vacation Club was added to New Vacation Operations. While Holz and Meg Crofton joined Disney Parks and Resorts executive committee in July 2011. At that time, Crofton was transferred from Disney World president to president of operations in the U.S. and France, a new positions.<ref name=os5/>\n\nThe ''Disney Dream'' began service in January 2011 and [[Disney Cruise Line]] (DCL) announced the maiden voyage of the ''[[Disney Fantasy]]'' to be March 31, 2012. The Dream deployment allowed Disney Wonder to be permanently stationed at Port of Los Angeles for Mexican Riviera cruises,<ref>{{cite news|last1=Garcia|first1=Jason|title=Disney sets maiden voyage for new cruise ship|url=http://articles.orlandosentinel.com/2010-10-18/the-daily-disney/os-new-disney-cruise-ship-20101018_1_disney-magic-disney-cruise-line-disney-dream|accessdate=April 20, 2016|work=Orlando Sentinel|date=October 18, 2010}}</ref> but initial served in the short Alaska cruise season.<ref name=\"usat2\" /> Magic moved to New York for Canadian or Bahama cruises starting May 25, 2012.<ref group=CDC>[http://kpolsson.com/disnehis/disn2009.htm Cruise Travel]. July 2011, Volume 33, Number 1. Page 36.</ref> DCL's Magic was refitted in late 2013.<ref>{{cite news|title=Major Refit Planned for Disney Magic|url=https://www.cruiseindustrynews.com/cruise-news/9130-major-refit-planned-for-disney-magic.html|accessdate=April 20, 2016|work=Cruise Industry News|date=April 26, 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe first of three expansion theme lands at Hong Kong Disneyland, [[Toy Story Land]], opened on November 18, 2011.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Li|first1=Zoe|title=Toy Story Land hopes to save Hong Kong Disney|url=http://travel.cnn.com/hong-kong/visit/how-toy-story-land-hopes-save-hong-kong-disney-081206/|accessdate=April 20, 2016|work=CNN.com|publisher=Turner Broadcasting System, Inc.|date=November 21, 2011}}</ref> [[Grizzly Gulch]] opened at Hong Kong Disneyland on July 13, 2012.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Guinigundo|first1=Andy|title=Out of the Loop: Hong Kong Disneyland debuts Grizzly Gulchf|url=http://attractionsmagazine.com/out-of-the-loop-hong-kong-disneyland-debuts-grizzly-gulch/|accessdate=April 20, 2016|work=Attractions Magazine|publisher=Dream Together Media, LLC.|date=July 31, 2012}}</ref> The final land of this expansion, [[Mystic Point]], opened at Hong Kong Disneyland on May 17, 2013.<ref>{{cite news|title=Hong Kong Disneyland's Mystic Point opens May 17|url=http://www.ttgasia.com/article.php?article_id=20853|accessdate=April 20, 2016|work=TTG Asia|date=April 19, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160509033627/http://www.ttgasia.com/article.php?article_id=20853|archive-date=May 9, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nOn February 5, 2015, it was announced that [[Thomas O. Staggs|Tom Staggs]] had been promoted to Disney Company [[Chief operating officer]] but would continue as chairman of Parks and Resorts until his successor was named.<ref>{{cite web| last1=Littleton |first1=Cynthia |title=Disney Promotes Tom Staggs to No. 2 Post, Positioning Him as Iger\u2019s Successor |url=https://variety.com/2015/biz/news/disney-promotes-tom-staggs-to-no-2-post-positioning-him-as-igers-successor-1201423601/|website=Variety.com|publisher=Variety Magazine|accessdate=February 5, 2015}}</ref> On February 23, 2015, [[Bob Chapek|Robert Chapek]] was named chairman of Walt Disney Parks and Resorts effective that day.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Barnes|first1=Brooks|title=Disney Names Robert Chapek Chairman for Theme Parks|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/02/24/business/media/disney-names-robert-chapek-chairman-for-theme-parks.html?_r=0|accessdate=February 26, 2015|work=New York Times|date=February 23, 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn April 29, 2015, The Walt Disney Company, through the subsidiary, Carousel Holdings Eat LLC, has purchased Carousel Inn & Suites hotel in Anaheim, from Good Hope International for $32 million. The purchase was considered a strategic purchase; the hotel would not be considered a part of the Disneyland hotel portfolio and would operate independently.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Pimentel|first1=Joseph|title=Disney purchases Carousel Inn for $32 million |url=http://www.ocregister.com/articles/disney-659941-hotel-inn.html|website=OCRegister.com|publisher=The Orange County Register|date=April 29, 2015}}</ref> Disney indicted in August 2016, that the company would be closing the Carousel Inn in October 2016 in preparation for razing it as part of plans to construct a new parking structure, transit plaza and pedestrian bridge over Harbor Boulevard.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Pimentel|first1=Joseph|title=Q&amp;A Disneyland's massive parking project|url=http://www.ocregister.com/articles/disney-725945-harbor-bridge.html|website=OCRegister.com|publisher=The Orange County Register|date=August 16, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn February 10, 2017, Disney revealed a deal to purchase [[Kingdom Holding]] Co.'s shares of [[Euro Disney S.C.A.]] as the first step in purchasing the remaining shares held by others. Disney has offered about $2.12 a share, a 67% premium over the Euronext Paris Stock Exchange value as of February 9. The company expects the buyout and delisting to be finished by June. Plans are for the company to invest another $1.4 billion into Disneyland Paris after the buyout to counteract the recent [[November 2015 Paris attacks|Paris terrorist attack]], which hurt a previous 2014 park hotel investment. If this buyout is successful, it would make the resort the only resort 100% owned and operated by Disney outside of the United States of America.<ref name=\"vty\">{{cite news|last1=Littleton|first1=Cynthia|title=Disney Seeks Full Ownership of Disneyland Paris|url=https://variety.com/2017/biz/news/disneyland-paris-disney-buyout-terrorist-attack-1201984089/|accessdate=February 16, 2017|work=Variety|date=February 10, 2017}}</ref> On June 13, 2017, The Walt Disney Company reached the 95% threshold required for a mandatory takeover according to French law, owning 97.08% of Euro Disney S.C.A., paving the way for The Walt Disney Company to become the sole owner and operator of Disneyland Paris.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.marketwatch.com/story/final-results-of-the-simplified-public-tender-offer-on-euro-disney-sca-the-walt-disney-company-to-implement-a-mandatory-buy-out-and-delisting-2017-06-13-102035936|title=Final results of the simplified public tender offer on Euro Disney S.C.A. The Walt Disney Company to implement a mandatory buy-out and delisting|work=MarketWatch|access-date=2017-06-13|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n===Disney Parks, Experiences and Products===\nAs part of [[The Walt Disney Company]]\u2019s March 2018 strategic reorganization, Disney Consumer Products, and Interactive Media was merged into the Walt Disney Parks and Resorts segment and renamed Walt Disney Parks, Experiences and Products. Parks and Resorts Chairman Bob Chapek was named chairman of this new segment, who also previously served as head of Disney Consumer Products.<ref name=cnbc>{{cite news|last1=Wang|first1=Christine|title=Disney announces strategic reorganization, effective immediately|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2018/03/14/disney-announces-strategic-reorganization-effective-immediately.html|accessdate=March 14, 2018|work=CNBC|date=March 14, 2018}}</ref> At the time, the Consumer Products chairman position was vacant, as its former holder, James Pitaro, had been recently appointed as the new head of [[ESPN Inc.|ESPN]] and co-chair of [[Disney Media Networks]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Barnes|first1=Brooks|title=Disney Reorganization Anticipates 21st Century Fox Assets|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/03/14/business/media/walt-disney-21st-century-fox.html|accessdate=March 14, 2018|work=The New York Times|date=March 14, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2018, a Disney Parks West regional division was formed with Disneyland Resort in California, Walt Disney World in Florida, and Disneyland Paris under Catherine Powell, outgoing Disneyland Paris president. This mirrors the Disney Parks East regional division consisting of Shanghai Disney Resort, Hong Kong Disneyland and Walt Disney Attractions Japan and headed by Michael Colglazier. Imagineering was expected to take on the development of merchandise, games, publishing, and apps. Paul Gainer moved up from Disney Retail head to head up the new Global Product Management and Distribution unit, which includes Disney Retail, Global Licensing, and digital guest experience.<ref>{{cite news |title=Imagineering Sees Big Growth as \"Parks, Experiences, and Consumer Products\" Announces Structure |url=https://www.laughingplace.com/w/news/2018/03/21/imagineering-sees-big-growth-parks-experiences-consumer-products-announces-structure/ |accessdate=June 18, 2018 |work=LaughingPlace.com |date=March 21, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Catherine Powell steps into new Disney role |url=http://www.parkworld-online.com/catherine-powell-steps-into-new-disney-role/ |accessdate=June 18, 2018 |work=Park World |date=March 29, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Disney Unveils Solo: A Star Wars Story Merch |url=https://www.licenseglobal.com/movies/disney-unveils-solo-star-wars-story-merch |accessdate=December 13, 2018 |work=License Global |publisher=UBM Americas |date=April 9, 2018 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nKen Potrock was promoted from Senior Vice President and General Manager of Disney Vacation Club to President of Consumer Products in May 2018.<ref>{{cite web |title=Ken Potrock profile |url=https://dpecp.disney.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/leadership_ken_potrock_121118.pdf |website=dpecp.disney.com |publisher=The Walt Disney Company |accessdate=13 December 2018 |format=PDF}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=The Walt Disney Company appoints new Head of Consumer Products Commercialization |url=https://www.retailnews.asia/the-walt-disney-company-appoints-new-head-of-consumer-products-commercialization/ |accessdate=December 13, 2018 |work=Retail News Asia |publisher=Mojju |date=November 27, 2018}}</ref> New Vacation Operations and Disney Cruise Line division was renamed Disney Signature Experiences along with a new president, Jeff Vahle, for the division in April 2018.<ref name=\"os6\">{{cite news|last1=Tribou|first1=Richard|title=New president named for Disney Cruise Line, Vacation Club and more|url=http://www.orlandosentinel.com/travel/attractions/the-daily-disney/os-disney-cruise-line-president-jeff-vahle-20180420-story.html|accessdate=April 30, 2018|work=Orlando Sentinel|date=April 20, 2018}}</ref> On January 1, 2019, Walt Disney Parks, Experiences and Consumer Products changed its name to Disney Parks, Experiences and Products.<ref>{{cite web |series=Detail by Entity Name |url=http://search.sunbiz.org/Inquiry/CorporationSearch/ConvertTiffToPDF?storagePath=COR%5C2019%5C0211%5C24080356.Tif&documentNumber=F09000001204 |title=Certificate of Amendment of the Articles of Incorporation of Disney Parks, Experiences and Consumer Products |website=Sunbiz.org |publisher=State of Florida |accessdate=October 10, 2018 |language=en}}</ref> Disney Cruise Line purchase in early March 2019 another Bahamas destination, Lighthouse Point property on the island of Eleuthera.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Tribou |first1=Richard |title=Disney Cruise Line completes land purchase, enters agreement for second Bahamas destination |url=https://www.orlandosentinel.com/travel/attractions/the-daily-disney/os-ae-disney-cruise-line-lighthouse-point-bahamas-update-20190311-story.html |accessdate=March 12, 2019 |work=Orlando Sentinel |date=March 11, 2019}}</ref> In July 2019, Disney denied reports of plans to launch its own airline with the purchase of small regional airlines in the United States.<ref name=\"Stuff\">{{cite news |title=Disney denies any plans to launch airline in the US |url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/travel/news/114417532/disney-to-launch-airline-in-the-us-reports |accessdate=July 31, 2019 |work=Stuff |date=July 22, 2019 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Elliott |first1=Annabel Fenwick |title=Disney denies rumours of US airline launch |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/travel/news/disney-to-launch-us-airline-cabin-crew-in-costume/ |accessdate=July 31, 2019 |work=The Telegraph |date=July 22, 2019}}</ref>\n\nPowell supervised the two Star Wars-themed land, [[Star Wars: Galaxy's Edge]], openings in May at Disneyland and August 2019 in Disney's Hollywood Studios. However, initial numbers showed an attendance dropped instead of the boost such an opening should have generated. In late September, Powell left the company with the Parks West regional division being dissolved, thus having those resorts' executives directly report to chairman Chapek.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Palmeri |first1=Christopher |title=Disney\u2019s U.S. Parks Chief Leaves After 15 Years With Company |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-09-23/disney-s-u-s-parks-chief-leaves-after-15-years-with-company |accessdate=September 25, 2019 |work=Bloomberg.com |date=September 23, 2019}}</ref> He denied that Powell was let go because of the low attendance issue from Galaxy's Edge, but instead, Powell's position was a temporary one to allow Chapek to focus on the [[Acquisition of 21st Century Fox by Disney|acquisition of 21st Century Fox]].<ref name=\"cnbcLeadership\">{{cite news|last1=Whitten|first1=Sarah|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/09/25/disney-names-new-leadership-for-disneyland-and-walt-disney-world.html|title=Disney names new leadership for Disneyland and Walt Disney World|date=September 25, 2019|work=CNBC|accessdate=September 30, 2019|language=en}}</ref>\n\nPowell's departure from Disney was soon followed by a domino of executive appointments, as announced on September 26, 2019.<ref name=\"cnbcLeadership\"/> George Kalogridis, then-president of the Walt Disney World Resort, was promoted as the president of segment development and enrichment. Kalogridis is replaced by Josh D'Amaro, then-president of the Disneyland Resort, as president of the Walt Disney World Resort. In turn, D'Amaro was replaced by Rebecca Campbell as president of the Disneyland Resort. Campbell transferred from the [[Walt Disney Direct-to-Consumer & International]] segment where she served as the president of Europe, the Middle East, and Africa. Both D'Amaro and Campbell assumed these roles in November 2019. In addition, Michael Colglazier is also promoted as the president and managing director of Disney Parks International and will oversee Disneyland Paris as well as those under the Parks East regional division.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.apnews.com/e70a439b2f2046a78aebdd2c72e87d67|title=Shake-up in the leadership of Disney theme park resorts|date=September 25, 2019|work=AP News|accessdate=September 30, 2019}}</ref> In February 2020, Chapek was promoted from Chairman of this segment to chief executive officer of the Walt Disney Company under executive chairman Bob Iger.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Littleton |first1=Cynthia |title=Bob Chapek to Succeed Bob Iger as Disney CEO |url=https://variety.com/2020/biz/news/bob-chapek-bob-iger-disney-ceo-succeed-1203515498/ |accessdate=February 26, 2020 |work=Variety |date=February 25, 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nWith the closure of all Disney parks in 2020 during the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|coronavirus pandemic]], Disney donated 150,000 rain ponchos usually sold at the parks to [[MedShare]], to be distributed in hospitals. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.parents.com/syndication/disney-parks-donates-150000-rain-ponchos-to-hospitals-and-medical-professionals/|title=Disney Parks Donates 150,000 Rain Ponchos to Hospitals and Medical Professionals|website=Parents|language=EN|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n\n==Disney resorts==\n{{See also| List of Disney theme park attractions}}\n{{location map+|Earth\n|float=center\n|width=775\n|caption=Locations of Disney resorts \u2014 [[File:Red pog.svg|8px]] International [[File:Blue pog.svg|8px]] US (direct reports)\n|places=\n{{Location map~|Earth|position=top|lat=31.144|long=121.657|label='''[[Shanghai Disney Resort]]''' |mark=Red pog.svg\n}}\n{{Location map~|Earth|position=bottom|lat=22.313333|long=114.043333|label='''[[Hong Kong Disneyland Resort]]''' |mark=Red pog.svg\n}}\n{{Location map~|Earth|position=right|lat=48.868719|long=2.7818|label='''[[Disneyland Paris]]''' |mark=Red pog.svg\n}}\n{{Location map~|Earth|position=right|lat=35.629722|long=139.882778|label='''[[Tokyo Disney Resort]]''' |mark=Red pog.svg\n}}\n{{Location map~|Earth|position=right|lat=28.418611|long=-81.581111|label='''[[Walt Disney World]]''' |mark=blue pog.svg\n}}\n{{Location map~|Earth|position=left|lat=33.8091|long=-117.919|label='''[[Disneyland Resort]]''' |mark=blue pog.svg\n}}\n}}\n===Disneyland Resort===\n{{Main|Disneyland Resort}}\n[[Disneyland]] was founded as a single park by [[Walt Disney]] and opened on July 17, 1955, in [[Anaheim, California]]. [[Disneyland Hotel (California)|Disneyland Hotel]] opened to the public on October 5, 1955. In 2001, the site expanded significantly and was renamed the Disneyland Resort with the opening of [[Disney California Adventure|Disney California Adventure Park]] on February 8, 2001, [[Disney's Grand Californian Hotel & Spa]] on January 2, 2001, [[Disney's Paradise Pier Hotel]] on December 15, 2000, and [[Downtown Disney (Disneyland Resort)|Downtown Disney]] on January 12, 2001. Disneyland was re-branded Disneyland Park to distinguish it from the larger resort complex. The resort focuses on [[Mickey Mouse]] and other Disney characters and occupies {{convert|500|acre|km2}}.\n\n===Walt Disney World===\n{{Main|Walt Disney World}}\nThe Walt Disney World resort opened October 1, 1971, in [[Lake Buena Vista, Florida]], with the [[Magic Kingdom]] theme park and three resort hotels. It expanded with the opening of [[Epcot]] in 1982, Disney-MGM Studios (now [[Disney's Hollywood Studios]]) and [[Disney's Typhoon Lagoon]] in 1989, [[Disney's Blizzard Beach]] in 1995, [[Disney's Animal Kingdom]] in 1998, [[Disney Springs]] retail, dining, and entertainment complex, eight golf courses, and 18 new resort hotels. The resort is the largest (by area) and most-visited vacation resort in the world, with four theme parks, two water parks, a shopping, dining, and entertainment complex, 21 resort hotels, eight golf courses, and several additional recreational activities, and covers 27,258 acres.\n\nOther venues:\n* [[ESPN Wide World of Sports Complex]]\n\n===Tokyo Disney Resort===\n{{Main|Tokyo Disney Resort}}\n'''Tokyo Disney Resort''', in [[Urayasu, Chiba]], Japan, opened April 15, 1983, as [[Tokyo Disneyland]]. On September 4, 2001, the resort expanded with [[Tokyo DisneySea]]. There are several resort hotels on-site, but only three are owned by the resort, which boasts the largest parking structure in the world. Designed by [[Walt Disney Imagineering]], the resort is fully owned and operated by [[The Oriental Land Company]] and licensed by The Walt Disney Company. The Walt Disney Attractions Japan team at The Walt Disney Company communicates with the Oriental Land Company over all aspects of the resort and assigns Imagineers to it. Its properties, below, are divided into parks, shopping centers, and lodging.\n\n*Shopping, dining, and entertainment complex: [[Ikspiari]]\n\n{{-}}\n\n===Disneyland Paris===\n{{Main|Disneyland Paris}}\n'''Disneyland Paris''', Disney's second international resort complex, and the largest Disney resort outside the United States, opened on April 12, 1992, as '''Euro Disney Resort'''. Located in [[Marne-la-Vall\u00e9e]] in the suburbs of Paris, France, it features two theme parks, a golf course, an entertainment complex, and seven Disney resort hotels. It is the only resort outside the United States fully owned and operated by [[The Walt Disney Company]].<ref name=\"vty\" /> Its properties, listed below, occupy {{convert|4940|acre|km2}} and are divided into parks and shopping centers.\n\n===Hong Kong Disneyland Resort===\n{{Main|Hong Kong Disneyland Resort}}\n'''Hong Kong Disneyland Resort''', Disney's fifth resort and its second in Asia, opened September 12, 2005. The resort is located in [[Penny's Bay]], [[Lantau Island]], Hong Kong. The resort consists of [[Hong Kong Disneyland]] theme park, [[Inspiration Lake Recreation Centre]], and three hotels, with land reserved for future expansion. It is owned and operated by [[Hong Kong International Theme Parks]], an incorporated company jointly owned by [[The Walt Disney Company]] and the [[Government of Hong Kong]]. The first phase of Hong Kong Disneyland Resort occupies {{convert|320|acre|km2}}.\n\n===Shanghai Disney Resort===\n{{Main|Shanghai Disney Resort}}\nIn November 2009, Disney received approval from the central government of China to build a Disney theme park, [[Shanghai Disneyland Park]], in [[Shanghai]]'s [[Pudong]] district. \"China is one of the most dynamic, exciting and important countries in the world and this approval marks a very significant milestone for Walt Disney Co in mainland China,\" said Robert Iger, president and CEO of Disney.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.reuters.com/article/rbssTechMediaTelecomNews/idUSN0352328120091104 | work=Reuters | title=UPDATE 4-Disney takes China stride as Shanghai park gets nod | date=November 4, 2009}}</ref> The resort opened on June 16, 2016.<ref name=open/> A groundbreaking ceremony took place on April 7, 2011.<ref name=\"skydisneychina\">{{cite news| url=http://news.sky.com/skynews/Home/Business/Disneyland-China-Disney-Agrees-A-Deal-To-Open-Amusement-Park-In-Shanghai/Article/201011115795782?f=rss | work=Sky News | title=Disney To Bring Magic Kingdom To Shanghai | date=November 5, 2010 | accessdate=November 5, 2010}}\n</ref>\n*Shopping, dining, and entertainment complex: [[Disneytown]]\n\n==Training==\nEach new employee (\"cast member\") at a Disney theme park is trained at a Disney University, founded by Walt Disney in 1955. Before training specific to the work they will perform, each employee attends the \"Disney Traditions\" course where they learn about the philosophies and history of Disney's guest services.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Yearout|first1=Steve|last2=Weil|first2=Gerry Miles, with Richard Koonce ; foreword by Audrey|title=Growing leaders : a leader-builder handbook for HRD and training professionals, business executives and managers, executive coaches|date=2001|publisher=ASTD|location=Alexandria, VA|isbn=1562862898|page=[https://archive.org/details/growingleadersle0000year/page/193 193]|url=https://archive.org/details/growingleadersle0000year/page/193}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Lipp|first1=Doug|title=Disney U : how Disney University develops the world's most engaged, loyal, and customer-centric employees|date=2013|publisher=McGraw-Hill|location=New York|isbn=0071808078}}</ref>\n\n==Abandoned and misreported concepts==\n{{Main| List of Disney attractions that were never built}}\nDisney had plans to build [[Walt Disney's Riverfront Square]] in [[St. Louis]], but canceled the project in July 1965.\n\nIn the 1960s, Disney initiated a plan for a ski resort at [[Mineral King]] in California. Opposition from environmental groups led by the [[Sierra Club]] led to a temporary court injunction in 1969 and legal battles through the 1970s. The project's planning and scale changed multiple times, and in 1978, Mineral King was annexed into [[Sequoia National Park]], ending any possibility of developing a resort there.<ref name=\"ski\">{{cite book|title=Challenge of the Big Trees|last=Dilsaver|first=L.M.|author2=Tweed, W.C. |chapter=New Directions and a Second Century (1972\u20131990)|year=1990|publisher=Sequoia Natural History Association |chapterurl= http://www.nps.gov/history/history/online_books/dilsaver-tweed/chap9c.htm}}</ref>\n\nDisney had plans to build a park named [[Disney's America]] in [[Haymarket, Virginia]], but abandoned the idea in 1994. On September 28, 1994, [[Michael Eisner]] announced Disney was canceling its plans after a bruising national media fight with Protect Historic America, and aggressive local opposition in Virginia from Protect Prince William and other citizen groups.\n\nDisney had plans to build a smaller Disneyland-style theme park in Sydney, Australia, between 2007 and 2008, with the proposed name \"Disney Wharf at Sydney Harbour\", but the concept was abandoned due to mixed responses in the [[Government of New South Wales|New South Wales Government]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.smh.com.au/nsw/walt-disney-company-proposed-a-disney-resort-in-sydney-20140111-30nfk.html|title=Walt Disney Company proposed a Disney Resort in Sydney|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|accessdate=October 4, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn early January 2011, conflicting reports emerged regarding Disney's involvement in a proposed entertainment complex in Haifa, Israel, whose plans include a small (30,000 square meter) amusement park scheduled to open in 2013. The project will be partially funded by [[Shamrock Holdings]], a Disney-affiliated investment firm. In the wake of reports from Israeli business newspaper, ''[[Globes]]'' and industry newswire ''Amusement Management'' that Disney itself would be involved in the project's development, a spokesperson for Walt Disney Parks and Resorts clarified to ''[[Fast Company (magazine)|Fast Company]]'' that Disney did not have any plans to be involved in the building of the park.<ref>Ungerleider, Neal. [http://www.fastcompany.com/1714452/disney-to-open-theme-park-in-israel \"Disney to Open Theme Park in Israel?\"] ''Fast Company''. January 5, 2011.</ref>\n\n==Disney intellectual properties outside Disney parks==\nDue to its acquisitions of [[Marvel Entertainment]] in 2009, [[Lucasfilm]] in 2012 and [[20th Century Studios ]] in 2019, some Disney-owned franchises are represented in its competitors' parks.\n\n===[[Marvel Entertainment]]===\n[[Marvel Super Hero Island]], a themed land featuring characters and settings from [[Marvel Comics]], has operated at [[Universal Orlando]] Resort's [[Islands of Adventure]] park since 1999, as well as the Islands of Adventure, cloned ride ''[[The Amazing Adventures of Spider-Man]]'' at [[Universal Studios Japan]] since 2004. Under Marvel's 1994 agreement with [[Universal Parks & Resorts]] in regional terms, none of the Marvel characters and other persons related to such characters (e.g., side characters, team members, and the villains associated with the [[Avengers (comics)|Avengers]], [[Fantastic Four]], [[X-Men]], [[Spider-Man]], etc.) connected with Islands of Adventure and Universal Studios Japan can be used at Walt Disney World and Tokyo Disney Resort.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Munarriz|first1=Rick|title=Disney is Taking Too Long to Add Marvel to Disneyland and Disney World|url=http://www.fool.com/investing/general/2015/10/18/disney-is-taking-too-long-to-add-marvel-to-disney.aspx|website=The Motley Fool|accessdate=January 17, 2016}}</ref> The [[Disneyland Resort]], Walt Disney World Resort, and Tokyo Disney Resort also cannot use the Marvel brand name as part of an attraction or marketing and the Marvel-themed [[simulator ride]].<ref name=\"Marvel Contract\">{{cite web|url=https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1262449/000119312510008732/dex1057.htm|title=Marvel Agreement between MCA Inc. and Marvel Entertainment Group|publisher=[[U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission]]|website=sec.gov}}</ref> This clause has allowed Walt Disney World to have meet-and-greets with Marvel characters not associated with the ones present at Islands of Adventure, such as [[Star-Lord]] and [[Gamora]] from ''[[Guardians of the Galaxy (film)|Guardians of the Galaxy]],''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.insidethemagic.net/2014/08/guardians-of-the-galaxy-theme-park-characters-appear-for-first-time-as-walt-disney-world-welcomes-marvel/|title=Guardians of the Galaxy theme park characters appear for the first time as Walt Disney World welcomes Marvel|work=Inside the Magic}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://disneyparks.disney.go.com/blog/2014/07/exclusive-guardians-of-the-galaxy-sneak-peek-debuts-july-4-at-disney-parks/|title=Exclusive \u2018Guardians of the Galaxy\u2019 Sneak Peek Debuts July 4 at Disney Parks|work=Disney Parks Blog}}</ref> and [[Doctor Strange]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.themeparkinsider.com/flume/201611/5319/|title=Walt Disney World news update: Doctor Strange, new castle show debut|last=Niles|first=Robert|date=November 5, 2016|website=Theme Park Insider|access-date=August 22, 2019}}</ref> Hong Kong Disneyland, Shanghai Disneyland, and Disneyland Paris either have or planned to incorporate meet and greets as well as attractions relating to the Marvel characters, as well as using the Marvel name and the Marvel simulator ride.\n\n[[IMG Worlds of Adventure]] in [[Dubai]] has a Marvel-themed section.<ref>https://www.imgworlds.com/language/en/#</ref>\n\n===''[[Star Wars]]''===\nA ''[[Star Wars]]''-themed section of [[Legoland California]]'s [[Legoland California#Miniland USA|Miniland USA]] opened in 2011, with a similar version opening at [[Legoland Florida]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://florida.legoland.com/map-explore/land-views/miniland/attractions/lego-star-wars/|title=LEGO\u00ae STAR WARS\u2122|publisher=}}</ref> in November 2012, just weeks before Disney's acquisition of Lucasfilm and the ''Star Wars'' franchise. However, the ''Star Wars''-themed sections at Miniland USA, Legoland Florida, and other Legoland areas will close at the start of 2020 before the 2020 theme park season due to the expiration of their contract with [[Lucasfilm]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.orlandoweekly.com/Blogs/archives/2019/12/15/as-disney-opens-its-new-star-wars-land-in-orlando-another-local-theme-park-says-goodbye|title=As Disney opens its new Star Wars land in Orlando, another local theme park says goodbye|newspaper=Orlando Weekly |access-date=December 15, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===[[20th Century Studios]]===\nFollowing Disney's [[Acquisition of 21st Century Fox by Disney|acquisition of 21st Century Fox]] in March 2019, ''[[The Simpsons (franchise)|The Simpsons]]'' became the intellectual property of Disney. Like Marvel before it, ''The Simpsons'' is represented in Universal parks, with [[The Simpsons Ride]] having operated at [[Universal Studios Hollywood]] and [[Universal Studios Florida]] since 2008, with accompanying themed areas based on the show's setting of [[Springfield (The Simpsons)|Springfield]].\n\nThe Fox acquisition also made Disney responsible for the future of [[Malaysia]]'s under-construction [[20th Century Fox World (Malaysia)|20th Century Fox World]] theme park. The park's owner, [[Genting Group]], filed suit against The Walt Disney Company and 21st Century Fox in November 2018, accusing Fox of trying to back out of the deal for licensing the theme park. In the suit, Genting Malaysia alleges that Fox has taken steps to cancel the contract. The suit also names Disney as a defendant, contending that Disney executives, following the company's [[Acquisition of 21st Century Fox by Disney|then-pending acquisition of Fox]], were \"calling the shots\" on the project and that they were opposed to the park because they would have \"no control\" over its operations and that it would be adjacent to a casino, which would go against Disney's \"family-friendly\" image.<ref name=\"Disney, Fox sued in U.S. for $1 billion over Malaysia theme park\">{{cite web |title=Disney, Fox sued in U.S. for $1 billion over Malaysia theme park |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-fox-disney-genting-malaysia/disney-fox-sued-in-us-for-1-billion-over-malaysia-theme-park-idUSKCN1NV2NP |website=Reuters |publisher=Reuters |accessdate=November 27, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181127151956/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-fox-disney-genting-malaysia/disney-fox-sued-in-us-for-1-billion-over-malaysia-theme-park-idUSKCN1NV2NP |archive-date=27 November 2018 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Fox, in turn, referred to the suit as \"without merit\", stating that their reasons for withdrawing from the deal were due to Genting consistently not meeting \"agreed-upon deadlines for several years\" and that Genting's attempts to blame Disney for Fox's default were \"made up\".<ref name=\"Deadline\">{{cite news|url=https://deadline.com/2018/11/disney-fox-lawsuit-kuala-lumpur-theme-park-deal-off-1202509020/|title=Disney & Fox Accused In $1.75B Suit Of Taking Theme Park Developer For A Ride|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=November 26, 2018|accessdate=November 27, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181128012047/https://deadline.com/2018/11/disney-fox-lawsuit-kuala-lumpur-theme-park-deal-off-1202509020/|archive-date=28 November 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In July 2019, it was announced that Fox and Genting had settled their lawsuits. As part of the deal, Genting would be given \"a license to use certain Fox intellectual properties\" and that non-Fox intellectual property would make up the rest of the attractions in the park. The outdoor park would also no longer be referred to as 20th Century Fox World, but instead would be given a new name at an unspecified time.<ref name=\"Legal Fight Over Fox Theme Park In Malaysia Ends In Settlement\">{{cite web |title=Legal Fight Over Fox Theme Park In Malaysia Ends In Settlement |url=https://deadline.com/2019/07/fox-world-malaysia-theme-park-settlement-legal-1202654605/ |website=Deadline.com |publisher=Deadline Hollywood |accessdate=July 26, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Adaptations==\nWhile Disney Parks generally adapt movies into rides, some Disney theme park attractions have been adapted into or have served inspiration for films,<ref>{{cite news|last1=Verrier|first1=Richard|title=Movies Imitate Disney's Parks|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2002/may/15/business/fi-disney15|accessdate=April 1, 2017|work=Los Angeles Times|date=May 15, 2002}}</ref> <!-- notability source & need to mine for more info --> books,<ref name=kr/> comic books,<ref name=spi/> and [[television pilot]]s. Disney entered the television field with a network TV show named after [[Walt Disney anthology television series|Disneyland]] (which was then its only park, and was being built at the time), in order to fund the park. In this series, some episodes featured the park or a park attraction.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Griffin|first1=Sean|title=Encyclopedia of Television|publisher=The Museum of Broadcast Communications|url=http://www.museum.tv/eotv/waltdisneyp.htm|accessdate=April 1, 2017|chapter=Walt Disney Programs|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170817202754/http://www.museum.tv/eotv/waltdisneyp.htm|archive-date=August 17, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> The Walt Disney Company pioneered and is the only film company and theme park company to have converted theme park attractions to film productions. However, lackluster results were achieved for most of these films except for the [[Pirates of the Caribbean (film series)|''Pirates of the Caribbean'']] series.<ref name=\"ew\">{{cite news|last1=Bacle|first1=Ariana |title=Theme park ride-based movies: Will 'Small World' follow the trend?|url=http://ew.com/article/2014/04/23/disney-theme-park-movies-small-world/ |accessdate= March 28, 2017 |work=Entertainment Weekly |date=April 23, 2014}}</ref> [[Walt Disney Pictures]] produced two ''Pirates of the Caribbean'' sequels in 2006 and 2011 that made over a billion-dollar at the box office.<ref name=dl0>{{cite news|url=http://deadline.com/2017/03/beauty-and-the-beast-sean-bailey-disney-emma-watson-1202047710/ |title=Sean Bailey On How Disney\u2019s Live-Action Division Found Its \u2018Beauty And The Beast\u2019 Mojo |date=March 21, 2017 |work=Deadline |publisher=Penske Business Media, LLC |last1=Jr|first1=Mike Fleming|accessdate=March 23, 2017}}</ref>\n\nAt first, Disney had merely dabbled with this type of film. [[Walt Disney Television#Disney Telefilms|Disney Telefilms]] made the first movie-based-on-ride, [[Tower of Terror (1997 film)|Tower of Terror]], for the [[Walt Disney anthology television series|Wonderful World of Disney]] anthology television series in 1997.<ref>{{cite news|title=Disney Sets ABC Pix|url=https://variety.com/1997/scene/vpage/disney-sets-abc-pix-1117342089/|accessdate=December 30, 2015|work=Variety|date=May 1, 1997}}</ref> In 2000, [[Touchstone Pictures]] made ''[[Mission to Mars]]'' based on the [[Mission to Mars (attraction)|closed ride of the same name]].<ref name=\"ew\"/><ref>{{cite news|last1=Schwarzbaum|first1=Lisa|title=Mission to Mars|url=http://ew.com/article/2000/03/17/mission-mars-4/|accessdate=March 28, 2017|work=Entertainment Weekly|date=March 17, 2000}}</ref>\n\n[[Walt Disney Pictures]] took the [[Country Bear Jamboree]] attraction and made it into ''[[The Country Bears]]'' in 2002. In 2003, Walt Disney Pictures issued two ride-based films in ''[[Pirates of the Caribbean: The Curse of the Black Pearl]]'' and ''[[The Haunted Mansion (film)|The Haunted Mansion]]''. ''Pirates of the Caribbean'' launched [[Pirates of the Caribbean (film series)|a film series and a franchise]].<ref name=\"ew\"/> After four Pirates sequels, the franchise took in more than $5.4 billion worldwide.<ref>{{cite news|last1=McNary |first1=Dave |last2=Graser |first2=Marc |url=https://variety.com/2013/biz/news/end-of-an-era-disney-and-jerry-bruckheimer-part-ways-1200652789/ |title=End of an Era: Disney and Jerry Bruckheimer Part Ways |date=September 19, 2013  |work=Variety |publisher= |accessdate=March 28, 2017}}</ref>\n\n[[Disney Publishing Worldwide]] started mining Disney Parks with its [[The Kingdom Keepers]] series. The first novel of the series, ''Disney after Dark'', was released in 2005.<ref name=kr>{{cite magazine|title=The Kingdom Keepers (review)|url=https://www.kirkusreviews.com/book-reviews/ridley-pearson/the-kingdom-keepers/|magazine=Kirkus Reviews|date=August 15, 2005|accessdate=April 9, 2014}}</ref> A five-book series was laid out by Pearson, but was extended to seven with the first book's success.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Hill|first1=Jim|title=Keeping up with Disney's \"Kingdom Keepers\" : Ridley Pearson talks about all the research that goes into this popular book series|url=http://jimhillmedia.com/editor_in_chief1/b/jim_hill/archive/2011/04/03/keeping-up-with-disney-s-quot-kingdom-keepers-quot-ridley-pearson-talks-about-all-the-research-he-does-for-this-popular-book-series.aspx|accessdate=May 1, 2017|work=jimhillmedia.com|date=April 3, 2011|language=en}}</ref>\n\nWith the Pirates of the Caribbean franchise as Disney Pictures' top franchise,<ref name=\"dl0\"/> the company had been looking for additional projects in this category for a decade.<ref name=ew0>{{cite news|last=Breznican|first=Anthony|title=Disney's mysterious '1952' movie has a new name ... 'Tomorrowland' |url=http://insidemovies.ew.com/2013/01/28/disneys-1952-is-tomorrowland/|accessdate=January 29, 2013|newspaper=Entertainment Weekly|date=January 28, 2013}}</ref> Disney Pictures took another push at additional adaptations in the 2010s.<ref name=ew0/> By November 2010, [[Jon Favreau]] had been tapped to develop the [[Magic Kingdom#Planned film|Magic Kingdom]] park into a \"Night at the Museum\" like film, with Strike Entertainment signed on to produce it<ref>{{cite news |last1=Graser |first1=Marc. |title=Jon Favreau enters Disney's 'Magic Kingdom |url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1118027299 |accessdate=September 11, 2018 |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |date=November 10, 2010 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5v00gTWGB?url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1118027299 |archive-date=December 15, 2010}}</ref> after a script by Ronald D. Moore was turned down.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Schaefer|first1=Sandy|title=Jon Favreau Says Magic Kingdom Movie Still in Development|url=http://screenrant.com/jon-favreau-magic-kingdom-movie-disney/|accessdate=April 26, 2017|work=Screen Rant|date=April 4, 2016}}</ref> Another Haunted Mansion film was in the works with [[Guillermo del Toro]] as of August 2012.<ref name=ew0/> [[Mr. Toad's Wild Ride]] ride film was in the works at Disney Pictures by January 2013.<ref>{{cite news|last=Tully|first=Sarah|title=Is 'Tomorrowland' movie tied to Disneyland area?|url=http://www.ocregister.com/news/movie-409540-disney-tomorrowland.html|accessdate=January 29, 2013|newspaper=Orange County Register|date=January 28, 2013}}</ref> [[Tomorrowland (film)|Tomorrowland]], first to be loosely based on a theme park area,<ref>{{cite news|first=Eliana |last=Kirshenblat |url=http://screenrant.com/disney-tower-terror-movie-writer/ |title=Disney\u2019s New Tower of Terror Movie Seeking a Writer |publisher=Screenrant.com |date=October 23, 2015 |accessdate=March 29, 2017}}</ref> was announced in January 2013 for a December 2014 release.<ref name=ew0/> Also in 2013, [[American Broadcasting Company]] had ordered a pilot based on [[Big Thunder Mountain Railroad]].<ref name=dl1>{{cite news|last1= |first1= |url=http://deadline.com/2015/10/tower-of-terror-movie-disney-theme-park-ride-john-august-1201592331/ |title=\u2018Tower Of Terror\u2019 Getting Movie Treatment; Venerable Disney Theme Park Fright Ride |date=October 23, 2015 |work=Deadline |publisher=Penske Business Media, LLC |accessdate=March 28, 2017}}</ref> [[It's A Small World]] was added to the list of known projects in April 2014.<ref>{{cite magazine|last=Fleming |first=Mike |url=http://www.deadline.com/2014/04/disney-taps-jon-turteltaub-to-direct-its-a-small-world-feature-film/ |title=Disney To Make 'It's A Small World' Movie: Jon Turteltaub To Direct |magazine=Deadline.com |date=April 22, 2014 |accessdate=May 20, 2014}}</ref> Tower of Terror was given a theatrical treatment by [[John August]] under producer Jim Whitaker in October 2015, while the long-in-production [[Jungle Cruise]] gained an actor.<ref name=dl1/>\n\n[[Marvel Comics|Marvel Worldwide]] with Disney announced in October 2013 that in January 2014 it would release its first comic book title under their joint [[Marvel Comics#Disney Kingdoms|Disney Kingdoms]] imprint.<ref name=spi>{{cite news |title=Marvel, Disney unveil 1st comic under new imprint |url=http://www.seattlepi.com/news/article/Marvel-Disney-unveil-1st-comic-under-new-imprint-4878283.php |accessdate=October 17, 2013 |agency=[[Associated Press]] |newspaper=[[Seattle Post-Intelligencer]] |date=October 8, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131018022343/http://www.seattlepi.com/news/article/Marvel-Disney-unveil-1st-comic-under-new-imprint-4878283.php |archivedate=October 18, 2013}}</ref> Running for six miniseries, Disney Kingdoms would feature adaptations of the unbuilt Museum of the Weird, two serials about [[Figment (Disney character)|Figment]] and Dreamfinder from [[Epcot]]'s [[Journey into Imagination]], Big Thunder Mountain Railroad, the Haunted Mansion, and [[Walt Disney's Enchanted Tiki Room]]. [[Disney Publishing Worldwide]]'s revived Disney Comics imprint<ref>{{cite news |last1=MacDonald |first1=Heidi |title=Disney Expands Its Comics Program |url=https://www.publishersweekly.com/pw/by-topic/childrens/childrens-industry-news/article/59991-disney-expands-their-comics-program.html |accessdate=January 10, 2020 |work=Publishers Weekly.com |date=November 13, 2013}}</ref> first publication was the ''[[Space Mountain]]'' graphic novel released on May 7, 2014 and based on the same name park attraction.<ref>{{cite news |title=Disney Comics Previews SPACE MOUNTAIN Graphic Novel |url=https://www.newsarama.com/21004-disney-comics-previews-space-mountain-graphic-novel.html |accessdate=January 10, 2020 |work=Newsarama |date=April 30, 2014 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nOn March 31, 2015, the first novel in The Kingdom Keepers sequel trilogy series was released.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Bevil|first1=Dewayne|title=Disney book writer Ridley Pearson heads back in time|url=http://www.orlandosentinel.com/travel/attractions/the-daily-disney/os-disney-ridley-pearson-returns-20150408-story.html|accessdate=May 1, 2017|work=Orlando Sentinel|date=April 8, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2017, [[Freeform (TV channel)|Freeform]] cable channel aired a special documentary, ''[[Disney's Fairy Tale Weddings (TV series)|Disney's Fairy Tale Weddings]]'', based on the services provided by Disney Parks and Resorts unit, [[Disney's Fairy Tale Weddings & Honeymoons]]. With success of the May special, the show was picked up as a series with seven episodes in October 2017.<ref>{{cite news|last=Goldberg|first=Lesley|title=Freeform Orders 'Disney's Fairy Tale Weddings' Series (Exclusive)|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/freeform-orders-disneys-fairy-tale-weddings-series-1049359|accessdate=January 29, 2018|work=The Hollywood Reporter|date=October 17, 2017|language=en}}</ref> However, another special, Holiday Magic, was aired on December 11, 2017 with the now six episode regular series starting on June 11, 2018.<ref>{{cite news|last=Sollosi|first=Mary|title='Disney's Fairy Tale Weddings' is here to make your magical wedding dreams come true|url=http://ew.com/tv/2018/06/07/disneys-fairy-tale-weddings/|accessdate=August 1, 2018|work=Entertainment Weekly|date=June 7, 2018|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Shows A-Z \u2013 disney's fairy tale weddings on freeform|url=http://www.thefutoncritic.com/showatch/disneys-fairy-tale-weddings/listings/|website=TheFutonCritic.com|accessdate=August 1, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Other ventures==\n===Disney Signature Experiences===\nDisney Signature Experiences division, formerly called Disney Cruise Line & New Vacation Operations, holds newer non-theme park travel units under president Jeff Vahle.<ref name=\"os6\"/>\n* [[Disney Cruise Line]] was formed in 1995. Its fleet comprises four ships: [[Disney Magic]] (launched 1998), [[Disney Wonder]] (1999), [[Disney Dream]] (2011), and [[Disney Fantasy]] (2012).<ref name=\"usatoday\"/> Disney Cruise Line has ordered three new ships that will be completed in 2021, 2022 and 2023.<ref name=\"os6\"/> Each ship was designed and built-in collaboration with [[Walt Disney Imagineering]]. Disney Cruise Line serves the Caribbean, Mexican Riviera, European, and Alaskan cruises market.\n* [[Disney Vacation Club]], a [[timeshare]] program that includes 14 themed hotels-resorts within Disneyland Resort and Walt Disney World Resort,  plus [[Aulani|Disney's Aulani Resort]], [[Disney's Hilton Head Island Resort]], and [[Disney's Vero Beach Resort]]. In December 2019, the 15th property, [[Disney's Riviera Resort]], opened next to the Caribbean Beach Resort at Walt Disney World. A 16th resort, [[Reflections - A Disney Lakeside Lodge]], is planned to open in 2022 just east of [[Disney's Wilderness Lodge]] on the former site of [[Disney's River Country]] water park.\n* [[Adventures by Disney]], a program of all-inclusive, guided vacation tour packages offered at predominantly non-Disney sites around the world.<ref name=\"os6\"/>\n*Golden Oak Realty, [[Golden Oak at Walt Disney World Resort]] sales<ref name=\"os6\"/>\n\n===Disney Sports Enterprises===\n{{Infobox company\n| name =Disney Sports Enterprises\n| logo =\n| logo_size =\n| logo_alt =\n| logo_caption =\n| logo_padding =\n| image =\n| image_size =\n| image_alt =\n| image_caption =\n| native_name =\n| native_name_lang = <!-- Use ISO 639-1 code, e.g. \"fr\" for French. For multiple names in different languages, use {{lang|[code]|[name]}}. -->\n| former_name =Disney Sports Attractions\n| type =\n| industry = Sports\n| founded = <!-- if known: {{start date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} in [[city]], [[state]], [[country]] -->\n| founder = [[Reggie Williams (linebacker)|Reggie Williams]].<ref name=os0/>\n| hq_location =\n| hq_location_city =\n| hq_location_country =\n| area_served = <!-- or: | areas_served = -->\n| key_people =Faron Kelley (vice president)\n| products =\n| brands =\n| divisions = [[ESPN Wide World of Sports Complex]]<br>[[runDisney]]\n| services =road race<br>sports events\n| owner = <!-- or: | owners = -->\n| website = {{URL|disneysportsnews.com/}}\n}}\n'''Disney Sports Enterprises''', formerly called Disney Sports Attractions,<ref name=sbd/> is the unit of Disney Parks and Resorts for Disney's sports functions and is made up of the [[ESPN Wide World of Sports Complex]] and the [[runDisney]] program.<ref name=sbd0>{{cite news|title=Executive Transactions|url=http://www.sportsbusinessdaily.com/Daily/Issues/2013/01/10/People-and-Pop-Culture/Execs.aspx|accessdate=April 22, 2016|work=Sports Business Daily|publisher=American City Business Journals|date=January 10, 2013}}</ref>\n\n====DSE background====\nDisney Golf facilities date back to the opening of Disney World with two golf courses, the Palm and Magnolia courses. At the time, those courses started hosting the [[Walt Disney World Golf Classic|Walt Disney World Open Invitational]], an annual PGA Tour event.<ref name=os>{{cite news| last1=Garcia| first1=Jason |title=Disney World to turn golf courses over to Arnold Palmer group |url= http://articles.orlandosentinel.com/2011-08-24/the-daily-disney/os-disney-golf-arnold-palmer-20110824_1_walt-disney-world-golf-courses-golf-datatech |accessdate=April 25, 2016 |work=Orlando Sentinel |date=August 24, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 1994, Disney held the [[Walt Disney World Marathon]], its first road race added additional races later.<ref name=fbs>{{cite news|last1=Sylt|first1=Christian|title=Disney's Runaway Success|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/csylt/2016/01/07/disneys-runaway-success/|accessdate=April 25, 2016|work=Forbes|date=January 7, 2016}}</ref> Disneyland Marathon and 5K were run in 1995 three weeks after the LA Marathon on March 26, 1995.<ref>{{cite news|last1=VanderKnyff|first1=Rick|title=Disneyland's Magical Marathon|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1995-03-23/news/ol-45988_1_disneyland-marathon|accessdate=April 25, 2016|work=Los Angeles Times|date=March 23, 1995}}</ref>\n\nIn 1995, Disney World had IMS Events, Inc. build the [[Walt Disney World Speedway]].<ref name=\"aw\">{{cite news|last1=Larson|first1=Mike|title=Walt Disney World Speedway shutting down for good|url= http://autoweek.com/article/indycar/walt-disney-world-speedway-shutting-down-good|accessdate=April 25, 2016|work=Autoweek|publisher=Crain Communications|date=February 12, 2015}}</ref> [[ESPN Wide World of Sports Complex|Disney's Wide World of Sports]] opened in 1997 under executive [[Reggie Williams (linebacker)|Reggie Williams]].<ref name=os0>{{cite news|last1=Robbins|first1=Josh|title=Reggie Williams to step down as Disney vice president of sports attractions|url=http://articles.orlandosentinel.com/2007-11-14/sports/williams14_1_legs-reggie-williams-atlanta-braves|accessdate=April 25, 2016 |work=Orlando Sentinel |date=November 14, 2007}}</ref>\n\n====DSE history====\nBy 1998, Williams was named Vice President of Disney Sports Attractions, overseeing a newly created sports & recreation division.<ref name=os1>{{cite news|last1=Solano|first1=Javier|title=Directing Sports Of Disney| url= http://articles.orlandosentinel.com/1998-03-27/sports/9803270617_1_disney-wide-disney-sports-complex-world-of-sports |accessdate=April 25, 2016 |work=Orlando Sentinel |date=March 27, 1998}}</ref> The first 10K Disney Classic race on October 3, 1999, kicked off Disney World's 15-month Millennium Celebration.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Carroll|first1=Frank|title=Disney Classic 10k Is Oct. 3|url=http://articles.orlandosentinel.com/1999-09-24/news/9909240052_1_10k-classic-three-aces-male-and-female|accessdate=April 27, 2016|work=Orlando Sentinel|date=September 24, 1999}}</ref> On March 30, 2003, Sports Attractions held the first Disney Inline Marathon.<ref>{{cite news|title=Putting together skate event was a marathon itself|url=http://www.sportsbusinessdaily.com/Journal/Issues/2002/10/20021014/Marketingsponsorship/Putting-Together-Skate-Event-Was-A-Marathon-Itself.aspx|accessdate=April 26, 2016|work=SportsBusiness Journal|issue=October 14\u201320, 2002|publisher=American City Business Journals|date=October 14, 2002}}</ref>\n\nOn November 21, 2007, Reggie Williams retired as vice president of Disney Sports Attractions.<ref name=os0/> His replacement was named on January 3, 2008, when Ken Potrock was promoted to Senior Vice President, Disney Sports Enterprises.<ref name=sbd>{{cite news|title=Disney Moves Marketing Exec Potrock To Sports Enterprises |url=http://www.sportsbusinessdaily.com/Daily/Issues/2008/01/Issue-72/Sports-Industrialists/Disney-Moves-Marketing-Exec-Potrock-To-Sports-Enterprises.aspx|accessdate=April 25, 2016|work=Sports Business Daily|publisher=American City Business Journals|date=January 3, 2008}}</ref> On February 25, 2010, Disney's Wide World of Sports was renamed ESPN Wide World of Sports Complex with some upgrades and new facilities.<ref>{{cite news|title=Disney's Wide World Of Sports Complex To Receive ESPN Rebranding|url=http://www.sportsbusinessdaily.com/Daily/Issues/2009/11/Issue-40/Facilities-Venues/Disneys-Wide-World-Of-Sports-Complex-To-Receive-ESPN-Rebranding.aspx?hl=Disney%20Sports%20Enterprises&sc=1|accessdate=April 26, 2016|work=Sports Business Daily|issue=40|publisher=American City Business Journals}}</ref>\n\nOn September 25, 2011, Disney started the lease of its five Disney World golf courses (Palm, Magnolia, Lake Buena Vista, Osprey Ridge, and Oak Trail) to Arnold Palmer Golf Management to operate for 20 years while splitting the revenue. As part of the deal, Arnold Palmer would redesign the Palm course. The Orlando market for golf had a glut of course from the building boom then bust making profitability a challenge for any golf course. Disney hoped that Palmer's involvement and \"Palmer Advantage\" membership club would draw more attention to Disney's course. With the Osprey Ridge course sold to Four Seasons Hotels and Resorts to build a hotel, which was delayed until 2014, the golf management company would run the course until hotel construction begins. While another golf course, the Eagle Pines, was closed several years ago to make way for a residential housing subdivision development called Golden Oak being built in 2011.<ref name=os/>\n\nIn January 2013, Ken Petrock was promoted to Disney Vacation Club and Adventures by Disney Senior VP & GM while Tom Wolber, Disney Cruise Line Senior VP/Operations, was promoted to replace Petrock at Disney Sports.<ref name=sbd0/> In late June 2015, the [[Walt Disney World Speedway]] was shut down.<ref name=\"aw\"/> Senior Vice President of Disney Springs and the ESPN Wide World of Sports Maribeth Bisienere was promoted to Senior Vice President of Parks in early March 2018.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Storey |first1=Ken |title=A heavily rumored Mary Poppins attraction is starting to look more real at Epcot |url=https://www.orlandoweekly.com/Blogs/archives/2018/03/12/a-heavily-rumored-mary-poppins-attraction-is-starting-to-look-more-real-at-epcot |accessdate=July 11, 2018 |work=Orlando Weekly |date=March 12, 2018 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\";\n|-\n!colspan=4| runDisney races<ref>{{cite news|title=Event Preview \u2013 RunDisney|url=http://www.endurancemag.com/2011/11/event-preview-rundisney/|accessdate=April 26, 2016|work=Endurance Magazine|date=November 21, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=runDisney|url=http://www.rundisney.com|website=rundisney.com|publisher=Disney Sports Enterprises|accessdate=April 27, 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n! Race weekend !! month !! location !! Inaugurated\n|-\n| Disney World Marathon || January \n|rowspan=4| Disney World\n|| 1994<ref name=fbs/> \n|-\n| Princess Half-Marathon|| February || 2009<ref name=os2/>\n|-\n| Star Wars Half Marathon<br>\u2014 The Dark Side || April || 2016<ref name=os2>{{cite news|last1=Ruiz|first1=Stephen|title=Runners from Wisconsin, New York conquer Star Wars Half Marathon at Disney|url=http://www.orlandosentinel.com/sports/os-star-wars-half-marathon-disney-world-20160417-story.html|accessdate=April 27, 2016|work=Orlando Sentinel|date=April 17, 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n| Wine & Dine Half-Marathon || November || \n|-\n| Tinker Bell Half-Marathon || May\n|rowspan=4|  Disneyland \n||\n|-\n| Disneyland Half-Marathon  ||  September<br>(Labor Day weekend) ||\n|-\n| Avengers Super Heroes Half Marathon || November || 2014<ref name=fbs/>\n|-\n| Star Wars Half Marathon<br>\u2014 The Light Side || January || 2015<ref name=fbs/>\n|-\n| Disneyland Paris Half Marathon || September || Disneyland Paris || 2016<ref name=fbs/>\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Universal Parks & Resorts]], Disney's major competitor in the theme park industry\n* [[Warner Bros. Global Brands and Experiences]], Disney's largest cinematic competitor's equivalent branch of their company. \n* [[Disney Consumer Products and Interactive Media#Franchises|Consumer Products franchises]]\n* [[Anaheim Sports]], formerly Disney Sports Enterprises\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\nFrom {{citation|last1=Polsson|first1=Ken|title=Chronology of the Walt Disney Company |url=http://kpolsson.com/disnehis/|website=Chronology of the Walt Disney Company|accessdate=May 5, 2015}}:\n{{reflist|group=CDC|30em}}\nFrom {{citation|last1=Polsson|first1=Ken|title=Chronology of Disneyland Theme Park|url=http://kpolsson.com/disland/|website=Chronology of the Walt Disney Company|accessdate=May 5, 2015}}:\n{{reflist|group=CDL|30em}}\nFrom {{citation|last1=Polsson|first1=Ken|title=Chronology of Disneyland Theme Park (1985\u20131989)|url=http://kpolsson.com/disland/dl1985.htm|website=Chronology of the Walt Disney Company|accessdate=May 5, 2015}}:\n{{reflist|group=CDL4|30em}}\nFrom {{citation|last1=Polsson|first1=Ken|title=Chronology of Disneyland Theme Park (1990\u20131999)|url=http://kpolsson.com/disland/dl1990.htm|website=Chronology of the Walt Disney Company|accessdate=May 5, 2015}}:\n{{reflist|group=CDL5|30em}}\nFrom {{citation|last1=Polsson|first1=Ken |title=Chronology of Walt Disney World (1958\u20131971) |url=http://kpolsson.com/wdworld/ |website=Chronology of the Walt Disney Company|accessdate=September 24, 2015}}:\n{{reflist|group=CDW|30em}}\nFrom {{citation|last1=Polsson|first1=Ken|title=Chronology of Walt Disney World (1972\u20131982) |url=http://kpolsson.com/wdworld/wdw1972.htm|website=Chronology of the Walt Disney Company|accessdate=September 24, 2015}}:\n{{reflist|group=CDW0|30em}}\nFrom {{citation|last1=Polsson|first1=Ken|title=Chronology of Walt Disney World (1983\u20131989)|url=http://kpolsson.com/wdworld/wdw1983.htm|website=Chronology of the Walt Disney Company|accessdate=September 24, 2015}}:\n{{reflist|group=CDW1|30em}}\nFrom {{citation|last1=Polsson|first1=Ken|title=Chronology of Walt Disney World (1990\u20131994)|url=http://kpolsson.com/wdworld/wdw1990.htm|website=Chronology of the Walt Disney Company|accessdate=September 24, 2015}}:\n{{reflist|group=CDW2|30em}}\nFrom {{citation|last1=Polsson|first1=Ken|title=Chronology of Walt Disney World (1995-end)|url=http://kpolsson.com/wdworld/wdw1995.htm |website=Chronology of the Walt Disney Company|accessdate=September 24, 2015}}:\n{{reflist|group=CDW3|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikivoyage|Disney}}\n* {{Official website|https://dpep.disney.com/}}\n\n{{Disney}}\n{{DisneyConsumer}}\n{{Disney Parks, Experiences and Products}}\n\n[[Category:American companies established in 1971]]\n[[Category:The Walt Disney Company]]\n[[Category:Walt Disney Parks and Resorts| ]]\n[[Category:The Walt Disney Company subsidiaries|Parks and Resorts]]\n[[Category:Amusement park companies]]\n[[Category:Hospitality companies of the United States]]\n[[Category:Entertainment companies based in California]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Florida]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Burbank, California]]\n[[Category:Entertainment companies established in 1971]]\n[[Category:1971 establishments in California]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2017}}\n{{use American English|date=March 2017}}\n\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Disney Parks, Experiences and Products, Inc.\n| logo = Disney parks, experiences & products logo.svg\n| former_name = {{ubl|Walt Disney Outdoor Recreation Division (1980\u20131989)|Walt Disney Attractions (1989\u20132008)|Walt Disney Parks and Resorts Worldwide, Inc. (2008\u20132018)|Walt Disney Parks, Experiences and Consumer Products (2018)<ref name=\"cnbc\"/>}}\n| type = Subsidiary<ref name=sbz/>\n| fate = \n| successor = \n| predecessors = {{ubl|Walt Disney Parks and Resorts Worldwide|Disney Consumer Products and Interactive Media}}\n| foundation = {{Start date and age|1971|04|01}}\n| defunct = \n| location_city = [[Lake Buena Vista, Florida]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Company Overview of Walt Disney Parks and Resorts U.S., Inc |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/research/stocks/private/snapshot.asp?privcapId=4159864 |website=Bloomberg}}</ref>\n| location_country = United States\n| key_people = {{ubl|Rebecca Campbell (President, Disneyland Resort)|Michael Colglazier (President, Disney Parks International)|Josh D\u2019Amaro (President, Walt Disney World Resort)|Ken Potrock (President, Consumer Products)}}\n| industry = Consumer products, theme parks, attractions, video games, publishing, recreation, and hospitality\n| services = {{flatlist|\n*Theme parks\n*Hotel lodging\n*Cruises\n*Timeshares\n*Guided tours\n*Travel packages\n*Attraction design\n*Licensing}}\n| parent = [[The Walt Disney Company]]\n| divisions = {{ubl|Disney Parks International|[[Disney Parks, Experiences and Products#Disney Signature Experiences|Disney Signature Experiences]] }}\n| subsid = {{ubl|[[Disney Consumer Products]]|[[Disneyland Resort]]|[[Walt Disney World]]|[[Disney Vacation Club|Disney Vacation Development, Inc.]]|[[Disneyland Paris]]|Disneyland International|[[Walt Disney Imagineering|Walt Disney Imagineering Research & Development, Inc.]]|[[Disney Publishing Worldwide]]|[[The Muppets Studio]]|[[Disney Interactive]]}}\n| module = <!-- Used to embed other templates -->\n| website = {{URL|dpep.disney.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Disney Parks, Experiences and Products, Inc.''', formerly '''Walt Disney Parks and Resorts Worldwide, Inc.''' and informally known as '''Disney Parks''', is one of [[The Walt Disney Company]]'s four major business segments and a subsidiary.<ref name=sbz>{{cite web|title=Detail by Entity Name: Walt Disney Parks and Resorts Worldwide, Inc.|url=http://search.sunbiz.org/Inquiry/CorporationSearch/SearchResultDetail?inquirytype=EntityName&directionType=ForwardList&searchNameOrder=WALTDISNEYPARKSRESORTSWORLDWID%20F090000012040&aggregateId=forp-f09000001204-dfbb7cc6-7dee-4d8b-bbef-3244c551d808&searchTerm=Walt%20Disney%20Parks%20and%20Resorts%20Worldwide&listNameOrder=WALTDISNEYPARKSRESORTSWORLDWID%20F090000012040|website=SunBiz.org|publisher=Florida Department of State Division of Corporations|accessdate=October 12, 2015}}</ref> It was founded on April 1, 1971, exactly six months before the opening of [[Magic Kingdom]] at [[Walt Disney World|Walt Disney World Resort]] in [[Bay Lake, Florida|Bay Lake]], [[Florida]] just outside of [[Orlando]], Florida.\n\nOriginally, the company was known as '''Walt Disney Outdoor Recreation Division''' and later as '''Walt Disney Attractions'''. The most recent chairman of Walt Disney Parks and Resorts was [[Bob Chapek]], formerly president of [[Disney Consumer Products]]. Chapek was promoted CEO of the entire Walt Disney Company on February 25, 2020.<ref>https://www.cnbc.com/2020/02/25/who-is-bob-chapek-the-new-ceo-of-disney.html</ref><ref>https://www.latimes.com/entertainment-arts/business/story/2020-02-25/bob-chapek-named-walt-disney-co-ceo-replacing-bob-iger</ref> In 2018, the company's theme parks hosted over 157.3 million guests, making Disney Parks the world's most visited theme park company worldwide,<ref name=\"TEA/AECOM\">{{Cite web|title=TEA/AECOM 2018 Theme Index and Museum Index: The Global Attractions Attendance Report|url=http://www.teaconnect.org/images/files/TEA_235_103719_170601.pdf|publisher=[[Themed Entertainment Association|TEA]]/[[AECOM]]|date=2019|p=5|accessdate=August 25, 2019|archiveurl=http://www.teaconnect.org/images/files/328_572762_190522.pdf|archivedate=June 2, 2019}}</ref> with United Kingdom-based [[Merlin Entertainments]] coming in second at 67 million guests. It is by far Disney's largest business segment according to employee headcount, with approximately 130,000<ref name=\"Barnes\">{{cite news|last1=Barnes|first1=Brooks|title=Thomas Staggs: Disney\u2019s Heir, Apparently|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/04/26/business/media/thomas-staggs-disneys-heir-apparently.html|accessdate=April 26, 2015|work=The New York Times|publisher=The New York Times Company|date=April 26, 2015|location=New York|page=BU1}}</ref> of the company's 180,000 employees as of 2015.<ref name=10K>{{cite web|url=http://thewaltdisneycompany.com/sites/default/files/reports/fy14-form-10k.pdf|title=Form 10-K, U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission, by the Walt Disney Company for the Fiscal Year Ended September 27, 2014|publisher=The Walt Disney Company|accessdate=November 23, 2014|date=November 19, 2014|page=1|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141217131710/http://thewaltdisneycompany.com/sites/default/files/reports/fy14-form-10k.pdf|archivedate=December 17, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> In March 2018, [[Disney Consumer Products|Disney Consumer Products and Interactive Media]] was merged into Parks and Resorts and renamed Disney Parks, Experiences and Products.\n\n==Background==\n{{main|Disneyland, Inc.}}\nIn 1949, [[Ice Capades]] added a Disney segment to its performances. Costumes from those shows were used at the opening of Disneyland in 1955 with some performers hired away for Disney.<ref name=jhm>{{cite news|last1=Korkis|first1=Jim|title=Wednesdays with Wade: 25 years of \"Disney on Ice\"|url=http://jimhillmedia.com/alumni1/b/wade_sampson/archive/2005/09/14/1278.aspx|accessdate=July 30, 2015|work=JimHillMedia|date=September 13, 2005}}</ref>\n\nOriginally, entry into the theme park and travel business was a side project of Walt Disney himself. As the Disneylandia project started to become a reality, [[The Walt Disney Company|Walt Disney Productions]] at Walt's request set up Disneyland, Inc. (DLI) in 1951 and agreed to a design deal in March 1953 with [[Retlaw Enterprises|WED Enterprises (WED)]], [[Walt Disney|Walt]]'s personal corporation, which then included what would now be called [[Walt Disney Imagineering|Disney Imagineering]].<ref name=hwrg>{{cite book|last1=Aberdeen|first1=J. A.|title=Hollywood Renegades|date=2000|publisher=Cobblestone Entertainment|isbn=1-890110-24-8|url=https://archive.org/details/hollywoodrenegad00aber|accessdate=May 5, 2015|chapter=Disneyland|chapter-url=http://www.cobbles.com/simpp_archive/simpp_1954disneyland.htm }}</ref><ref group=CDL>{{cite book|last1=Thomas |first1=Bob |title=Building a Company - Roy O. Disney and the Creation of an Entertainment Empire|date=1998|page=254}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Gabler|first1=Neal|title=Walt Disney \u2013 The Triumph of the American Imagination|date=2006|page=493}}</ref> With the WED concept designs and prospectus for Disneylandia, Roy Disney in September 1953 met with TV networks in a deal for Disney-produced TV show and Disneyland investment. [[American Broadcasting-Paramount Theatres]] (AB-PT) agreed to the Disneyland, Inc. investment.<ref name=hwrg/> Joining AB-PT as Disneyland investors were [[Walt Disney Productions]] (WDP), [[Western Publishing]] and [[Walt Disney]].<ref group=CDL>{{cite book|last1=Thomas|first1=Bob|title=Walt Disney \u2013 An American Original|date=1994|page=222}}</ref> Walt Disney Productions had the option to repurchase the Walt Disney, WED and Western Publishing shares (31%) by May 1, 1959, for $562,500.<ref name=bbd>{{cite news|title=Disneyland Tabs $2.29 Per Capita; See Small Net First Yr.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yB4EAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA69&lpg=PA69&dq=Walt+Disney+Productions+Disneyland,+Inc.+option&source=bl&ots=0NOMFq8DpO&sig=eQQINoEQqlhCBUd2kikDffo7G3U&hl=en&sa=X&ei=qi5JVZ2xF4uYsAWrloCQDw&ved=0CB8Q6AEwATge#v=onepage&q=Walt%20Disney%20Productions%20Disneyland%2C%20Inc.%20option&f=false|accessdate=May 6, 2015|work=Billboard|date=January 28, 1956|page=69}}</ref>\n\nWith a need for the [[Disneyland Hotel (California)|Disneyland Hotel]] nearby and no funding available for Disney to build it, Walt Disney approached [[Jack Wrather]] to build the hotel who agreed.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Kimler|first1=Forest|title=Jack Built More Than a House|url=http://2.bp.blogspot.com/_OYARMoeQUr4/TH_wXKWs_pI/AAAAAAAABnU/XnEcgWwEtwk/s1600/1978+newspaper+2aa.JPG |accessdate=August 28, 2015 |work=Orange County Register|date=September 11, 1978}}</ref>\n\n[[Disneyland]], changed from Disneylandia, was announced in {{dts|1954|4}} by Walt to be opened in {{dts|1955|7}}.<ref group=CDL>Walt Disney, by Jim Fanning, 1994. Page 100.</ref><ref group=CDL>Walt Disney \u2013 Hollywood's Dark Prince, by Marc Eliot, 1993. Page 223.</ref> On {{dts|1955|7|17}}, the Disneyland park opened with five themed \"lands\" containing eighteen attractions with double the expected guests.<ref group=CDL>Walt Disney, by Jim Fanning, 1994. Page 102.</ref> WED owned [[Disneyland Railroad|Santa Fe & Disneyland Railroad]] opened, too.<ref name=lat>{{cite news|last=Peltz|first=James F.|title=The Wonderful World of Disney's Other Firm : Entertainment: Walt Disney created a separate company for his family. Retlaw Enterprises Inc. is now worth hundreds of millions.|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1990-10-02/business/fi-1834_1_walt-disney|accessdate=July 19, 2012|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|date=October 2, 1990}}</ref>\n\nOn June 29, 1957, Disney Production exercised its options to purchase all but AB-PT's common stock outstanding. This allowed WDP to consolidate DLI into its 1957 annual accounting statements adding four months' worth of net profits, $511K.<ref>{{cite news|title=Disneyland Draws 4,200,000; Parent Firm Buys More Stock|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ayEEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA86|accessdate=May 6, 2015|work=Billboard|date=January 13, 1958}}</ref> In June 1960, Walt Disney Productions completed the purchase of AB-PT's share of the company for nearly $7.5 million and its TV contract, and the theme park became a fully owned subsidiary of Walt Disney Productions.<ref group=CDL>{{cite book|last1=Thomas|first1=Bob |title=Walt Disney \u2013 An American Original |date=1994|page=286}}</ref> The first [[Audio-Animatronics|Audio-Animatronic]] attraction, [[Walt Disney's Enchanted Tiki Room]], opened at [[Disneyland]] in 1963.<ref>{{cite book |first=Richard W. |last=Kroon |title=A/V A to Z: An Encyclopedic Dictionary of Media, Entertainment and Other Audiovisual Terms |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HjmNAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA64 |year=2014 |publisher=McFarland |isbn=978-0-7864-5740-3 |page=64}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nBeginning in 1958 with the contracting of Economics Research Associates (ERA) to find a location for another Disney resort, Disney Productions moved beyond a single park. ERA recommended Florida; another study in 1961 named [[Ocala, Florida|Ocala]] or [[Orlando]] in Florida as possible locations. In {{dts|1963|11}}, Walt Disney made a trip to Florida for final site selection.<ref name=p48 group=CDW>Walt Disney \u2013 An American Original, by Bob Thomas, 1994.</ref><sup>:333, 334</sup> In 1962, Disney Productions purchased [[Celebrity Sports Center]] (opened on September 17, 1960, in Denver, Colorado) from its owners, including Walt Disney, [[Art Linkletter]], and [[John Payne (actor)|John Payne]], to use as a staff training center for its second resort.<ref name=d23a>{{cite web|title=Celebrity Sports Center|url=https://d23.com/a-to-z/celebrity-sports-center/|website=D23.com|publisher=The Walt Disney Company|accessdate=October 6, 2015}}</ref> In 1963, Roy made plans to buy from {{convert|5,000|to|10,000|acre}}, which was carried out in 1964, amassing {{convert|27,443|acre}} by {{dts|1965|10}}.<ref group=CDW>Building a Company \u2013 Roy O. Disney and the Creation of an Entertainment Empire, by Bob Thomas, 1998. Pages 278, 279, 281\u2013282.</ref><ref group=CDW name=aao>Walt Disney \u2013 An American Original, by Bob Thomas, 1994. Page 337.</ref> Plans for the Florida project that would eventually become [[Walt Disney World]] were announced to the public in November 1965.<ref group=CDW name=aao/> Legislation forming the [[Reedy Creek Improvement District]] was signed into law by Florida Governor [[Claude R. Kirk, Jr.]] on May 12, 1967, allowing Disney to build the infrastructure for the second park.<ref group=CDW>{{cite book|last1=Thomas |first1=Bob|title=Walt Disney \u2013 An American Original|date=1994|page=357}}</ref> Ground breaking followed for the future Reedy Creek park on May 30.<ref group=CDW>{{cite book|last1=Smith|first1=Dave|last2=Clark|first2=Steven|title=Disney \u2013 The First 100 Years|date=2002|page=103|edition=updated}}</ref> In Roy O. Disney's last act as CEO in 1968, he officially named the second park [[Walt Disney World]].<ref name=p48 group=CDW/><sup>:357</sup>\n\nDisneyland International was incorporated on November 20, 1961.<ref>{{cite web|title=Business Entity Detail: Disneyland International (C0423655; must search on name)|url=http://kepler.sos.ca.gov/|website=California Department of State|accessdate=September 24, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150315010639/http://kepler.sos.ca.gov/|archive-date=March 15, 2015|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The next year, [[The Oriental Land Company]] contacted Disney about building a theme park.<ref name=lat1>{{cite news|title=Disneyland in Tokyo Is a 10-Year Hit|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1994-04-12/business/fi-45190_1_tokyo-disneyland|accessdate=August 20, 2015|work=Los Angeles Times|agency=Associated Press|date=April 12, 1994}}</ref>\n\nIn 1959, the WED-owned [[Disneyland Monorail System|Disneyland-Alweg Monorail System]] was installed at Disneyland.<ref name=lat/><ref name=lat0>{{cite news|title=Disneyland: A Chronology|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1991-05-09/news/mn-2210_1_walt-disney| accessdate=September 23, 2015 |work=Los Angeles Times| date=May 9, 1991}}</ref> Disneyland's first new themed land, New Orleans Square, opened in {{dts|1966}}. Tomorrowland was revamped in 1967 with seven new attractions.<ref name=lat0/> The design and architectural group and the WED Enterprise name was purchased from Walt's corporation, renamed as Retlaw Enterprise.<ref name=lat/>\n\nDisney expanded into attractions at the [[1964 New York World's Fair]] with [[It's a Small World]]<ref name=gma/> and costumed character appearances. When the characters proved a hit at the 1964 World's Fair, Walt wanted another outlet for \"live\" characters; thus, Disneyland put on ''Disney on Parade'', a self-produced live arena show starting in 1969.<ref name=jhm/><ref>{{cite news|title=Live Disney Characters in Traveling Arena Show|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=rDwwAAAAIBAJ&sjid=ySoDAAAAIBAJ&pg=3905%2C4281044|accessdate=July 30, 2015|work=The News and the Eastern Townships Advocate|issue=Vol. 123 No. 45|publisher=E.R. Smith Co. Ltd.|date=September 17, 1970|location=St. Johns, PQ|pages=2, 3}}</ref> Small World and its famous song lasted two years at the fair; it was then moved to Disneyland as an expanded major attraction in 1966 and later duplicated in the other Disney theme parks.<ref name=gma>{{cite news|last1=Shaw Brown|first1=Genevieve|title=It's a Small World: 9 Little-Known Facts|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Travel/disneys-small-world-facts/story?id=22990670|accessdate=August 26, 2015|work=Good Morning America|publisher=ABC News|date=March 21, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 1965, Walt Disney won a bid with the [[US Forest Service]] to develop [[Mineral King]] as a ski resort. The [[Sierra Club]] sued in {{dts|1969|6}} to stop the development, which was granted by the federal district judge. The Forest Service appealed and won at the appeal and the Supreme Court. The Supreme Court ruling left open to the Club the possibility of refiling. In the next round of lawsuits, the same district judge blocked the redevelopment. The injunction and the passage of the [[National Environmental Policy Act]] led to Disney backing out.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.hcn.org/wotr/the-saga-of-mineral-king |title=The saga of Mineral King |date=February 2, 2009 |newspaper=High Country News |accessdate=September 12, 2009}}</ref>\n\n$40 million worth of Walt Disney Productions Convertible [[Debenture]]s were sold in {{dts|1968|1}} to fund Disney World (WDW). The next year in February, an agreement was made with multiple labor unions, in which the unions exchanged the right to strike for regular pay increases during the first building phase.<ref group=CDW>{{cite news|work=U.S. News & World Report|last1=Cooper|first1=M|last2=Friedman|first2=D|title=Empire of the Sun|date=May 28, 1990|page=47}}</ref> By 1971, chairman of the Park Operations Committee and vice president of park operations Dick Nunis was appointed executive vice president of Disneyland and Walt Disney World.<ref>{{cite web|title=Disney Legend: Dick Nunis|url=https://d23.com/walt-disney-legend/dick-nunis/|website=d23|publisher=The Walt Disney Company|accessdate=October 7, 2015}}</ref>\n\n[[Walt Disney World]] began operation on {{dts|1971|10|1}}, with the [[Magic Kingdom]] park at a cost of $400 million. The Magic Kingdom had six themed lands: Main Street, Adventureland, Fantasyland, Frontierland, Liberty Square, and Tomorrowland.<ref group=CDW>{{cite book|title=Birnbaum's Walt Disney World 1997|url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780786881925|url-access=registration|date=1996|publisher=Hearst Business Publishing|page=[https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780786881925/page/15 15]}}</ref> Additionally, Disney's Fort Wilderness Resort campground and two hotels, Disney's Contemporary Resort and Disney's Polynesian Village Resort, also opened.<ref group=CDW>{{cite book| last1=Smith|first1=Dave |title=Disney A to Z \u2013 The Official Encyclopedia| url=https://archive.org/details/disneytozofficia00smit| url-access=registration|date=1996|page=[https://archive.org/details/disneytozofficia00smit/page/103 103], 191,397}}</ref>\n\nDisneyland expanded in 1972 with a seventh themed land, [[Bear Country (Disneyland)|Bear Country]], replacing the Indian Village of Frontierland, and later renamed Critter Country. In 1979, the Disneyland crafts and maintenance union workers went on strike for 15 days, at first, rejecting and then accepting the park's contract.<ref name=lat0/> [[Space Mountain (Disneyland)|Space Mountain]] opens at Disneyland in 1977.<ref name=lat0/>\n\nTwo more hotels opened in 1973 at Walt Disney World: the Golf Resort<ref>{{cite web|title=Disney Inn, The|url=https://d23.com/a-to-z/disney-inn-the/|website=D23: Disney A to Z|publisher=The Walt Disney Company|accessdate=September 23, 2015}}</ref> and the Gold Resort;<ref group=CDW>{{cite book|last1=Smith|first1=Dave|title=Disney A to Z \u2013 The Official Encyclopedia|url=https://archive.org/details/disneytozofficia00smit|url-access=registration|date=1996|page=[https://archive.org/details/disneytozofficia00smit/page/209 209]}}</ref> Disney's Village Resort hotel opened in 1974.{{citation needed|date=September 2015}} Disney opened the Buena Vista Club golf club in Lake Buena Vista on {{dts|1974|11|22}}.<ref name=r228 group=CDW0>{{cite book|last1=Smith|first1=Dave|title=Disney A to Z \u2013 The Official Encyclopedia|url=https://archive.org/details/disneytozofficia00smit|url-access=registration|date=1996}}</ref><sup>:71</sup> [[Disney Springs|Lake Buena Vista Village]], the shopping area, opened on {{dts|1975|3|22}}<ref name=r228 group=CDW0/> and was renamed Walt Disney World Village in 1977.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Smith |first1=Dave |title=Downtown Disney Marketplace |url=https://d23.com/a-to-z/downtown-disney-marketplace/|website=D23: Disney A to Z|publisher=Walt Disney Company|accessdate=September 24, 2015}}</ref><sup>:280</sup> Celebrity Sports Center, Disney World's training center, was sold on March 29, 1979.<ref name=d23a/>\n\nAt Walt Disney World, the Treasure Island nature preserve pens opened on April 8, 1974,<ref name=r501 group=CDW0>Disney A to Z \u2013 The Updated Official Encyclopedia, by Dave Smith, 1998.</ref><sup>:569</sup> renamed Discovery Island in 1977.<ref name=r228 group=CDW0/><sup>:126</sup> On {{dts|1975|7|1}}, the [[WEDway PeopleMover]] opened in the Magic Kingdom's Tomorrowland.<ref group=CDW0>Disney Magazine, Summer 1999. Page 85.</ref> The first water park, [[Disney's River Country|River Country]], opened on {{dts|1976|6|20}} at Disney World.<ref name=r210 group=CDW0>Birnbaum's Walt Disney World 1997, by Hearst Business Publishing, 1996.</ref><sup>:22</sup> [[Epcot|EPCOT]] Center's groundbreaking occurred at Walt Disney World in May 1979.<ref group=CDW0>Walt Disney World, by The Walt Disney Company, 1994?.</ref>\n\nIn 1979, [[Oriental Land]] and Disney agreed to build a Japanese theme park.<ref name=lat1 /> [[Tokyo Disneyland]] opened on {{dts|1983|4|15}} on {{convert|200|acre|sigfig=1}} in [[Urayasu, Chiba]], Japan.<ref name=lat2>{{cite news|last1=Miller|first1=Greg|title=Disney Plans Aquatic Park in Tokyo|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1995-11-08/business/fi-711_1_tokyo-disneysea|accessdate=August 20, 2015|work=Los Angeles Times|date=November 8, 1995}}</ref>\n\n===Walt Disney Outdoor Recreation Division===\nWith the June 3, 1980, retirement of [[Donn Tatum]] as Walt Disney Productions' Chairman and CEO, three divisions were formed, including the Walt Disney Outdoor Recreation Division, of which Nunis was named division president.<ref group=CDW0>The New York Times, [http://kpolsson.com/disnehis/disn1980.htm June 4, 1980]. Page D1.</ref> Disneyland started using [[Company scrip|Disney Dollars]] on May 5, 1987,<ref group=CDL4>Canadian Coin News, July 21, 1987, Volume 25, Number 6. Page 2.</ref>  while Walt Disney World parks started with Epcot on October 2.<ref group=CDW1>Canadian Coin News, October 27, 1987, Volume 25, Number 13. Page 1.</ref> A renegotiated Disneyland Japan royalty agreement in April 1988 by Chief Financial Officer [[Gary L. Wilson]] netted Disney US$723 million in cash in exchange for lower royalty payments.<ref group=CDW0>Forbes, [http://kpolsson.com/disnehis/disn1988.htm March 6, 1989], Volume 143. Page 42.</ref>\n\nThe steam railroad and monorail at Disneyland were purchased from [[Retlaw Enterprises]], formerly WED Enterprises, in 1982.<ref name=lat0/> Bear Country was renamed [[Critter Country]] on November 23, 1988.<ref group=CDL4>'' Disneyland: Then, Now, and Forever'', by Bruce Gordon and Tim O'Day, 2005. Page 99.</ref>\n\n[[Tishman Realty & Construction|Tishman Company]]'s plans for two Walt Disney World hotels were rejected by the new CEO [[Michael Eisner]] on September 30, 1984, marking a change in Disney architecture. New plans for the Dolphin and Swan hotels were submitted by Michael Graves in July 1986;<ref group=CDW1>Building a Dream \u2013 The Art of Disney Architecture, by Beth Dunlop, 1996. Pages 63,66.</ref> ground breaking took place on January 28, 1988.<ref group=CDW1>The New York Times, January 28, 1988. Page C1.</ref> The first non-Disney owned hotel, Pickett Suite Resort, opened in [[Disney Springs|Disney World Village]] on March 15, 1987.<ref group=CDW1>Disney A to Z \u2013 The Official Encyclopedia, by Dave Smith, 1996. Page 387.</ref>\n\nOn June 1, 1982, the Walt Disney World monorail line was extended to EPCOT Center from the Ticket and Transportation Center.<ref name=r228 group=CDW0/><sup>:338</sup> The EPCOT Center theme park opened on October 1, 1982, at a building cost of US$1.2 billion, with two areas, [[Epcot#Future World|Future World]] and [[World Showcase]].<ref group=CDW0>Walt Disney \u2013 Hollywood's Dark Prince, by Marc Eliot, 1993.</ref><sup>:272</sup>\n\nPlans for a Hollywood-style theme park were announced in April 1985 for the Walt Disney World resort at a project cost of US$300 million.<ref group=CDW1>Prince of the Magic Kingdom, by Joe Flower, 1991.</ref> In April 1985, Disney signed a licensing agreement with [[MGM]], giving Disney the right to use the MGM name, logo and movie library for this third park.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Weiss|first1=Werner|title=Disney-MGM Studios: The End of the MGM Name|url=http://www.yesterland.com/mgm-end.html|website=Yesterland.com|publisher=|accessdate=October 7, 2015}} sources:\n*{{cite book|last1=Eisner|first1=Michael|title=Work in Progress|url=https://archive.org/details/workinprogress00eisn_0|url-access=registration|date=1998}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Grover|first1=Ron|title=The Disney Touch|url=https://archive.org/details/disneytouchhowda0000grov|url-access=registration|date=1991}}</ref> Construction of the [[Disney's Hollywood Studios|Disney-MGM Studios]] theme park began in 1986.<ref group=CDW1>Walt Disney World \u2013 20 Magical Years, by the Walt Disney Company, 1991/2?.</ref> Disney-MGM Studios opened on May 1, 1989,<ref group=CDW1>Page D5. The New York Times, May 1, 1989, Volume 138, Number 47857.</ref> along with a Pleasure Island entertainment area;<ref group=CDW1>Birnbaum's Walt Disney World 1997, by Hearst Business Publishing, 1996. Page 18.</ref> its second water park, [[Disney's Typhoon Lagoon]], opened on June 1.<ref group=CDW1>Orlando Attractions, Summer 2009. Page 33.</ref> In 1983, Walt Disney World Village's name was changed to the Disney Village Marketplace.<ref group=CDW1>Disney A to Z \u2013 The Official Encyclopedia, by Dave Smith, 1996. Page 132.</ref> A new themed area, Mickey's Birthdayland, opened in the Magic Kingdom near Fantasyland on June 18, 1988.<ref group=CDW1>Disney A to Z \u2013 The Official Encyclopedia, by Dave Smith, 1996. Page 324.</ref>\n\nIn 1987, Disney and [[Ron Brierley]]'s Industrial Equity (Pacific) Ltd., already a 28% owner of the [[Jack Wrather|Wrather Corporation]], agreed to purchase the remaining Wrather Corporation stock with a 50% share each.<ref name=nyt>{{cite news|last1=Berg|first1=Eric N.|title=Company News; Wrather Accepts $21-a-Share Offer|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1987/09/29/business/company-news-wrather-accepts-21-a-share-offer.html|accessdate=August 27, 2015|work=New York Times|date=September 29, 1987}}</ref><ref name=nyt0>{{cite news|last1=|first1=|title=COMPANY NEWS; Disney Buys Stake|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1988/03/30/business/company-news-disney-buys-stake.html|accessdate=August 27, 2015|work=New York Times|date=March 30, 1988}}</ref> Wrather Corporation owned the [[Disneyland Hotel (California)|Disneyland Hotel]] and operated the [[RMS Queen Mary|Queen Mary]] and [[Hughes H-4 Hercules|Spruce Goose]] tourist attractions.<ref name=nyt/> In March 1988, Disney purchased Industrial Equity's half of Wrather Corporation.<ref name=nyt0/>\n\nIn 1985, [[Premier Cruise Line]] became the licensed partner cruise line with Disney. This allowed Disney characters on their ships and combined cruise, hotel, and theme park packages.<ref name=usat2>{{cite news|last1=Fritscher|first1=Lisa|title=How Disney Cruises Started|url=http://traveltips.usatoday.com/disney-cruises-started-17319.html|accessdate=October 8, 2015|work=USA Today|agency=Demand Media|publisher=Gannett Satellite Information Network, Inc.\n|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180316130947/https://traveltips.usatoday.com/disney-cruises-started-17319.html |archive-date=March 16, 2018}} (use archival url as original info was replaced.)</ref>\n\n===Walt Disney Attractions===\nThe Walt Disney Outdoor Recreation Division was incorporated as Walt Disney Attractions, Inc. on August 10, 1989.<ref>{{cite web|title=Detail by Entity Name: Walt Disney Attractions, Incorporated |url= http://search.sunbiz.org/Inquiry/CorporationSearch/SearchResultDetail?inquirytype=EntityName&directionType=PreviousList&searchNameOrder=WALTDISNEYATTRACTIONS%20P255770&aggregateId=forp-p25577-93b956e8-76e8-42c2-b789-99a8528d7053&searchTerm=Walt%20Disney%20Parks%20and%20Resorts%20Worldwide&listNameOrder=WALTDIESINGASSOCIATES%20K475700 |website=SunBiz.org |publisher=Florida Department of State Division of Corporations|accessdate=October 12, 2015}}</ref> In January 1990, Disney CEO Eisner announced plans to expand both Disneyland (by 20% in 10 years)<ref group=CDC>The New York Times, [http://kpolsson.com/disnehis/disn1990.htm January 13, 1990]. Page 37.</ref> and Walt Disney World (WDW). The plan would have WDW add another theme park and 16 new attractions in Disney-MGM Studios.<ref group=CDW2>The New York Times, January 16, 1990. Page D8.</ref> Disney and [[The Coca-Cola Company]] agreed to a 15-year marketing contract on January 25: Coca-Cola products would be exclusive in Disney theme parks, and Coca-Cola would use some Disney characters in their ads.<ref group=CDC>The New York Times, January 26, 1990. Page D4.</ref> On March 16, 1990, Attractions president Nunis announced a 25-year plan for a {{convert|4400|acre|adj=on}} development in [[Osceola, Florida]], with homes, shopping malls and industrial buildings.<ref group=CDC>The New York Times, [http://kpolsson.com/disnehis/disn1990.htm March 17, 1990]. Page 37.</ref>\n\nIn 1990, the possibility of a West Coast version of Epcot Center was placed in development.<ref group=CDC>Business Week, [http://kpolsson.com/disnehis/disn1990.htm January 29, 2001]. Page 58.</ref> This was announced as [[WestCOT]] in 1991, to be placed at the Disneyland Resort.<ref name=lat0/> On July 31, 1990, a new {{convert|350|acre|adj=on}} ocean-themed park and resort, Port Disney, was announced for Long Beach. Port was to have a cruise-ship terminal, five hotels, restaurants, and shopping areas, costing $2 billion to build.<ref group=CDC>The New York Times, [http://kpolsson.com/disnehis/disn1990jul.htm August 1, 1990]. Page D4.</ref> On December 12, 1991, Disney selected only one California project to go forward with, Disneyland Resort, which was to include the WestCOT Center, hotels, a shopping mall, and a lake. <ref group=CDL5>The New York Times, December 13, 1991. Page D1.</ref> Port Disney was abandoned in March 1992, and Disney canceled its leases on the Queen Mary and Spruce Goose attractions picked up from the Wrather Corporation.<ref group=CDC>The New York Times, [http://kpolsson.com/disnehis/disn1992.htm March 7, 1992]. Page 49.</ref> [[Mickey's Toontown]], a new themed land at Disneyland, opened on January 24, 1993.<ref group=CDL5>Walt Disney \u2013 Hollywood's Dark Prince, by Marc Eliot, 1993. Page 279.</ref> Disney canceled its plans for WestCOT in mid-1995 due to financial issues at [[Disneyland Paris]] and the park's projected high cost. That park was then replaced by plans for the [[Disney California Adventure|California Adventure]] park, hotels, and a retail district.<ref name=wsj>{{cite news|last1=Marr|first1=Merissa|title=Disney's $1 Billion Adventure|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB119257768823361264|accessdate=November 16, 2015|work=The Wall Street Journal|date=October 17, 2007|page=B1}}</ref>\n\nAt Walt Disney World, Mickey's Birthdayland closed on April 22, 1991, then reopened on May 26 as Mickey's Starland.<ref name=r228 group=CDW2>Disney A to Z \u2013 The Official Encyclopedia, by Dave Smith, 1996.</ref><sup>324, 329, 333</sup> In order to expand Disney World on wetland, on April 23, 1993, the company agreed to form an {{convert|8500|acre|adj=on}} wilderness preserve in Florida.<ref group=CDW2>Disney Magazine, Summer 2001. Page 39.</ref> The Disney Inn hotel was leased starting February 1, 1994, by the US Army, then purchased on January 12, 1996, and later renamed Shades of Green.<ref name=r228 group=CDW2/><sup>130</sup> [[Planet Hollywood]] opened a location in Pleasure Island on December 17, 1994.<ref group=CDW1>''The Disney Magazine'', Fall 1995, Volume 30, Number 4. Page 43.</ref> The third water park at Walt Disney World, [[Disney's Blizzard Beach]], opened on April 1, 1995.<ref group=CDW3>Birnbaum's Walt Disney World 1997, by Hearst Business Publishing, 1996. Page 192.</ref> The Magic Kingdom's Tomorrowland was completely refurbished and reopened in June 1995.<ref group=CDW3>Building a Dream \u2013 The Art of Disney Architecture, by Beth Dunlop, 1996. Page 192.</ref> Taking up a corner of the Magic Kingdom parking lot, the [[Walt Disney World Speedway]] opened on November 28, 1995.<ref group=CDW3>[https://d23.com/a-to-z/walt-disney-world-speedway/ Walt Disney World Speedway]. Disney A to Z \u2013 The Updated Official Encyclopedia, by Dave Smith, 1998. Page 597.</ref> In 1996, the [[Disney Institute]] opened on February 9,<ref group=CDW3>Birnbaum's Walt Disney World 1997, by Hearst Business Publishing, 1996. Page 181.</ref> and [[Disney's BoardWalk Resort|Disney's BoardWalk]] opened on July 1.<ref group=CDW3>[https://d23.com/a-to-z/boardwalk/ Boardwalk]. Page 62. (1996). Disney A to Z \u2013 The Official Encyclopedia, by Dave Smith.</ref> The first of the [[World of Disney]] stores opened in the Disney Village Marketplace on October 3.<ref group=CDW3>Smith, Dave. [https://d23.com/a-to-z/world-of-disney/ World of Disney]. Page 62. (1999). Disney A to Z \u2013 The Updated Official Encyclopedia.</ref> The Downtown Disney district opened in November 1997, combining Disney Village Marketplace and Pleasure Island.<ref group=CDW3>Disney Magazine, Spring 1998. Page 31.</ref> A fourth theme park, [[Disney's Animal Kingdom]], opened at Disney World the week of April 20, 1998.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lancaster|first1=Cory|title=Animal Kingdom Throws Star-studded Bash|url=http://articles.orlandosentinel.com/1998-04-20/news/9804190408_1_walt-disney-animal-kingdom-disney-theme|accessdate=November 12, 2015|work=Orlando Sentinel|date=April 20, 1998}}</ref>\n\nThe first [[Disney Vacation Club|Disney Vacation Club Resorts]], Vacation Club Resort, opened on October 1, 1991, and was renamed Disney's Old Key West Resort in January 1996. These vacation club hotels were operated by Disney Vacation Developments, Inc. as vacation [[timeshares]].<ref group=CDW2>The Disney Magazine, Spring 1996, Volume 31, Number 2. Page 18.\n*Disney A to Z \u2013 The Updated Official Encyclopedia, by Dave Smith, 1998. Page 584.</ref> The first off-resort vacation club hotel was Vacation Club Resort, which opened on October 1, 1995, in [[Vero Beach, Florida]].<ref group=CDC>[https://d23.com/a-to-z/vacation-club-resort-vero-beach-florida/ \"Vacation Club Resort, Vero Beach, Florida\"]. Page 584. ''Disney A to Z \u2013 The Updated Official Encyclopedia'', by Dave Smith, 1998. Via [http://kpolsson.com/disnehis/disn1994jul.htm Chronology of Walt Disney Company (End of 1994)].</ref>\n\nIn 1993, Premier Cruises discontinued its partnership with Disney for one with [[Warner Bros.]] After failing to reach agreements with [[Carnival Cruise Line|Carnival]] or [[Royal Caribbean International|Royal Caribbean]], Disney announced in 1994 the formation of its cruise line. The [[Disney Cruise Line]] launched with the Disney Magic ship in 1998 along with its exclusive resort island port of Castaway Cay.<ref name=usat2/>\n\nDisney reportedly had plans to build a park named [[Disney's America]]. The park was to have been located in [[Haymarket, Virginia]]; {{convert|2300|acre}} of property were purchased from Exxon in 1993.<ref group=CDC>[http://kpolsson.com/disnehis/disn1993.htm Work in Progress], by Michael Eisner, 1998. Page 321.</ref> The history-themed park was announced on November 11, 1993. The plans for the {{convert|3000|acre}} called for a {{convert|150|acre|adj=on}} amusement park, a campground, a golf course, {{convert|2|e6sqft|m2}} of office/commercial space, and 2500 homes.<ref group=CDC>The New York Times, [http://kpolsson.com/disnehis/disn1993jul.htm November 12, 1993]. Page A14.</ref> With projections indicating that the park would operate at a loss and with opposition in the press, Disney canceled the project on September 15, 1994.<ref group=CDC>''Disney War'', by James Stewart, 2005. Page 190.</ref>\n\n[[Walt Disney Imagineering]] created [[Disney Fair]], a U.S. traveling attraction, which premiered in September 1996. The fair was poorly attended and was pulled after a few stops. Disney Entertainment Projects (Asia Pacific) Inc., a new Disney Asian Pacific subsidiary, selected a renamed fair called DisneyFest as its first project, taking it to Singapore to open there on October 30, 1997.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Matzer|first1=Marla|title=It Didn't Play in Puyallup, so Disney Tries Singapore|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1997/aug/28/business/fi-26586|accessdate=September 23, 2015|work=Los Angeles Times|date=August 28, 1997}}</ref>\n\nIn November 1995, Disney announced the building of [[Tokyo DisneySea]], to be owned by Oriental along with Tokyo Disneyland.<ref name=lat2/> Oriental and Disney signed the DisneySea licensing agreement in November 1997; the theme park was scheduled to open in 2001 at a cost of $2.6 billion.<ref>{{cite news|title=Disney, Partner to Build New Tokyo Theme Park|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1997/nov/27/business/fi-58134|accessdate=August 20, 2015|work=Los Angeles Times|agency=Associated Press|date=November 27, 1997}}</ref>\n\nIn December 1998, Walt Disney Attractions added [[Euro Disney S.C.A.|Disneyland Paris]], Disney Regional Entertainment and [[Walt Disney Imagineering]] to its portfolio, which already held Disney World, Disney Cruise Line, Disneyland, and Tokyo Disneyland. Chairman Dick Nunis retired at the same time.<ref name=\"os3\">{{cite news|last1=Lancaster|first1=Cory|title=Disney's Nunis To Retire|url=http://articles.orlandosentinel.com/1998-12-12/business/9812111396_1_walt-disney-disney-world-disney-imagineering|accessdate=August 20, 2015|work=Orlando Sentinel|date=December 12, 1998}}</ref> On October 31, 1999, Walt Disney Attractions, Inc. was merged into Walt Disney Attractions, LLC.<ref>{{cite web|title=Merger Sheet|url=http://search.sunbiz.org/Inquiry/CorporationSearch/ConvertTiffToPDF?storagePath=COR\\1999\\1105\\00031850.TIF&documentNumber=P25577|website=SunBiz.org|publisher=State of Florida|accessdate=November 17, 2015|format=tif|date=October 28, 1999}}</ref>\n\nOn June 19, 1998, Disney Regional Entertainment opened its first DisneyQuest, a location-based entertainment venue, at Downtown Disney West Side in Walt Disney World.<ref name=ct>{{cite news|last1=Pecho|first1=Bruce|title=Virtual Reality Rules At Disney's Newest Theme Park|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1998-05-31/travel/9805310289_1_virtual-jungle-cruise-disneyquest-virtual-reality|accessdate=April 18, 2016|work=Chicago Tribune|publisher=Tribune Publishing|date=May 31, 1998}}</ref> The first DisneyQuest outside of a resort was opened in Chicago on June 16, 1999, with plans for more locations worldwide.<ref name=\"ct0\">{{cite news|last1=Bigness|first1=Jon|title=Disney's Daring Concept|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1999-06-16/business/9906160311_1_virtual-jungle-cruise-disney-regional-entertainment-disney-theme-park-experience |accessdate=April 18, 2016 |work=Chicago Tribune|publisher=Tribune Publishing|date=June 16, 1999}}</ref>\n\nIn 1999, plans were announced for a new resort in [[Hong Kong]], [[Hong Kong Disneyland]], as a joint venture, Hong Kong International Theme Parks Ltd., between the Hong Kong Government and Disney Resorts.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Chung|first1=Yulanda|title=Making A Magic Kingdom|url=http://www.cnn.com/ASIANOW/asiaweek/magazine/99/1112/cover1.html|accessdate=April 18, 2016|work=Asiaweek|issue=Volume 25, Number 45.|publisher=CNN|date=November 12, 1999}}</ref> The ''[[Disney Wonder]]'' cruise ship began operation on August 15.<ref name=\"usatoday\">{{cite news|last1=Nefer|first1=Barb|title=Disney Cruise Line History|url=http://traveltips.usatoday.com/disney-cruise-line-history-20748.html|accessdate=April 18, 2016|work=USA Today|agency=Demand Media}}</ref> Disney World's [[Discovery Island (Bay Lake)|Discovery Island]] was closed on April 8, 1999.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Hill|first1=Jim|title=Will pirates soon be returning to Treasure ... er ... Discovery Island?|url=http://jimhillmedia.com/editor_in_chief1/b/jim_hill/archive/2008/06/06/will-pirates-soon-be-returning-to-treasure-er-discovery-island.aspx|accessdate=April 13, 2016|work=Jim Hill Media|date=June 5, 2008}}</ref>\n\n===Disney Destinations===\nWalt Disney Attractions, LLC changed its name to Walt Disney Parks and Resorts, LLC on April 14, 2000, then to Disney Destinations, LLC on April 25, 2006.<ref>{{cite web|title=Events: Name History|url=http://search.sunbiz.org/Inquiry/CorporationSearch/NameHistory?aggregateId=flal-l99000007022-1294f8b4-a7e2-4162-b4d2-08fe03fbfb5c&entityId=L99000007022&CurrentPage=0&SearchTerm=Walt%20Disney%20Parks%20and%20Resorts%20Worldwide&InquiryType=EntityName&inquiryDirectionType=CurrentList&SearchNameOrder=WALTDISNEYATTRACTIONS%20L990000070220&ListNameOrder=WALTDIESINGASSOCIATES%20K475700 |website=SunBiz.org|publisher=State of Florida|accessdate=November 17, 2015}}</ref> [[Tokyo DisneySea]] at [[Tokyo Disney Resort]] opened on September 4, 2001.<ref>{{cite news|title=Disney's New Tokyo Sea-Themed Park Opens|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2001/sep/05/business/fi-42280|accessdate=August 20, 2015|work=Los Angeles Times|agency=|date=September 5, 2001|first=Richard|last=Verrier}}</ref> The Walt Disney Company in selling its Japanese and US chains decided to keep the [[Disney Store]]s in Europe, along with the store in Manhattan, which was converted into a [[World of Disney]] store run by Walt Disney Parks and Resorts in 2004.<ref>{{cite news|last1=McGeehan|first1=Patrick|title=For Disney, the Magic on Fifth Avenue Ends|url=http://cityroom.blogs.nytimes.com/2009/09/23/for-disney-the-magic-on-fifth-avenue-ends/comment-page-1/?_r=0|accessdate=November 12, 2015|work=New York Times|date=September 23, 2009}}</ref>\n\n[[Downtown Disney (Disneyland Resort)|Downtown Disney]] opened at the [[Disneyland Resort]] on January 12, 2001, between Disneyland and the future California Adventure. <ref group=CDC>Pages 23,28. [http://kpolsson.com/disnehis/disn2001.htm Disney Magazine]. Fall 2000. Accessed on April 18, 2016.\n*Page 16. Disney Magazine, Winter 2000\u20132001.</ref> [[Disney California Adventure|Disney California Adventure Park]] opened at the [[Disneyland Resort]] on February 8, 2001, with three major areas: Paradise Pier, Hollywood Pictures Backlot, and the Golden State.<ref name=wsj/> In California Adventure on October 6, 2002, A Bug's Land area opened.<ref group=CDC>http://kpolsson.com/disnehis/disn2002.htm Disney Magazine, Spring 2003, Volume 8, Number 2. Page 29.</ref> Parks and Resorts chairman Jay Rasulo announced at Disney's D23 Expo in Anaheim, California on September 12, 2009, that Walt Disney World's Fantasyland would be overhauled and increased in size by 2013.<ref group=CDC>[http://kpolsson.com/disnehis/disn2009.htm Orlando Attractions], Winter 2010. Page 33.  Accessed on April 18, 2016.</ref> A $1 billion expansion/renovation of [[Disney California Adventure|Disney California Adventure Park]] was announced in 2007 to be completed by 2012.<ref name=lat3>{{cite news|last1=MacDonald|first1=Brady|title=Disney California Adventure: How we got here and what's next |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2012/jun/18/news/la-trb-disney-california-adventure-retrospective-06201217 |accessdate=April 19, 2016|work=Los Angeles Times|date=June 18, 2012}}</ref>\n\n[[Disney's River Country|River Country]] water park closed on September 1, 2001.<ref group=CDC>Disney Twenty-three, Fall 2011, Volume 3, Issue 3.</ref><ref>Orlando Attractions, October 2008, Volume 1, Number 6.</ref> Disney-MGM Studios is renamed [[Disney's Hollywood Studios]] in January 2008.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Mervine|first1=Bob|title=Disney-MGM Studios to be renamed|url=http://www.bizjournals.com/orlando/stories/2007/08/06/daily34.html|accessdate=April 19, 2016|work=Orlando Business Journal|publisher=American City Business Journals|date=August 9, 2007}}</ref> [[Pleasure Island (Walt Disney World Resort)|Pleasure Island]]'s core remaining six nightclubs were closed down in late 2008 to change the area to match the family friendly make-up of the other two sections of [[Disney Springs|Downtown Disney]] at Disney World.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Powers|first1=Scott|title=The party's over at Pleasure Island: Disney to shut down 6 nightclubs|url=http://articles.orlandosentinel.com/2008-06-28/news/disney28_1_pleasure-island-downtown-disney-downtown-orlando|accessdate=April 19, 2016|work=Orlando Sentinel|date=June 28, 2008}}</ref>\n\n[[Walt Disney Studios Park]] opened March 16, 2002, as the second theme park at the renamed [[Disneyland Paris|Disneyland Resort Paris]]. The first park was renamed [[Disneyland Park (Paris)|Disneyland Park]] (DLP.<ref group=CDC>[http://kpolsson.com/disnehis/disn2002.htm Disney Magazine]. Winter 2001\u20132002.  Page 22.\n*Disney Magazine, Spring 2002.  Page 28.\n*Disney Magazine, Winter 2002, Volume 8, Number 1.  Page 54.\n*Stewart, James (2005). ''Disney War''. Page 387.\n*Jody Revenson (editor), 2006. Disney Insider Yearbook 2005 Year in Review. Page 81. Accessed on April 19, 2016.</ref> DLP Paris opened in August 2000 [[Toy Story Land|Toy Story Playland]] with three attractions.<ref name=CDC>[http://kpolsson.com/disnehis/disn2009.htm Orlando Attractions], Fall 2010, Volume 3, Number 4. Page 22. Accessed on April 19, 2016.</ref>\n\nConstruction on Hong Kong Disneyland began on January 12, 2003,<ref>Jody Revenson (editor), 2006. ''[http://kpolsson.com/disnehis/disn2003.htm Disney Insider Yearbook 2005 Year in Review]''. Page 69. Accessed on April 19, 2016.</ref> then opened September 12, 2005.<ref group=CDC>[http://kpolsson.com/disnehis/disn2005.htm Disney Magazine], Summer 2005, Volume 10, Number 3.  Page 33. Accessed on April 19, 2016.\n*Jody Revenson (editor), 2006. Disney Insider Yearbook 2005 Year in Review]''. Page 5.</ref> Groundbreaking occurred at Hong Kong Disneyland in December 2009 for a three land expansion: [[Mystic Point]], [[Grizzly Gulch]], and [[Toy Story Land]].<ref group=CDC>[http://kpolsson.com/disnehis/disn2009.htm Orlando Attractions]. Spring 2010, Volume 3, Number 2. Page 61. Accessed on April 19, 2016.</ref>\n\nIn June 2005, Disney Magic made the first cruise outside of the Caribbean, by moving its port for the summer to Los Angeles with a Mexican Riviera schedule.<ref name=\"usatoday\"/> Disney Cruise Line ordered a new 2 ships class from [[Meyer Werft]] shipyard in Germany by February 22, 2007.<ref name=\"usatoday\"/><ref group=CDC>[http://kpolsson.com/disnehis/disn2007.htm Oars & Ears]. December 2006, Volume 7, Number 9. Page 7. Accessed on April 19, 2016.</ref> The Magic in May 2007 transferred its homeport to Barcelona, Spain, for the lines' first summer Mediterranean itinerary then returned to its permanent port in September.<ref name=\"usatoday\"/>\n\nThe Chicago DisneyQuest location was closed in September 2001.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Elder|first1=Robert K.|title=What went wrong at DisneyQuest? |url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2001-07-16/features/0107160127_1_disneyquest-family-entertainment-entertainment-companies |accessdate=April 18, 2016 |work=Chicago Tribune |publisher=Tribune Publishing |date=July 16, 2001}}</ref> Disney Parks started the [[Adventures by Disney]] tour vacation business in 2005.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Ward|first1=Terry |title=Adventures by Disney: Long weekends, Disney-style |url= http://experience.usatoday.com/weekend/story/my-weekend-experience/2015/02/24/adventures-by-disney-weekend-trips/23950735/ |accessdate=April 19, 2016|work=USA Today |date=February 24, 2015 }}</ref> Disney entered a float, \"The Most Magical Celebration on Earth\", into the 2006 Pasadena [[Rose Parade|Tournament of Roses parade]].<ref group=CDC>Jody Revenson (editor), 2006. [http://kpolsson.com/disnehis/disn2006.htm Disney Insider Yearbook 2005 Year in Review]''. Page 5. Accessed on April 19, 2016.</ref>\n\nIn October 2007, Disney announced plans to build a resort at Ko Olina Resort & Marina in [[Kapolei, Hawaii]], featuring both a hotel and Disney Vacation Club timeshare units. The 800-unit property, named [[Aulani]], opened in 2011 and joined the other resorts not associated with a theme park, such as [[Disney's Hilton Head Island Resort]] in South Carolina.<ref>{{cite news | title=Aloha, Disney | url=http://starbulletin.com/2007/10/04/news/story01.html | work=[[Honolulu Star-Bulletin]] | first=Allison | last=Schaefers | date=October 4, 2007 | accessdate=October 6, 2007}}</ref>\n\nWith the Walt Disney World Millennium Celebration starting on October 1, 2000, sanctioned Disney Pin Trading was started.<ref group=CDC>''[http://kpolsson.com/disnehis/disn1999jul.htm Orlando Attractions]''. Volume 2, Number 1. Page 32. December 2008. Accessed on April 18, 2016.</ref><ref group=CDC>''Eyes & Ears''. Volume 29, Number 38. Page 5.  September 23, 1999. Accessed on April 18, 2016.</ref> In 2001, the [[Themed Entertainment Association]] gave Disney Parks and Resorts the Thea Award for Breakthrough Innovation for the park's FastPass system.<ref group=CDC>Strodder, Chris. (2008). ''[http://kpolsson.com/disnehis/disn2001.htm The Disneyland Encyclopedia]''. Page 166. Accessed on April 19, 2016.</ref>\n\n===Walt Disney Parks and Resorts Worldwide===\nWalt Disney Parks and Resorts Worldwide, Inc. was incorporated on September 29, 2008, <ref name=sbz/> and took over the parks and resorts business segment. Disney Parks and Resorts reorganized in early 2009 which included layoffs in all units due to recession-induced falling attendance. 600 U.S. managers in January were buyout packages. Worldwide Operations was formed under President Al Weiss in 2009. Worldwide Operations would take over various back-office functions previously performed by both Disney World and Disneyland including training, procurement, menu planning, and merchandise development. While its Walt Disney Imagineering subsidiary combined its three development units.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Chmielewski |first1=Dawn C. |title=Disney combines theme park functions in prelude to job cuts |url= http://articles.latimes.com/2009/feb/19/business/fi-disney19 |accessdate=September 22, 2015 |work=Los Angeles Times |date=February 19, 2009}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2009, Disney received approval from the Chinese government to build a [[Shanghai Disneyland|Disneyland resort]] in [[Shanghai]]'s [[Pudong]] district.<ref>{{cite web|title=Shanghai Disneyland Project Gets Approval|url=http://www.bernama.com/bernama/v5/newsworld.php?id=452465|accessdate=June 21, 2012}}</ref> The resort opened on June 16, 2016.<ref name=open>{{cite web|last=Smith|first=Thomas|title=Opening Date Set for Shanghai Disney Resort, Disney\u2019s Newest World-Class Destination|url=http://disneyparks.disney.go.com/blog/2016/01/opening-date-set-for-shanghai-disney-resort-disneys-newest-world-classdestination/|publisher=DisneyParks Blog|accessdate=January 14, 2016|date=January 12, 2016}}</ref>\n\nCalifornia Adventure completed its overhaul in 2012 adding two new lands: [[Cars Land]] and [[Buena Vista Street]]. The overhaul also included a re-themed of several attractions plus a pair of classic dark rides.<ref name=lat3/> In July 2017, it was announced that [[Paradise Pier]] land would be replaced by Pixar Pier,<ref>{{cite news |last1=Pimentel |first1=Joseph |title=D23 Expo: Pixar Pier to replace Paradise Pier at Disney California Adventure |url=https://www.ocregister.com/2017/07/15/d23-expo-pixar-pier-to-replace-paradise-pier-at-disney-california-adventure/ |accessdate=March 20, 2020 |work=Orange County Register |date=July 16, 2017}}</ref> with four neighborhoods, and the remainder not in Pixar Pier would be replaced by Paradise Park. Pixar Pier opened on June 23, 2018.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Wisel |first1=Carlye |title=Pixar Pier Is Finally Open at Disney California Adventure \u2014 Here\u2019s What You Can Expect |url=https://www.travelandleisure.com/trip-ideas/disney-vacations/pixar-pier-opening-info-prices |accessdate=March 20, 2020 |work=Travel + Leisure |date=June 22, 2018 |language=EN}}</ref>\n\n[[Star Wars: Galaxy's Edge|''Star Wars'': Galaxy's Edge]], a {{convert|14|acre|ha|adj=on}} themed land for both [[Disneyland]] and [[Disney's Hollywood Studios]] announced at the [[D23 (Disney)|D23 Expo]] on August 15, 2015.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Pedicini|first1=Sandra |url=http://www.orlandosentinel.com/travel/attractions/the-daily-disney/os-star-wars-disney-hollywood-studios-20150815-story.html|title=Star Wars land coming to Disney's Hollywood Studios|date=August 15, 2015|work=Orlando Sentinel}}</ref> Construction began at both locations on April 14, 2016.<ref name=conbegin>{{cite news|last1=Parker|first1=Ryan|title=Disney Breaks Ground on 'Star Wars' Land in California and Florida|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/disneys-star-wars-land-photos-883997|accessdate=April 14, 2016|work=The Hollywood Reporter|date=April 14, 2016}}</ref> The lands at both parks opened in 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://disneyparks.disney.go.com/blog/2018/05/opening-season-just-announced-for-star-wars-galaxys-edge/|title=Opening Season Just Announced for Star Wars: Galaxy\u2019s Edge|work=Disney Parks Blog|publisher=The Walt Disney Company|accessdate=June 15, 2018|date=May 22, 2018|first=Scott|last=Trowbridge|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe New Fantasyland at Magic Kingdom opened on December 6, 2012. It is the biggest upgrade to the theme park since its opening in 1971.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Sekula|first1=Sarah|title=Disney brings more oomph with New Fantasyland|url=http://www.cnn.com/2012/12/05/travel/disney-new-fantasyland/|accessdate=April 20, 2016|work=CNN.com|publisher=Turner Broadcasting System, Inc.|date=December 10, 2012}}</ref> Announced along with its new Star Wars Land expansion at the D23 Expo on August 15, 2015, Hollywood Studios was slated to have a version of [[Toy Story Land]].<ref>{{cite news| last1=Kubersky|first1=Seth|title=Updated Toy Story Land concept art unveiled at Disney\u2019s Hollywood Studios|url=http://attractionsmagazine.com/updated-toy-story-land-concept-art-unveiled-disneys-hollywood-studios/ | accessdate=April 20, 2016|work=Attractions Magazine|publisher=Dream Together Media, LLC|date=April 4, 2016}}</ref>\n\nHolz became president of New Vacation Operations of Parks & Resorts<ref name=os4>{{cite news|url=http://articles.orlandosentinel.com/2009-02-14/news/dizcruise14_1_disney-cruise-line-disney-declined-mcalpin|title=Familiar face takes Disney Cruise Line helm: Karl Holz|last1=Garcia|first1=Jason|date=February 14, 2009|newspaper=Orlando Sentinel|accessdate=April 9, 2017}}</ref> reporting to [[Al Weiss]], president of worldwide operations for Walt Disney Parks and Resorts.<ref name=os5>{{cite news|last1=Garcia|first1=Jason|title=Disney executive changes: Head of Disney's theme parks makes executive changes|url=http://articles.orlandosentinel.com/2011-07-05/the-daily-disney/os-disney-executive-changes-20110705_1_al-weiss-crofton-resorts-chairman-tom-staggs|accessdate=April 13, 2017|work=Orlando Sentinel|date=July 5, 2011|language=en}}</ref> by April 2008.<ref>{{cite press release | author       = <!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> | title  = Philippe Gas to Assume Top Duties at Euro Disney  | url = http://corporate.disneylandparis.com/CORP/EN/Neutral/Images/uk-2008-04-10-nomination-philippe-gas.pdf | format = PDF | location     =Marne-la-Vall\u00e9e  | publisher    =Euro Disney S.C.A. | date = April 11, 2008 | access-date  = April 14, 2016}}</ref> In February 2009, Holz returned to the presidency of Disney Cruise Line in addition to his continuing as head of New Vacation Operations,<ref name=os4/> which was primarily [[Adventures by Disney]]. As an extension of the \"One Disney\" initiative and the resignation of Weiss, Disney Vacation Club was added to New Vacation Operations. While Holz and Meg Crofton joined Disney Parks and Resorts executive committee in July 2011. At that time, Crofton was transferred from Disney World president to president of operations in the U.S. and France, a new positions.<ref name=os5/>\n\nThe ''Disney Dream'' began service in January 2011 and [[Disney Cruise Line]] (DCL) announced the maiden voyage of the ''[[Disney Fantasy]]'' to be March 31, 2012. The Dream deployment allowed Disney Wonder to be permanently stationed at Port of Los Angeles for Mexican Riviera cruises,<ref>{{cite news|last1=Garcia|first1=Jason|title=Disney sets maiden voyage for new cruise ship|url=http://articles.orlandosentinel.com/2010-10-18/the-daily-disney/os-new-disney-cruise-ship-20101018_1_disney-magic-disney-cruise-line-disney-dream|accessdate=April 20, 2016|work=Orlando Sentinel|date=October 18, 2010}}</ref> but initial served in the short Alaska cruise season.<ref name=\"usat2\" /> Magic moved to New York for Canadian or Bahama cruises starting May 25, 2012.<ref group=CDC>[http://kpolsson.com/disnehis/disn2009.htm Cruise Travel]. July 2011, Volume 33, Number 1. Page 36.</ref> DCL's Magic was refitted in late 2013.<ref>{{cite news|title=Major Refit Planned for Disney Magic|url=https://www.cruiseindustrynews.com/cruise-news/9130-major-refit-planned-for-disney-magic.html|accessdate=April 20, 2016|work=Cruise Industry News|date=April 26, 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe first of three expansion theme lands at Hong Kong Disneyland, [[Toy Story Land]], opened on November 18, 2011.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Li|first1=Zoe|title=Toy Story Land hopes to save Hong Kong Disney|url=http://travel.cnn.com/hong-kong/visit/how-toy-story-land-hopes-save-hong-kong-disney-081206/|accessdate=April 20, 2016|work=CNN.com|publisher=Turner Broadcasting System, Inc.|date=November 21, 2011}}</ref> [[Grizzly Gulch]] opened at Hong Kong Disneyland on July 13, 2012.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Guinigundo|first1=Andy|title=Out of the Loop: Hong Kong Disneyland debuts Grizzly Gulchf|url=http://attractionsmagazine.com/out-of-the-loop-hong-kong-disneyland-debuts-grizzly-gulch/|accessdate=April 20, 2016|work=Attractions Magazine|publisher=Dream Together Media, LLC.|date=July 31, 2012}}</ref> The final land of this expansion, [[Mystic Point]], opened at Hong Kong Disneyland on May 17, 2013.<ref>{{cite news|title=Hong Kong Disneyland's Mystic Point opens May 17|url=http://www.ttgasia.com/article.php?article_id=20853|accessdate=April 20, 2016|work=TTG Asia|date=April 19, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160509033627/http://www.ttgasia.com/article.php?article_id=20853|archive-date=May 9, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nOn February 5, 2015, it was announced that [[Thomas O. Staggs|Tom Staggs]] had been promoted to Disney Company [[Chief operating officer]] but would continue as chairman of Parks and Resorts until his successor was named.<ref>{{cite web| last1=Littleton |first1=Cynthia |title=Disney Promotes Tom Staggs to No. 2 Post, Positioning Him as Iger\u2019s Successor |url=https://variety.com/2015/biz/news/disney-promotes-tom-staggs-to-no-2-post-positioning-him-as-igers-successor-1201423601/|website=Variety.com|publisher=Variety Magazine|accessdate=February 5, 2015}}</ref> On February 23, 2015, [[Bob Chapek|Robert Chapek]] was named chairman of Walt Disney Parks and Resorts effective that day.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Barnes|first1=Brooks|title=Disney Names Robert Chapek Chairman for Theme Parks|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/02/24/business/media/disney-names-robert-chapek-chairman-for-theme-parks.html?_r=0|accessdate=February 26, 2015|work=New York Times|date=February 23, 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn April 29, 2015, The Walt Disney Company, through the subsidiary, Carousel Holdings Eat LLC, has purchased Carousel Inn & Suites hotel in Anaheim, from Good Hope International for $32 million. The purchase was considered a strategic purchase; the hotel would not be considered a part of the Disneyland hotel portfolio and would operate independently.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Pimentel|first1=Joseph|title=Disney purchases Carousel Inn for $32 million |url=http://www.ocregister.com/articles/disney-659941-hotel-inn.html|website=OCRegister.com|publisher=The Orange County Register|date=April 29, 2015}}</ref> Disney indicted in August 2016, that the company would be closing the Carousel Inn in October 2016 in preparation for razing it as part of plans to construct a new parking structure, transit plaza and pedestrian bridge over Harbor Boulevard.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Pimentel|first1=Joseph|title=Q&amp;A Disneyland's massive parking project|url=http://www.ocregister.com/articles/disney-725945-harbor-bridge.html|website=OCRegister.com|publisher=The Orange County Register|date=August 16, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn February 10, 2017, Disney revealed a deal to purchase [[Kingdom Holding]] Co.'s shares of [[Euro Disney S.C.A.]] as the first step in purchasing the remaining shares held by others. Disney has offered about $2.12 a share, a 67% premium over the Euronext Paris Stock Exchange value as of February 9. The company expects the buyout and delisting to be finished by June. Plans are for the company to invest another $1.4 billion into Disneyland Paris after the buyout to counteract the recent [[November 2015 Paris attacks|Paris terrorist attack]], which hurt a previous 2014 park hotel investment. If this buyout is successful, it would make the resort the only resort 100% owned and operated by Disney outside of the United States of America.<ref name=\"vty\">{{cite news|last1=Littleton|first1=Cynthia|title=Disney Seeks Full Ownership of Disneyland Paris|url=https://variety.com/2017/biz/news/disneyland-paris-disney-buyout-terrorist-attack-1201984089/|accessdate=February 16, 2017|work=Variety|date=February 10, 2017}}</ref> On June 13, 2017, The Walt Disney Company reached the 95% threshold required for a mandatory takeover according to French law, owning 97.08% of Euro Disney S.C.A., paving the way for The Walt Disney Company to become the sole owner and operator of Disneyland Paris.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.marketwatch.com/story/final-results-of-the-simplified-public-tender-offer-on-euro-disney-sca-the-walt-disney-company-to-implement-a-mandatory-buy-out-and-delisting-2017-06-13-102035936|title=Final results of the simplified public tender offer on Euro Disney S.C.A. The Walt Disney Company to implement a mandatory buy-out and delisting|work=MarketWatch|access-date=2017-06-13|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n===Disney Parks, Experiences and Products===\nAs part of [[The Walt Disney Company]]\u2019s March 2018 strategic reorganization, Disney Consumer Products, and Interactive Media was merged into the Walt Disney Parks and Resorts segment and renamed Walt Disney Parks, Experiences and Products. Parks and Resorts Chairman Bob Chapek was named chairman of this new segment, who also previously served as head of Disney Consumer Products.<ref name=cnbc>{{cite news|last1=Wang|first1=Christine|title=Disney announces strategic reorganization, effective immediately|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2018/03/14/disney-announces-strategic-reorganization-effective-immediately.html|accessdate=March 14, 2018|work=CNBC|date=March 14, 2018}}</ref> At the time, the Consumer Products chairman position was vacant, as its former holder, James Pitaro, had been recently appointed as the new head of [[ESPN Inc.|ESPN]] and co-chair of [[Disney Media Networks]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Barnes|first1=Brooks|title=Disney Reorganization Anticipates 21st Century Fox Assets|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/03/14/business/media/walt-disney-21st-century-fox.html|accessdate=March 14, 2018|work=The New York Times|date=March 14, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2018, a Disney Parks West regional division was formed with Disneyland Resort in California, Walt Disney World in Florida, and Disneyland Paris under Catherine Powell, outgoing Disneyland Paris president. This mirrors the Disney Parks East regional division consisting of Shanghai Disney Resort, Hong Kong Disneyland and Walt Disney Attractions Japan and headed by Michael Colglazier. Imagineering was expected to take on the development of merchandise, games, publishing, and apps. Paul Gainer moved up from Disney Retail head to head up the new Global Product Management and Distribution unit, which includes Disney Retail, Global Licensing, and digital guest experience.<ref>{{cite news |title=Imagineering Sees Big Growth as \"Parks, Experiences, and Consumer Products\" Announces Structure |url=https://www.laughingplace.com/w/news/2018/03/21/imagineering-sees-big-growth-parks-experiences-consumer-products-announces-structure/ |accessdate=June 18, 2018 |work=LaughingPlace.com |date=March 21, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Catherine Powell steps into new Disney role |url=http://www.parkworld-online.com/catherine-powell-steps-into-new-disney-role/ |accessdate=June 18, 2018 |work=Park World |date=March 29, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Disney Unveils Solo: A Star Wars Story Merch |url=https://www.licenseglobal.com/movies/disney-unveils-solo-star-wars-story-merch |accessdate=December 13, 2018 |work=License Global |publisher=UBM Americas |date=April 9, 2018 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nKen Potrock was promoted from Senior Vice President and General Manager of Disney Vacation Club to President of Consumer Products in May 2018.<ref>{{cite web |title=Ken Potrock profile |url=https://dpecp.disney.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/leadership_ken_potrock_121118.pdf |website=dpecp.disney.com |publisher=The Walt Disney Company |accessdate=13 December 2018 |format=PDF}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=The Walt Disney Company appoints new Head of Consumer Products Commercialization |url=https://www.retailnews.asia/the-walt-disney-company-appoints-new-head-of-consumer-products-commercialization/ |accessdate=December 13, 2018 |work=Retail News Asia |publisher=Mojju |date=November 27, 2018}}</ref> New Vacation Operations and Disney Cruise Line division was renamed Disney Signature Experiences along with a new president, Jeff Vahle, for the division in April 2018.<ref name=\"os6\">{{cite news|last1=Tribou|first1=Richard|title=New president named for Disney Cruise Line, Vacation Club and more|url=http://www.orlandosentinel.com/travel/attractions/the-daily-disney/os-disney-cruise-line-president-jeff-vahle-20180420-story.html|accessdate=April 30, 2018|work=Orlando Sentinel|date=April 20, 2018}}</ref> On January 1, 2019, Walt Disney Parks, Experiences and Consumer Products changed its name to Disney Parks, Experiences and Products.<ref>{{cite web |series=Detail by Entity Name |url=http://search.sunbiz.org/Inquiry/CorporationSearch/ConvertTiffToPDF?storagePath=COR%5C2019%5C0211%5C24080356.Tif&documentNumber=F09000001204 |title=Certificate of Amendment of the Articles of Incorporation of Disney Parks, Experiences and Consumer Products |website=Sunbiz.org |publisher=State of Florida |accessdate=October 10, 2018 |language=en}}</ref> Disney Cruise Line purchase in early March 2019 another Bahamas destination, Lighthouse Point property on the island of Eleuthera.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Tribou |first1=Richard |title=Disney Cruise Line completes land purchase, enters agreement for second Bahamas destination |url=https://www.orlandosentinel.com/travel/attractions/the-daily-disney/os-ae-disney-cruise-line-lighthouse-point-bahamas-update-20190311-story.html |accessdate=March 12, 2019 |work=Orlando Sentinel |date=March 11, 2019}}</ref> In July 2019, Disney denied reports of plans to launch its own airline with the purchase of small regional airlines in the United States.<ref name=\"Stuff\">{{cite news |title=Disney denies any plans to launch airline in the US |url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/travel/news/114417532/disney-to-launch-airline-in-the-us-reports |accessdate=July 31, 2019 |work=Stuff |date=July 22, 2019 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Elliott |first1=Annabel Fenwick |title=Disney denies rumours of US airline launch |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/travel/news/disney-to-launch-us-airline-cabin-crew-in-costume/ |accessdate=July 31, 2019 |work=The Telegraph |date=July 22, 2019}}</ref>\n\nPowell supervised the two Star Wars-themed land, [[Star Wars: Galaxy's Edge]], openings in May at Disneyland and August 2019 in Disney's Hollywood Studios. However, initial numbers showed an attendance dropped instead of the boost such an opening should have generated. In late September, Powell left the company with the Parks West regional division being dissolved, thus having those resorts' executives directly report to chairman Chapek.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Palmeri |first1=Christopher |title=Disney\u2019s U.S. Parks Chief Leaves After 15 Years With Company |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-09-23/disney-s-u-s-parks-chief-leaves-after-15-years-with-company |accessdate=September 25, 2019 |work=Bloomberg.com |date=September 23, 2019}}</ref> He denied that Powell was let go because of the low attendance issue from Galaxy's Edge, but instead, Powell's position was a temporary one to allow Chapek to focus on the [[Acquisition of 21st Century Fox by Disney|acquisition of 21st Century Fox]].<ref name=\"cnbcLeadership\">{{cite news|last1=Whitten|first1=Sarah|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/09/25/disney-names-new-leadership-for-disneyland-and-walt-disney-world.html|title=Disney names new leadership for Disneyland and Walt Disney World|date=September 25, 2019|work=CNBC|accessdate=September 30, 2019|language=en}}</ref>\n\nPowell's departure from Disney was soon followed by a domino of executive appointments, as announced on September 26, 2019.<ref name=\"cnbcLeadership\"/> George Kalogridis, then-president of the Walt Disney World Resort, was promoted as the president of segment development and enrichment. Kalogridis is replaced by Josh D'Amaro, then-president of the Disneyland Resort, as president of the Walt Disney World Resort. In turn, D'Amaro was replaced by Rebecca Campbell as president of the Disneyland Resort. Campbell transferred from the [[Walt Disney Direct-to-Consumer & International]] segment where she served as the president of Europe, the Middle East, and Africa. Both D'Amaro and Campbell assumed these roles in November 2019. In addition, Michael Colglazier is also promoted as the president and managing director of Disney Parks International and will oversee Disneyland Paris as well as those under the Parks East regional division.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.apnews.com/e70a439b2f2046a78aebdd2c72e87d67|title=Shake-up in the leadership of Disney theme park resorts|date=September 25, 2019|work=AP News|accessdate=September 30, 2019}}</ref> In February 2020, Chapek was promoted from Chairman of this segment to chief executive officer of the Walt Disney Company under executive chairman Bob Iger.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Littleton |first1=Cynthia |title=Bob Chapek to Succeed Bob Iger as Disney CEO |url=https://variety.com/2020/biz/news/bob-chapek-bob-iger-disney-ceo-succeed-1203515498/ |accessdate=February 26, 2020 |work=Variety |date=February 25, 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nWith the closure of all Disney parks in 2020 during the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|coronavirus pandemic]], Disney donated 150,000 rain ponchos usually sold at the parks to [[MedShare]], to be distributed in hospitals. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.parents.com/syndication/disney-parks-donates-150000-rain-ponchos-to-hospitals-and-medical-professionals/|title=Disney Parks Donates 150,000 Rain Ponchos to Hospitals and Medical Professionals|website=Parents|language=EN|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n\n==Disney resorts==\n{{See also| List of Disney theme park attractions}}\n{{location map+|Earth\n|float=center\n|width=775\n|caption=Locations of Disney resorts \u2014 [[File:Red pog.svg|8px]] International [[File:Blue pog.svg|8px]] US (direct reports)\n|places=\n{{Location map~|Earth|position=top|lat=31.144|long=121.657|label='''[[Shanghai Disney Resort]]''' |mark=Red pog.svg\n}}\n{{Location map~|Earth|position=bottom|lat=22.313333|long=114.043333|label='''[[Hong Kong Disneyland Resort]]''' |mark=Red pog.svg\n}}\n{{Location map~|Earth|position=right|lat=48.868719|long=2.7818|label='''[[Disneyland Paris]]''' |mark=Red pog.svg\n}}\n{{Location map~|Earth|position=right|lat=35.629722|long=139.882778|label='''[[Tokyo Disney Resort]]''' |mark=Red pog.svg\n}}\n{{Location map~|Earth|position=right|lat=28.418611|long=-81.581111|label='''[[Walt Disney World]]''' |mark=blue pog.svg\n}}\n{{Location map~|Earth|position=left|lat=33.8091|long=-117.919|label='''[[Disneyland Resort]]''' |mark=blue pog.svg\n}}\n}}\n===Disneyland Resort===\n{{Main|Disneyland Resort}}\n[[Disneyland]] was founded as a single park by [[Walt Disney]] and opened on July 17, 1955, in [[Anaheim, California]]. [[Disneyland Hotel (California)|Disneyland Hotel]] opened to the public on October 5, 1955. In 2001, the site expanded significantly and was renamed the Disneyland Resort with the opening of [[Disney California Adventure|Disney California Adventure Park]] on February 8, 2001, [[Disney's Grand Californian Hotel & Spa]] on January 2, 2001, [[Disney's Paradise Pier Hotel]] on December 15, 2000, and [[Downtown Disney (Disneyland Resort)|Downtown Disney]] on January 12, 2001. Disneyland was re-branded Disneyland Park to distinguish it from the larger resort complex. The resort focuses on [[Mickey Mouse]] and other Disney characters and occupies {{convert|500|acre|km2}}.\n\n===Walt Disney World===\n{{Main|Walt Disney World}}\nThe Walt Disney World resort opened October 1, 1971, in [[Lake Buena Vista, Florida]], with the [[Magic Kingdom]] theme park and three resort hotels. It expanded with the opening of [[Epcot]] in 1982, Disney-MGM Studios (now [[Disney's Hollywood Studios]]) and [[Disney's Typhoon Lagoon]] in 1989, [[Disney's Blizzard Beach]] in 1995, [[Disney's Animal Kingdom]] in 1998, [[Disney Springs]] retail, dining, and entertainment complex, eight golf courses, and 18 new resort hotels. The resort is the largest (by area) and most-visited vacation resort in the world, with four theme parks, two water parks, a shopping, dining, and entertainment complex, 21 resort hotels, eight golf courses, and several additional recreational activities, and covers 27,258 acres.\n\nOther venues:\n* [[ESPN Wide World of Sports Complex]]\n\n===Tokyo Disney Resort===\n{{Main|Tokyo Disney Resort}}\n'''Tokyo Disney Resort''', in [[Urayasu, Chiba]], Japan, opened April 15, 1983, as [[Tokyo Disneyland]]. On September 4, 2001, the resort expanded with [[Tokyo DisneySea]]. There are several resort hotels on-site, but only three are owned by the resort, which boasts the largest parking structure in the world. Designed by [[Walt Disney Imagineering]], the resort is fully owned and operated by [[The Oriental Land Company]] and licensed by The Walt Disney Company. The Walt Disney Attractions Japan team at The Walt Disney Company communicates with the Oriental Land Company over all aspects of the resort and assigns Imagineers to it. Its properties, below, are divided into parks, shopping centers, and lodging.\n\n*Shopping, dining, and entertainment complex: [[Ikspiari]]\n\n{{-}}\n\n===Disneyland Paris===\n{{Main|Disneyland Paris}}\n'''Disneyland Paris''', Disney's second international resort complex, and the largest Disney resort outside the United States, opened on April 12, 1992, as '''Euro Disney Resort'''. Located in [[Marne-la-Vall\u00e9e]] in the suburbs of Paris, France, it features two theme parks, a golf course, an entertainment complex, and seven Disney resort hotels. It is the only resort outside the United States fully owned and operated by [[The Walt Disney Company]].<ref name=\"vty\" /> Its properties, listed below, occupy {{convert|4940|acre|km2}} and are divided into parks and shopping centers.\n\n===Hong Kong Disneyland Resort===\n{{Main|Hong Kong Disneyland Resort}}\n'''Hong Kong Disneyland Resort''', Disney's fifth resort and its second in Asia, opened September 12, 2005. The resort is located in [[Penny's Bay]], [[Lantau Island]], Hong Kong. The resort consists of [[Hong Kong Disneyland]] theme park, [[Inspiration Lake Recreation Centre]], and three hotels, with land reserved for future expansion. It is owned and operated by [[Hong Kong International Theme Parks]], an incorporated company jointly owned by [[The Walt Disney Company]] and the [[Government of Hong Kong]]. The first phase of Hong Kong Disneyland Resort occupies {{convert|320|acre|km2}}.\n\n===Shanghai Disney Resort===\n{{Main|Shanghai Disney Resort}}\nIn November 2009, Disney received approval from the central government of China to build a Disney theme park, [[Shanghai Disneyland Park]], in [[Shanghai]]'s [[Pudong]] district. \"China is one of the most dynamic, exciting and important countries in the world and this approval marks a very significant milestone for Walt Disney Co in mainland China,\" said Robert Iger, president and CEO of Disney.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.reuters.com/article/rbssTechMediaTelecomNews/idUSN0352328120091104 | work=Reuters | title=UPDATE 4-Disney takes China stride as Shanghai park gets nod | date=November 4, 2009}}</ref> The resort opened on June 16, 2016.<ref name=open/> A groundbreaking ceremony took place on April 7, 2011.<ref name=\"skydisneychina\">{{cite news| url=http://news.sky.com/skynews/Home/Business/Disneyland-China-Disney-Agrees-A-Deal-To-Open-Amusement-Park-In-Shanghai/Article/201011115795782?f=rss | work=Sky News | title=Disney To Bring Magic Kingdom To Shanghai | date=November 5, 2010 | accessdate=November 5, 2010}}\n</ref>\n*Shopping, dining, and entertainment complex: [[Disneytown]]\n\n==Training==\nEach new employee (\"cast member\") at a Disney theme park is trained at a Disney University, founded by Walt Disney in 1955. Before training specific to the work they will perform, each employee attends the \"Disney Traditions\" course where they learn about the philosophies and history of Disney's guest services.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Yearout|first1=Steve|last2=Weil|first2=Gerry Miles, with Richard Koonce ; foreword by Audrey|title=Growing leaders : a leader-builder handbook for HRD and training professionals, business executives and managers, executive coaches|date=2001|publisher=ASTD|location=Alexandria, VA|isbn=1562862898|page=[https://archive.org/details/growingleadersle0000year/page/193 193]|url=https://archive.org/details/growingleadersle0000year/page/193}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Lipp|first1=Doug|title=Disney U : how Disney University develops the world's most engaged, loyal, and customer-centric employees|date=2013|publisher=McGraw-Hill|location=New York|isbn=0071808078}}</ref>\n\n==Abandoned and misreported concepts==\n{{Main| List of Disney attractions that were never built}}\nDisney had plans to build [[Walt Disney's Riverfront Square]] in [[St. Louis]], but canceled the project in July 1965.\n\nIn the 1960s, Disney initiated a plan for a ski resort at [[Mineral King]] in California. Opposition from environmental groups led by the [[Sierra Club]] led to a temporary court injunction in 1969 and legal battles through the 1970s. The project's planning and scale changed multiple times, and in 1978, Mineral King was annexed into [[Sequoia National Park]], ending any possibility of developing a resort there.<ref name=\"ski\">{{cite book|title=Challenge of the Big Trees|last=Dilsaver|first=L.M.|author2=Tweed, W.C. |chapter=New Directions and a Second Century (1972\u20131990)|year=1990|publisher=Sequoia Natural History Association |chapterurl= http://www.nps.gov/history/history/online_books/dilsaver-tweed/chap9c.htm}}</ref>\n\nDisney had plans to build a park named [[Disney's America]] in [[Haymarket, Virginia]], but abandoned the idea in 1994. On September 28, 1994, [[Michael Eisner]] announced Disney was canceling its plans after a bruising national media fight with Protect Historic America, and aggressive local opposition in Virginia from Protect Prince William and other citizen groups.\n\nDisney had plans to build a smaller Disneyland-style theme park in Sydney, Australia, between 2007 and 2008, with the proposed name \"Disney Wharf at Sydney Harbour\", but the concept was abandoned due to mixed responses in the [[Government of New South Wales|New South Wales Government]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.smh.com.au/nsw/walt-disney-company-proposed-a-disney-resort-in-sydney-20140111-30nfk.html|title=Walt Disney Company proposed a Disney Resort in Sydney|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|accessdate=October 4, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn early January 2011, conflicting reports emerged regarding Disney's involvement in a proposed entertainment complex in Haifa, Israel, whose plans include a small (30,000 square meter) amusement park scheduled to open in 2013. The project will be partially funded by [[Shamrock Holdings]], a Disney-affiliated investment firm. In the wake of reports from Israeli business newspaper, ''[[Globes]]'' and industry newswire ''Amusement Management'' that Disney itself would be involved in the project's development, a spokesperson for Walt Disney Parks and Resorts clarified to ''[[Fast Company (magazine)|Fast Company]]'' that Disney did not have any plans to be involved in the building of the park.<ref>Ungerleider, Neal. [http://www.fastcompany.com/1714452/disney-to-open-theme-park-in-israel \"Disney to Open Theme Park in Israel?\"] ''Fast Company''. January 5, 2011.</ref>\n\n==Disney intellectual properties outside Disney parks==\nDue to its acquisitions of [[Marvel Entertainment]] in 2009, [[Lucasfilm]] in 2012 and [[20th Century Studios ]] in 2019, some Disney-owned franchises are represented in its competitors' parks.\n\n===[[Marvel Entertainment]]===\n[[Marvel Super Hero Island]], a themed land featuring characters and settings from [[Marvel Comics]], has operated at [[Universal Orlando]] Resort's [[Islands of Adventure]] park since 1999, as well as the Islands of Adventure, cloned ride ''[[The Amazing Adventures of Spider-Man]]'' at [[Universal Studios Japan]] since 2004. Under Marvel's 1994 agreement with [[Universal Parks & Resorts]] in regional terms, none of the Marvel characters and other persons related to such characters (e.g., side characters, team members, and the villains associated with the [[Avengers (comics)|Avengers]], [[Fantastic Four]], [[X-Men]], [[Spider-Man]], etc.) connected with Islands of Adventure and Universal Studios Japan can be used at Walt Disney World and Tokyo Disney Resort.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Munarriz|first1=Rick|title=Disney is Taking Too Long to Add Marvel to Disneyland and Disney World|url=http://www.fool.com/investing/general/2015/10/18/disney-is-taking-too-long-to-add-marvel-to-disney.aspx|website=The Motley Fool|accessdate=January 17, 2016}}</ref> The [[Disneyland Resort]], Walt Disney World Resort, and Tokyo Disney Resort also cannot use the Marvel brand name as part of an attraction or marketing and the Marvel-themed [[simulator ride]].<ref name=\"Marvel Contract\">{{cite web|url=https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1262449/000119312510008732/dex1057.htm|title=Marvel Agreement between MCA Inc. and Marvel Entertainment Group|publisher=[[U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission]]|website=sec.gov}}</ref> This clause has allowed Walt Disney World to have meet-and-greets with Marvel characters not associated with the ones present at Islands of Adventure, such as [[Star-Lord]] and [[Gamora]] from ''[[Guardians of the Galaxy (film)|Guardians of the Galaxy]],''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.insidethemagic.net/2014/08/guardians-of-the-galaxy-theme-park-characters-appear-for-first-time-as-walt-disney-world-welcomes-marvel/|title=Guardians of the Galaxy theme park characters appear for the first time as Walt Disney World welcomes Marvel|work=Inside the Magic}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://disneyparks.disney.go.com/blog/2014/07/exclusive-guardians-of-the-galaxy-sneak-peek-debuts-july-4-at-disney-parks/|title=Exclusive \u2018Guardians of the Galaxy\u2019 Sneak Peek Debuts July 4 at Disney Parks|work=Disney Parks Blog}}</ref> and [[Doctor Strange]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.themeparkinsider.com/flume/201611/5319/|title=Walt Disney World news update: Doctor Strange, new castle show debut|last=Niles|first=Robert|date=November 5, 2016|website=Theme Park Insider|access-date=August 22, 2019}}</ref> Hong Kong Disneyland, Shanghai Disneyland, and Disneyland Paris either have or planned to incorporate meet and greets as well as attractions relating to the Marvel characters, as well as using the Marvel name and the Marvel simulator ride.\n\n[[IMG Worlds of Adventure]] in [[Dubai]] has a Marvel-themed section.<ref>https://www.imgworlds.com/language/en/#</ref>\n\n===''[[Star Wars]]''===\nA ''[[Star Wars]]''-themed section of [[Legoland California]]'s [[Legoland California#Miniland USA|Miniland USA]] opened in 2011, with a similar version opening at [[Legoland Florida]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://florida.legoland.com/map-explore/land-views/miniland/attractions/lego-star-wars/|title=LEGO\u00ae STAR WARS\u2122|publisher=}}</ref> in November 2012, just weeks before Disney's acquisition of Lucasfilm and the ''Star Wars'' franchise. However, the ''Star Wars''-themed sections at Miniland USA, Legoland Florida, and other Legoland areas will close at the start of 2020 before the 2020 theme park season due to the expiration of their contract with [[Lucasfilm]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.orlandoweekly.com/Blogs/archives/2019/12/15/as-disney-opens-its-new-star-wars-land-in-orlando-another-local-theme-park-says-goodbye|title=As Disney opens its new Star Wars land in Orlando, another local theme park says goodbye|newspaper=Orlando Weekly |access-date=December 15, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===[[20th Century Studios]]===\nFollowing Disney's [[Acquisition of 21st Century Fox by Disney|acquisition of 21st Century Fox]] in March 2019, ''[[The Simpsons (franchise)|The Simpsons]]'' became the intellectual property of Disney. Like Marvel before it, ''The Simpsons'' is represented in Universal parks, with [[The Simpsons Ride]] having operated at [[Universal Studios Hollywood]] and [[Universal Studios Florida]] since 2008, with accompanying themed areas based on the show's setting of [[Springfield (The Simpsons)|Springfield]].\n\nThe Fox acquisition also made Disney responsible for the future of [[Malaysia]]'s under-construction [[20th Century Fox World (Malaysia)|20th Century Fox World]] theme park. The park's owner, [[Genting Group]], filed suit against The Walt Disney Company and 21st Century Fox in November 2018, accusing Fox of trying to back out of the deal for licensing the theme park. In the suit, Genting Malaysia alleges that Fox has taken steps to cancel the contract. The suit also names Disney as a defendant, contending that Disney executives, following the company's [[Acquisition of 21st Century Fox by Disney|then-pending acquisition of Fox]], were \"calling the shots\" on the project and that they were opposed to the park because they would have \"no control\" over its operations and that it would be adjacent to a casino, which would go against Disney's \"family-friendly\" image.<ref name=\"Disney, Fox sued in U.S. for $1 billion over Malaysia theme park\">{{cite web |title=Disney, Fox sued in U.S. for $1 billion over Malaysia theme park |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-fox-disney-genting-malaysia/disney-fox-sued-in-us-for-1-billion-over-malaysia-theme-park-idUSKCN1NV2NP |website=Reuters |publisher=Reuters |accessdate=November 27, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181127151956/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-fox-disney-genting-malaysia/disney-fox-sued-in-us-for-1-billion-over-malaysia-theme-park-idUSKCN1NV2NP |archive-date=27 November 2018 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Fox, in turn, referred to the suit as \"without merit\", stating that their reasons for withdrawing from the deal were due to Genting consistently not meeting \"agreed-upon deadlines for several years\" and that Genting's attempts to blame Disney for Fox's default were \"made up\".<ref name=\"Deadline\">{{cite news|url=https://deadline.com/2018/11/disney-fox-lawsuit-kuala-lumpur-theme-park-deal-off-1202509020/|title=Disney & Fox Accused In $1.75B Suit Of Taking Theme Park Developer For A Ride|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=November 26, 2018|accessdate=November 27, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181128012047/https://deadline.com/2018/11/disney-fox-lawsuit-kuala-lumpur-theme-park-deal-off-1202509020/|archive-date=28 November 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In July 2019, it was announced that Fox and Genting had settled their lawsuits. As part of the deal, Genting would be given \"a license to use certain Fox intellectual properties\" and that non-Fox intellectual property would make up the rest of the attractions in the park. The outdoor park would also no longer be referred to as 20th Century Fox World, but instead would be given a new name at an unspecified time.<ref name=\"Legal Fight Over Fox Theme Park In Malaysia Ends In Settlement\">{{cite web |title=Legal Fight Over Fox Theme Park In Malaysia Ends In Settlement |url=https://deadline.com/2019/07/fox-world-malaysia-theme-park-settlement-legal-1202654605/ |website=Deadline.com |publisher=Deadline Hollywood |accessdate=July 26, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Adaptations==\nWhile Disney Parks generally adapt movies into rides, some Disney theme park attractions have been adapted into or have served inspiration for films,<ref>{{cite news|last1=Verrier|first1=Richard|title=Movies Imitate Disney's Parks|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2002/may/15/business/fi-disney15|accessdate=April 1, 2017|work=Los Angeles Times|date=May 15, 2002}}</ref> <!-- notability source & need to mine for more info --> books,<ref name=kr/> comic books,<ref name=spi/> and [[television pilot]]s. Disney entered the television field with a network TV show named after [[Walt Disney anthology television series|Disneyland]] (which was then its only park, and was being built at the time), in order to fund the park. In this series, some episodes featured the park or a park attraction.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Griffin|first1=Sean|title=Encyclopedia of Television|publisher=The Museum of Broadcast Communications|url=http://www.museum.tv/eotv/waltdisneyp.htm|accessdate=April 1, 2017|chapter=Walt Disney Programs|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170817202754/http://www.museum.tv/eotv/waltdisneyp.htm|archive-date=August 17, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> The Walt Disney Company pioneered and is the only film company and theme park company to have converted theme park attractions to film productions. However, lackluster results were achieved for most of these films except for the [[Pirates of the Caribbean (film series)|''Pirates of the Caribbean'']] series.<ref name=\"ew\">{{cite news|last1=Bacle|first1=Ariana |title=Theme park ride-based movies: Will 'Small World' follow the trend?|url=http://ew.com/article/2014/04/23/disney-theme-park-movies-small-world/ |accessdate= March 28, 2017 |work=Entertainment Weekly |date=April 23, 2014}}</ref> [[Walt Disney Pictures]] produced two ''Pirates of the Caribbean'' sequels in 2006 and 2011 that made over a billion-dollar at the box office.<ref name=dl0>{{cite news|url=http://deadline.com/2017/03/beauty-and-the-beast-sean-bailey-disney-emma-watson-1202047710/ |title=Sean Bailey On How Disney\u2019s Live-Action Division Found Its \u2018Beauty And The Beast\u2019 Mojo |date=March 21, 2017 |work=Deadline |publisher=Penske Business Media, LLC |last1=Jr|first1=Mike Fleming|accessdate=March 23, 2017}}</ref>\n\nAt first, Disney had merely dabbled with this type of film. [[Walt Disney Television#Disney Telefilms|Disney Telefilms]] made the first movie-based-on-ride, [[Tower of Terror (1997 film)|Tower of Terror]], for the [[Walt Disney anthology television series|Wonderful World of Disney]] anthology television series in 1997.<ref>{{cite news|title=Disney Sets ABC Pix|url=https://variety.com/1997/scene/vpage/disney-sets-abc-pix-1117342089/|accessdate=December 30, 2015|work=Variety|date=May 1, 1997}}</ref> In 2000, [[Touchstone Pictures]] made ''[[Mission to Mars]]'' based on the [[Mission to Mars (attraction)|closed ride of the same name]].<ref name=\"ew\"/><ref>{{cite news|last1=Schwarzbaum|first1=Lisa|title=Mission to Mars|url=http://ew.com/article/2000/03/17/mission-mars-4/|accessdate=March 28, 2017|work=Entertainment Weekly|date=March 17, 2000}}</ref>\n\n[[Walt Disney Pictures]] took the [[Country Bear Jamboree]] attraction and made it into ''[[The Country Bears]]'' in 2002. In 2003, Walt Disney Pictures issued two ride-based films in ''[[Pirates of the Caribbean: The Curse of the Black Pearl]]'' and ''[[The Haunted Mansion (film)|The Haunted Mansion]]''. ''Pirates of the Caribbean'' launched [[Pirates of the Caribbean (film series)|a film series and a franchise]].<ref name=\"ew\"/> After four Pirates sequels, the franchise took in more than $5.4 billion worldwide.<ref>{{cite news|last1=McNary |first1=Dave |last2=Graser |first2=Marc |url=https://variety.com/2013/biz/news/end-of-an-era-disney-and-jerry-bruckheimer-part-ways-1200652789/ |title=End of an Era: Disney and Jerry Bruckheimer Part Ways |date=September 19, 2013  |work=Variety |publisher= |accessdate=March 28, 2017}}</ref>\n\n[[Disney Publishing Worldwide]] started mining Disney Parks with its [[The Kingdom Keepers]] series. The first novel of the series, ''Disney after Dark'', was released in 2005.<ref name=kr>{{cite magazine|title=The Kingdom Keepers (review)|url=https://www.kirkusreviews.com/book-reviews/ridley-pearson/the-kingdom-keepers/|magazine=Kirkus Reviews|date=August 15, 2005|accessdate=April 9, 2014}}</ref> A five-book series was laid out by Pearson, but was extended to seven with the first book's success.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Hill|first1=Jim|title=Keeping up with Disney's \"Kingdom Keepers\" : Ridley Pearson talks about all the research that goes into this popular book series|url=http://jimhillmedia.com/editor_in_chief1/b/jim_hill/archive/2011/04/03/keeping-up-with-disney-s-quot-kingdom-keepers-quot-ridley-pearson-talks-about-all-the-research-he-does-for-this-popular-book-series.aspx|accessdate=May 1, 2017|work=jimhillmedia.com|date=April 3, 2011|language=en}}</ref>\n\nWith the Pirates of the Caribbean franchise as Disney Pictures' top franchise,<ref name=\"dl0\"/> the company had been looking for additional projects in this category for a decade.<ref name=ew0>{{cite news|last=Breznican|first=Anthony|title=Disney's mysterious '1952' movie has a new name ... 'Tomorrowland' |url=http://insidemovies.ew.com/2013/01/28/disneys-1952-is-tomorrowland/|accessdate=January 29, 2013|newspaper=Entertainment Weekly|date=January 28, 2013}}</ref> Disney Pictures took another push at additional adaptations in the 2010s.<ref name=ew0/> By November 2010, [[Jon Favreau]] had been tapped to develop the [[Magic Kingdom#Planned film|Magic Kingdom]] park into a \"Night at the Museum\" like film, with Strike Entertainment signed on to produce it<ref>{{cite news |last1=Graser |first1=Marc. |title=Jon Favreau enters Disney's 'Magic Kingdom |url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1118027299 |accessdate=September 11, 2018 |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |date=November 10, 2010 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5v00gTWGB?url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1118027299 |archive-date=December 15, 2010}}</ref> after a script by Ronald D. Moore was turned down.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Schaefer|first1=Sandy|title=Jon Favreau Says Magic Kingdom Movie Still in Development|url=http://screenrant.com/jon-favreau-magic-kingdom-movie-disney/|accessdate=April 26, 2017|work=Screen Rant|date=April 4, 2016}}</ref> Another Haunted Mansion film was in the works with [[Guillermo del Toro]] as of August 2012.<ref name=ew0/> [[Mr. Toad's Wild Ride]] ride film was in the works at Disney Pictures by January 2013.<ref>{{cite news|last=Tully|first=Sarah|title=Is 'Tomorrowland' movie tied to Disneyland area?|url=http://www.ocregister.com/news/movie-409540-disney-tomorrowland.html|accessdate=January 29, 2013|newspaper=Orange County Register|date=January 28, 2013}}</ref> [[Tomorrowland (film)|Tomorrowland]], first to be loosely based on a theme park area,<ref>{{cite news|first=Eliana |last=Kirshenblat |url=http://screenrant.com/disney-tower-terror-movie-writer/ |title=Disney\u2019s New Tower of Terror Movie Seeking a Writer |publisher=Screenrant.com |date=October 23, 2015 |accessdate=March 29, 2017}}</ref> was announced in January 2013 for a December 2014 release.<ref name=ew0/> Also in 2013, [[American Broadcasting Company]] had ordered a pilot based on [[Big Thunder Mountain Railroad]].<ref name=dl1>{{cite news|last1= |first1= |url=http://deadline.com/2015/10/tower-of-terror-movie-disney-theme-park-ride-john-august-1201592331/ |title=\u2018Tower Of Terror\u2019 Getting Movie Treatment; Venerable Disney Theme Park Fright Ride |date=October 23, 2015 |work=Deadline |publisher=Penske Business Media, LLC |accessdate=March 28, 2017}}</ref> [[It's A Small World]] was added to the list of known projects in April 2014.<ref>{{cite magazine|last=Fleming |first=Mike |url=http://www.deadline.com/2014/04/disney-taps-jon-turteltaub-to-direct-its-a-small-world-feature-film/ |title=Disney To Make 'It's A Small World' Movie: Jon Turteltaub To Direct |magazine=Deadline.com |date=April 22, 2014 |accessdate=May 20, 2014}}</ref> Tower of Terror was given a theatrical treatment by [[John August]] under producer Jim Whitaker in October 2015, while the long-in-production [[Jungle Cruise]] gained an actor.<ref name=dl1/>\n\n[[Marvel Comics|Marvel Worldwide]] with Disney announced in October 2013 that in January 2014 it would release its first comic book title under their joint [[Marvel Comics#Disney Kingdoms|Disney Kingdoms]] imprint.<ref name=spi>{{cite news |title=Marvel, Disney unveil 1st comic under new imprint |url=http://www.seattlepi.com/news/article/Marvel-Disney-unveil-1st-comic-under-new-imprint-4878283.php |accessdate=October 17, 2013 |agency=[[Associated Press]] |newspaper=[[Seattle Post-Intelligencer]] |date=October 8, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131018022343/http://www.seattlepi.com/news/article/Marvel-Disney-unveil-1st-comic-under-new-imprint-4878283.php |archivedate=October 18, 2013}}</ref> Running for six miniseries, Disney Kingdoms would feature adaptations of the unbuilt Museum of the Weird, two serials about [[Figment]] and Dreamfinder from [[Epcot]]'s [[Journey into Imagination]], Big Thunder Mountain Railroad, the Haunted Mansion, and [[Walt Disney's Enchanted Tiki Room]]. [[Disney Publishing Worldwide]]'s revived Disney Comics imprint<ref>{{cite news |last1=MacDonald |first1=Heidi |title=Disney Expands Its Comics Program |url=https://www.publishersweekly.com/pw/by-topic/childrens/childrens-industry-news/article/59991-disney-expands-their-comics-program.html |accessdate=January 10, 2020 |work=Publishers Weekly.com |date=November 13, 2013}}</ref> first publication was the ''[[Space Mountain]]'' graphic novel released on May 7, 2014 and based on the same name park attraction.<ref>{{cite news |title=Disney Comics Previews SPACE MOUNTAIN Graphic Novel |url=https://www.newsarama.com/21004-disney-comics-previews-space-mountain-graphic-novel.html |accessdate=January 10, 2020 |work=Newsarama |date=April 30, 2014 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nOn March 31, 2015, the first novel in The Kingdom Keepers sequel trilogy series was released.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Bevil|first1=Dewayne|title=Disney book writer Ridley Pearson heads back in time|url=http://www.orlandosentinel.com/travel/attractions/the-daily-disney/os-disney-ridley-pearson-returns-20150408-story.html|accessdate=May 1, 2017|work=Orlando Sentinel|date=April 8, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2017, [[Freeform (TV channel)|Freeform]] cable channel aired a special documentary, ''[[Disney's Fairy Tale Weddings (TV series)|Disney's Fairy Tale Weddings]]'', based on the services provided by Disney Parks and Resorts unit, [[Disney's Fairy Tale Weddings & Honeymoons]]. With success of the May special, the show was picked up as a series with seven episodes in October 2017.<ref>{{cite news|last=Goldberg|first=Lesley|title=Freeform Orders 'Disney's Fairy Tale Weddings' Series (Exclusive)|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/freeform-orders-disneys-fairy-tale-weddings-series-1049359|accessdate=January 29, 2018|work=The Hollywood Reporter|date=October 17, 2017|language=en}}</ref> However, another special, Holiday Magic, was aired on December 11, 2017 with the now six episode regular series starting on June 11, 2018.<ref>{{cite news|last=Sollosi|first=Mary|title='Disney's Fairy Tale Weddings' is here to make your magical wedding dreams come true|url=http://ew.com/tv/2018/06/07/disneys-fairy-tale-weddings/|accessdate=August 1, 2018|work=Entertainment Weekly|date=June 7, 2018|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Shows A-Z \u2013 disney's fairy tale weddings on freeform|url=http://www.thefutoncritic.com/showatch/disneys-fairy-tale-weddings/listings/|website=TheFutonCritic.com|accessdate=August 1, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Other ventures==\n===Disney Signature Experiences===\nDisney Signature Experiences division, formerly called Disney Cruise Line & New Vacation Operations, holds newer non-theme park travel units under president Jeff Vahle.<ref name=\"os6\"/>\n* [[Disney Cruise Line]] was formed in 1995. Its fleet comprises four ships: [[Disney Magic]] (launched 1998), [[Disney Wonder]] (1999), [[Disney Dream]] (2011), and [[Disney Fantasy]] (2012).<ref name=\"usatoday\"/> Disney Cruise Line has ordered three new ships that will be completed in 2021, 2022 and 2023.<ref name=\"os6\"/> Each ship was designed and built-in collaboration with [[Walt Disney Imagineering]]. Disney Cruise Line serves the Caribbean, Mexican Riviera, European, and Alaskan cruises market.\n* [[Disney Vacation Club]], a [[timeshare]] program that includes 14 themed hotels-resorts within Disneyland Resort and Walt Disney World Resort,  plus [[Aulani|Disney's Aulani Resort]], [[Disney's Hilton Head Island Resort]], and [[Disney's Vero Beach Resort]]. In December 2019, the 15th property, [[Disney's Riviera Resort]], opened next to the Caribbean Beach Resort at Walt Disney World. A 16th resort, [[Reflections - A Disney Lakeside Lodge]], is planned to open in 2022 just east of [[Disney's Wilderness Lodge]] on the former site of [[Disney's River Country]] water park.\n* [[Adventures by Disney]], a program of all-inclusive, guided vacation tour packages offered at predominantly non-Disney sites around the world.<ref name=\"os6\"/>\n*Golden Oak Realty, [[Golden Oak at Walt Disney World Resort]] sales<ref name=\"os6\"/>\n\n===Disney Sports Enterprises===\n{{Infobox company\n| name =Disney Sports Enterprises\n| logo =\n| logo_size =\n| logo_alt =\n| logo_caption =\n| logo_padding =\n| image =\n| image_size =\n| image_alt =\n| image_caption =\n| native_name =\n| native_name_lang = <!-- Use ISO 639-1 code, e.g. \"fr\" for French. For multiple names in different languages, use {{lang|[code]|[name]}}. -->\n| former_name =Disney Sports Attractions\n| type =\n| industry = Sports\n| founded = <!-- if known: {{start date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} in [[city]], [[state]], [[country]] -->\n| founder = [[Reggie Williams (linebacker)|Reggie Williams]].<ref name=os0/>\n| hq_location =\n| hq_location_city =\n| hq_location_country =\n| area_served = <!-- or: | areas_served = -->\n| key_people =Faron Kelley (vice president)\n| products =\n| brands =\n| divisions = [[ESPN Wide World of Sports Complex]]<br>[[runDisney]]\n| services =road race<br>sports events\n| owner = <!-- or: | owners = -->\n| website = {{URL|disneysportsnews.com/}}\n}}\n'''Disney Sports Enterprises''', formerly called Disney Sports Attractions,<ref name=sbd/> is the unit of Disney Parks and Resorts for Disney's sports functions and is made up of the [[ESPN Wide World of Sports Complex]] and the [[runDisney]] program.<ref name=sbd0>{{cite news|title=Executive Transactions|url=http://www.sportsbusinessdaily.com/Daily/Issues/2013/01/10/People-and-Pop-Culture/Execs.aspx|accessdate=April 22, 2016|work=Sports Business Daily|publisher=American City Business Journals|date=January 10, 2013}}</ref>\n\n====DSE background====\nDisney Golf facilities date back to the opening of Disney World with two golf courses, the Palm and Magnolia courses. At the time, those courses started hosting the [[Walt Disney World Golf Classic|Walt Disney World Open Invitational]], an annual PGA Tour event.<ref name=os>{{cite news| last1=Garcia| first1=Jason |title=Disney World to turn golf courses over to Arnold Palmer group |url= http://articles.orlandosentinel.com/2011-08-24/the-daily-disney/os-disney-golf-arnold-palmer-20110824_1_walt-disney-world-golf-courses-golf-datatech |accessdate=April 25, 2016 |work=Orlando Sentinel |date=August 24, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 1994, Disney held the [[Walt Disney World Marathon]], its first road race added additional races later.<ref name=fbs>{{cite news|last1=Sylt|first1=Christian|title=Disney's Runaway Success|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/csylt/2016/01/07/disneys-runaway-success/|accessdate=April 25, 2016|work=Forbes|date=January 7, 2016}}</ref> Disneyland Marathon and 5K were run in 1995 three weeks after the LA Marathon on March 26, 1995.<ref>{{cite news|last1=VanderKnyff|first1=Rick|title=Disneyland's Magical Marathon|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1995-03-23/news/ol-45988_1_disneyland-marathon|accessdate=April 25, 2016|work=Los Angeles Times|date=March 23, 1995}}</ref>\n\nIn 1995, Disney World had IMS Events, Inc. build the [[Walt Disney World Speedway]].<ref name=\"aw\">{{cite news|last1=Larson|first1=Mike|title=Walt Disney World Speedway shutting down for good|url= http://autoweek.com/article/indycar/walt-disney-world-speedway-shutting-down-good|accessdate=April 25, 2016|work=Autoweek|publisher=Crain Communications|date=February 12, 2015}}</ref> [[ESPN Wide World of Sports Complex|Disney's Wide World of Sports]] opened in 1997 under executive [[Reggie Williams (linebacker)|Reggie Williams]].<ref name=os0>{{cite news|last1=Robbins|first1=Josh|title=Reggie Williams to step down as Disney vice president of sports attractions|url=http://articles.orlandosentinel.com/2007-11-14/sports/williams14_1_legs-reggie-williams-atlanta-braves|accessdate=April 25, 2016 |work=Orlando Sentinel |date=November 14, 2007}}</ref>\n\n====DSE history====\nBy 1998, Williams was named Vice President of Disney Sports Attractions, overseeing a newly created sports & recreation division.<ref name=os1>{{cite news|last1=Solano|first1=Javier|title=Directing Sports Of Disney| url= http://articles.orlandosentinel.com/1998-03-27/sports/9803270617_1_disney-wide-disney-sports-complex-world-of-sports |accessdate=April 25, 2016 |work=Orlando Sentinel |date=March 27, 1998}}</ref> The first 10K Disney Classic race on October 3, 1999, kicked off Disney World's 15-month Millennium Celebration.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Carroll|first1=Frank|title=Disney Classic 10k Is Oct. 3|url=http://articles.orlandosentinel.com/1999-09-24/news/9909240052_1_10k-classic-three-aces-male-and-female|accessdate=April 27, 2016|work=Orlando Sentinel|date=September 24, 1999}}</ref> On March 30, 2003, Sports Attractions held the first Disney Inline Marathon.<ref>{{cite news|title=Putting together skate event was a marathon itself|url=http://www.sportsbusinessdaily.com/Journal/Issues/2002/10/20021014/Marketingsponsorship/Putting-Together-Skate-Event-Was-A-Marathon-Itself.aspx|accessdate=April 26, 2016|work=SportsBusiness Journal|issue=October 14\u201320, 2002|publisher=American City Business Journals|date=October 14, 2002}}</ref>\n\nOn November 21, 2007, Reggie Williams retired as vice president of Disney Sports Attractions.<ref name=os0/> His replacement was named on January 3, 2008, when Ken Potrock was promoted to Senior Vice President, Disney Sports Enterprises.<ref name=sbd>{{cite news|title=Disney Moves Marketing Exec Potrock To Sports Enterprises |url=http://www.sportsbusinessdaily.com/Daily/Issues/2008/01/Issue-72/Sports-Industrialists/Disney-Moves-Marketing-Exec-Potrock-To-Sports-Enterprises.aspx|accessdate=April 25, 2016|work=Sports Business Daily|publisher=American City Business Journals|date=January 3, 2008}}</ref> On February 25, 2010, Disney's Wide World of Sports was renamed ESPN Wide World of Sports Complex with some upgrades and new facilities.<ref>{{cite news|title=Disney's Wide World Of Sports Complex To Receive ESPN Rebranding|url=http://www.sportsbusinessdaily.com/Daily/Issues/2009/11/Issue-40/Facilities-Venues/Disneys-Wide-World-Of-Sports-Complex-To-Receive-ESPN-Rebranding.aspx?hl=Disney%20Sports%20Enterprises&sc=1|accessdate=April 26, 2016|work=Sports Business Daily|issue=40|publisher=American City Business Journals}}</ref>\n\nOn September 25, 2011, Disney started the lease of its five Disney World golf courses (Palm, Magnolia, Lake Buena Vista, Osprey Ridge, and Oak Trail) to Arnold Palmer Golf Management to operate for 20 years while splitting the revenue. As part of the deal, Arnold Palmer would redesign the Palm course. The Orlando market for golf had a glut of course from the building boom then bust making profitability a challenge for any golf course. Disney hoped that Palmer's involvement and \"Palmer Advantage\" membership club would draw more attention to Disney's course. With the Osprey Ridge course sold to Four Seasons Hotels and Resorts to build a hotel, which was delayed until 2014, the golf management company would run the course until hotel construction begins. While another golf course, the Eagle Pines, was closed several years ago to make way for a residential housing subdivision development called Golden Oak being built in 2011.<ref name=os/>\n\nIn January 2013, Ken Petrock was promoted to Disney Vacation Club and Adventures by Disney Senior VP & GM while Tom Wolber, Disney Cruise Line Senior VP/Operations, was promoted to replace Petrock at Disney Sports.<ref name=sbd0/> In late June 2015, the [[Walt Disney World Speedway]] was shut down.<ref name=\"aw\"/> Senior Vice President of Disney Springs and the ESPN Wide World of Sports Maribeth Bisienere was promoted to Senior Vice President of Parks in early March 2018.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Storey |first1=Ken |title=A heavily rumored Mary Poppins attraction is starting to look more real at Epcot |url=https://www.orlandoweekly.com/Blogs/archives/2018/03/12/a-heavily-rumored-mary-poppins-attraction-is-starting-to-look-more-real-at-epcot |accessdate=July 11, 2018 |work=Orlando Weekly |date=March 12, 2018 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\";\n|-\n!colspan=4| runDisney races<ref>{{cite news|title=Event Preview \u2013 RunDisney|url=http://www.endurancemag.com/2011/11/event-preview-rundisney/|accessdate=April 26, 2016|work=Endurance Magazine|date=November 21, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=runDisney|url=http://www.rundisney.com|website=rundisney.com|publisher=Disney Sports Enterprises|accessdate=April 27, 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n! Race weekend !! month !! location !! Inaugurated\n|-\n| Disney World Marathon || January \n|rowspan=4| Disney World\n|| 1994<ref name=fbs/> \n|-\n| Princess Half-Marathon|| February || 2009<ref name=os2/>\n|-\n| Star Wars Half Marathon<br>\u2014 The Dark Side || April || 2016<ref name=os2>{{cite news|last1=Ruiz|first1=Stephen|title=Runners from Wisconsin, New York conquer Star Wars Half Marathon at Disney|url=http://www.orlandosentinel.com/sports/os-star-wars-half-marathon-disney-world-20160417-story.html|accessdate=April 27, 2016|work=Orlando Sentinel|date=April 17, 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n| Wine & Dine Half-Marathon || November || \n|-\n| Tinker Bell Half-Marathon || May\n|rowspan=4|  Disneyland \n||\n|-\n| Disneyland Half-Marathon  ||  September<br>(Labor Day weekend) ||\n|-\n| Avengers Super Heroes Half Marathon || November || 2014<ref name=fbs/>\n|-\n| Star Wars Half Marathon<br>\u2014 The Light Side || January || 2015<ref name=fbs/>\n|-\n| Disneyland Paris Half Marathon || September || Disneyland Paris || 2016<ref name=fbs/>\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Universal Parks & Resorts]], Disney's major competitor in the theme park industry\n* [[Warner Bros. Global Brands and Experiences]], Disney's largest cinematic competitor's equivalent branch of their company. \n* [[Disney Consumer Products and Interactive Media#Franchises|Consumer Products franchises]]\n* [[Anaheim Sports]], formerly Disney Sports Enterprises\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\nFrom {{citation|last1=Polsson|first1=Ken|title=Chronology of the Walt Disney Company |url=http://kpolsson.com/disnehis/|website=Chronology of the Walt Disney Company|accessdate=May 5, 2015}}:\n{{reflist|group=CDC|30em}}\nFrom {{citation|last1=Polsson|first1=Ken|title=Chronology of Disneyland Theme Park|url=http://kpolsson.com/disland/|website=Chronology of the Walt Disney Company|accessdate=May 5, 2015}}:\n{{reflist|group=CDL|30em}}\nFrom {{citation|last1=Polsson|first1=Ken|title=Chronology of Disneyland Theme Park (1985\u20131989)|url=http://kpolsson.com/disland/dl1985.htm|website=Chronology of the Walt Disney Company|accessdate=May 5, 2015}}:\n{{reflist|group=CDL4|30em}}\nFrom {{citation|last1=Polsson|first1=Ken|title=Chronology of Disneyland Theme Park (1990\u20131999)|url=http://kpolsson.com/disland/dl1990.htm|website=Chronology of the Walt Disney Company|accessdate=May 5, 2015}}:\n{{reflist|group=CDL5|30em}}\nFrom {{citation|last1=Polsson|first1=Ken |title=Chronology of Walt Disney World (1958\u20131971) |url=http://kpolsson.com/wdworld/ |website=Chronology of the Walt Disney Company|accessdate=September 24, 2015}}:\n{{reflist|group=CDW|30em}}\nFrom {{citation|last1=Polsson|first1=Ken|title=Chronology of Walt Disney World (1972\u20131982) |url=http://kpolsson.com/wdworld/wdw1972.htm|website=Chronology of the Walt Disney Company|accessdate=September 24, 2015}}:\n{{reflist|group=CDW0|30em}}\nFrom {{citation|last1=Polsson|first1=Ken|title=Chronology of Walt Disney World (1983\u20131989)|url=http://kpolsson.com/wdworld/wdw1983.htm|website=Chronology of the Walt Disney Company|accessdate=September 24, 2015}}:\n{{reflist|group=CDW1|30em}}\nFrom {{citation|last1=Polsson|first1=Ken|title=Chronology of Walt Disney World (1990\u20131994)|url=http://kpolsson.com/wdworld/wdw1990.htm|website=Chronology of the Walt Disney Company|accessdate=September 24, 2015}}:\n{{reflist|group=CDW2|30em}}\nFrom {{citation|last1=Polsson|first1=Ken|title=Chronology of Walt Disney World (1995-end)|url=http://kpolsson.com/wdworld/wdw1995.htm |website=Chronology of the Walt Disney Company|accessdate=September 24, 2015}}:\n{{reflist|group=CDW3|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikivoyage|Disney}}\n* {{Official website|https://dpep.disney.com/}}\n\n{{Disney}}\n{{DisneyConsumer}}\n{{Disney Parks, Experiences and Products}}\n\n[[Category:American companies established in 1971]]\n[[Category:The Walt Disney Company]]\n[[Category:Walt Disney Parks and Resorts| ]]\n[[Category:The Walt Disney Company subsidiaries|Parks and Resorts]]\n[[Category:Amusement park companies]]\n[[Category:Hospitality companies of the United States]]\n[[Category:Entertainment companies based in California]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Florida]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Burbank, California]]\n[[Category:Entertainment companies established in 1971]]\n[[Category:1971 establishments in California]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toFigment(link changed toFigment (Disney character)) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Disney_Parks,_Experiences_and_Products"}
{"title_page": "Mutare District", "text_new": "{{short description|District in Zimbabwe}}\n[[File:Manicaland districts.png|thumb|A map of the districts of Manicaland Province]]\n[[Image:Zim map.jpg|220px|thumb|right|Mutare District lies on Zimbabwe's eastern border ''(click map to enlarge)'']]\n'''Mutare District''' is a district in [[Manicaland Province]] of eastern [[Zimbabwe]]. The district headquarters is the city of [[Mutare]].\n\n==Geography==\nThe district has a rural area of 5,523 km\u00b2, and 191 km\u00b2 It is bounded on the east by [[Mozambique]], on the northeast by [[Mutasa District]], on the northwest by [[Makoni District]], on the southwest by [[Buhera District]], and on the southeast by [[Chimanimani District]].\n\nThe city of [[Mutare]] is in the northeastern corner of the district, near the border with Mozambique. Mutare is the largest city in the district, and the fourth-largest city in Zimbabwe. Other towns include [[Chiadzwa]] and [[Odzi]].\n\nThe [[Eastern Highlands]] extend north and south through eastern portion of the district, along the border with Mozambique. The [[Bvumba Mountains]] form a part of the highlands, and rise southeast of Mutare city. The highest peak is Castle Beacon at 1,911 metres. The [[Bunga Forest Botanical Reserve]] conserves the mountains' high-elevation mist forest. [[Banti Forest Reserve]] (22.2 km\u00b2) is located south of Bvumba range, in the mountains along the Mozambican border.\n\nMost of the district lies in the basin of the [[Save River (Africa)|Save River]], which forms the southwestern boundary of the district. The [[Odzi River]], a tributary of the Save, drains the center of the district, flowing southwards to join the Save at the district's southernmost point. The [[Burma Valley]], an area along the southeastern border with Mozambique on the eastern slope of the Bvumba mountains, drains eastwards into the [[Revu\u00e9 River]], a tributary of the [[Buzi River (Mozambique)|Buzi River]].<ref>Sande, Shadreck & Zimba, Moses & P., Chinwada & Masendu, Hieronymo & Mazando, Sungai & Makuwaza, Aramu. (2015). The emergence of insecticide resistance in the major malaria vector Anopheles funestus (Diptera: Culicidae) from sentinel sites in Mutare and Mutasa Districts, Zimbabwe. Malaria Journal. 14. 10.1186/s12936-015-0993-8.</ref>\n\n==People== \nThe 2012 census recorded a population of 262,124 in the rural portion of the district. Mutare urban had a population of 187,621.<ref>\"Census 2020 Provincial Report, Manicaland\". Zimbabwe National Statistics Agency, Population Census Office. Accessed 11 April 2020. [http://www.zimstat.co.zw/sites/default/files/img/publications/Population/Manicaland.pdf]</ref>\n\n==Administration==\nThe rural portion of the district is divided into 36 administrative wards.<ref>\"Census 2020 Provincial Report, Manicaland\". Zimbabwe National Statistics Agency, Population Census Office. Accessed 11 April 2020. [http://www.zimstat.co.zw/sites/default/files/img/publications/Population/Manicaland.pdf]</ref> Mutare has an elected City Council, with 19 councillors each representing one of the city's 19 wards.<ref>\"About Us\". Mutare City Council. Accessed 11 April 2020. [https://www.mutarecity.co.zw/index.php/about-us]</ref> The city of Mutare is the district's administrative headquarters, and also serves as the administrative headquarters of Manicaland Province.\n\nThe district is divided into five [[National Assembly of Zimbabwe|Assembly]] [[List of Zimbabwean parliamentary constituencies|parliamentary constituencies]]: [[Dangamvura-Chikanga]], [[Mutare Central]], [[Mutare North]], [[Mutare South]], and [[Mutare West]]. The district is divided into two [[Senate of Zimbabwe|Senate]] constituencies; Mutare constituency includes Dangamvura-Chikanga, Mutare Central, Mutare South, Mutare North, while Mutare West and Mutare South are in Chimanimani constituency.\n\n==Transport==\nThe main east-west road from [[Harare]] to the Mozambican port of [[Beira, Mozambique|Beira]] ([[R5 road (Zimbabwe)|R5]], or A3 in the older numbering system) runs through Mutare district, crossing the international border just east of Mutare city.\n\nThe [[Beira\u2013Bulawayo railway]] also passes through Mutare, which has a railway station.\n\nAirports in the district include [[Mutare Airport]], located close to the city, and [[Grand Reef Airport]], located 20 km west of Mutare Airport.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n[[Category:Mutare District]]\n[[Category:Districts of Manicaland Province]]\n[[Category:Districts of Zimbabwe]]\n\n{{Geography of Zimbabwe}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|District in Zimbabwe}}\n[[File:Manicaland districts.png|thumb|A map of the districts of Manicaland Province]]\n[[Image:Zim map.jpg|220px|thumb|right|Mutare District lies on Zimbabwe's eastern border ''(click map to enlarge)'']]\n'''Mutare District''' is a district in [[Manicaland Province]] of eastern [[Zimbabwe]]. The district headquarters is the city of [[Mutare]].\n\n==Geography==\nThe district has a rural area of 5,523 km\u00b2, and 191 km\u00b2 It is bounded on the east by [[Mozambique]], on the northeast by [[Mutasa District]], on the northwest by [[Makoni District]], on the southwest by [[Buhera District]], and on the southeast by [[Chimanimani District]].\n\nThe city of [[Mutare]] is in the northeastern corner of the district, near the border with Mozambique. Mutare is the largest city in the district, and the fourth-largest city in Zimbabwe. Other towns include [[Chiadzwa]] and [[Odzi]].\n\nThe [[Eastern Highlands]] extend north and south through eastern portion of the district, along the border with Mozambique. The [[Bvumba Mountains]] form a part of the highlands, and rise southeast of Mutare city. The highest peak is Castle Beacon at 1,911 metres. The [[Bunga Forest Botanical Reserve]] conserves the mountains' high-elevation mist forest. [[Banti Forest Reserve]] (22.2 km\u00b2) is located south of Bvumba range, in the mountains along the Mozambican border.\n\nMost of the district lies in the basin of the [[Save River (Africa)|Save River]], which forms the southwestern boundary of the district. The [[Odzi River]], a tributary of the Save, drains the center of the district, flowing southwards to join the Save at the district's southernmost point. The [[Burma Valley]], an area along the southeastern border with Mozambique on the eastern slope of the Bvumba mountains, drains eastwards into the [[Revu\u00e9 River]], a tributary of the [[Buzi River (Mozambique)|Buzi River]].<ref>Sande, Shadreck & Zimba, Moses & P., Chinwada & Masendu, Hieronymo & Mazando, Sungai & Makuwaza, Aramu. (2015). The emergence of insecticide resistance in the major malaria vector Anopheles funestus (Diptera: Culicidae) from sentinel sites in Mutare and Mutasa Districts, Zimbabwe. Malaria Journal. 14. 10.1186/s12936-015-0993-8.</ref>\n\n==People== \nThe 2012 census recorded a population of 262,124 in the rural portion of the district. Mutare urban had a population of 187,621.<ref>\"Census 2020 Provincial Report, Manicaland\". Zimbabwe National Statistics Agency, Population Census Office. Accessed 11 April 2020. [http://www.zimstat.co.zw/sites/default/files/img/publications/Population/Manicaland.pdf]</ref>\n\n==Administration==\nThe rural portion of the district is divided into 36 administrative wards.<ref>\"Census 2020 Provincial Report, Manicaland\". Zimbabwe National Statistics Agency, Population Census Office. Accessed 11 April 2020. [http://www.zimstat.co.zw/sites/default/files/img/publications/Population/Manicaland.pdf]</ref> Mutare has an elected City Council, with 19 councillors each representing one of the city's 19 wards.<ref>\"About Us\". Mutare City Council. Accessed 11 April 2020. [https://www.mutarecity.co.zw/index.php/about-us]</ref> The city of Mutare is the district's administrative headquarters, and also serves as the administrative headquarters of Manicaland Province.\n\nThe district is divided into five [[National Assembly of Zimbabwe|Assembly]] [[List of Zimbabwean parliamentary constituencies|parliamentary constituencies]]: [[Dangamvura-Chikanga]], [[Mutare Central]], [[Mutare North]], [[Mutare South]], and [[Mutare West]]. The district is divided into two senate constituencies; Mutare constituency includes Dangamvura-Chikanga, Mutare Central, Mutare South, Mutare North, while Mutare West and Mutare South are in Chimanimani constituency.\n\n==Transport==\nThe main east-west road from [[Harare]] to the Mozambican port of [[Beira, Mozambique|Beira]] ([[R5 road (Zimbabwe)|R5]], or A3 in the older numbering system) runs through Mutare district, crossing the international border just east of Mutare city.\n\nThe [[Beira\u2013Bulawayo railway]] also passes through Mutare, which has a railway station.\n\nAirports in the district include [[Mutare Airport]], located close to the city, and [[Grand Reef Airport]], located 20 km west of Mutare Airport.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n[[Category:Mutare District]]\n[[Category:Districts of Manicaland Province]]\n[[Category:Districts of Zimbabwe]]\n\n{{Geography of Zimbabwe}}\n", "name_user": "Tom Radulovich", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eAdministration:link senate", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mutare_District"}
{"title_page": "Agi Orsi", "text_new": "'''Agi Orsi''' is an independent Los Angeles-based documentary filmmaker<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0650709/|title=Agi Orsi|last=|first=|date=|website=IMDB|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> who produces films for television and for theatrical release on music and sports subcultures, as well as socially relevant themes, such as the criminalization of homelessness and the challenges of living on the street with mental illness. The subjects of her productions include kayakers achieving a diplomatic triumph in a joint U-Soviet expedition,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.deseret.com/1989/10/15/18828526/river-rafting-in-siberia-is-topic-of-documentary|title=River Rafting in Siberia is Topic of Documentary|last=|first=|date=1989|website=Desert News|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0650709/bio|title=Agi Orsi Bio|last=|first=|date=|website=IMDB|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> rebellious Venice skateboarders carving their separate identity in a surf-dominated culture,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2001/film/reviews/dogtown-and-z-boys-1200466864/|title=Dogtown and Z-Boys|last=Harvey|first=Dennis|date=2001|website=Variety|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=2001|access-date=}}</ref> a courageous Hawaiian surfer remembered as the symbol of Aloha or kindness for risking his life to save others,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tribecafilm.com/festival/archive/51471ed0c07f5d4659000002-hawaiian-the-legend-of-ed|title=Hawaiian: The Legend of Eddie Aikau|last=|first=|date=|website=TribecaFilm.Com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> the backyard punk rock scene in East Los Angeles<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/music/la-et-los-punks-movie-20160525-snap-story.html|title=Los Punks\u2019 documentary goes behind the scenes of L.A.'s underground punk rock scene|last=Roberts|first=Randall|date=2016|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> where homegrown musicians, not music conglomerates, set the tone, and struggling Skid Row homeless building community and embracing hope despite widespread despair and drug abuse.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cinemalibrestudio.com/skidrowismyhome/production_team.html|title=Lost Angels: Production Team|last=|first=|date=2018|website=Cinema Libre Studio|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nOrsi is the Founder of Agi Orsi Productions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://open.spotify.com/playlist/26jh0hj7TQfsPtlGrOIjbn|title=Agi Orsi Productions-Riding Giants|last=|first=|date=|website=Spotify|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nIn addition to producing for theater and television, Orsi is a DGA Unit Production Manager on most of her documentaries.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://m.imdb.com/name/nm0650709/filmotype/production_manager?ref_=m_nmfm_2|title=Agi Orsi: Unit Production Manager|last=|first=|date=|website=IMDB|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n== Education ==\nA native of Budapest, Hungary, fluent in English, French and Hungarian, Orsi received her Masters in French Language and Civilization from Universit\u00e9 Panth\u00e9 on Sorbonne in Paris.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cinemalibrestudio.com/skidrowismyhome/production_team.html|title=Los Angels: Production Team|last=|first=|date=|website=Cinema Libre Studio|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> \u00a0\n\n== Philanthropy ==\nOrsi serves on the Board of Housing Works,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://housingworksca.org/team/|title=Board of Directors|last=|first=|date=|website=Housing Works|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> a non-profit organization committed to providing supportive housing for the homeless, and participates in film forums to promote independent documentary film making and mentor aspiring documentarians.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.workingfilms.org/reel-change-in-the-bay-area/|title=Reel Change: Managing Social Issue Film Campaigns|last=|first=|date=|website=Working Films|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n== Film Financing ==\nTo finance '''''Dogtown and Z-Boys''''', Orsi sought and obtained financing from Vans shoe manufacturing company, which manufactured deck shoes with \"sticky souls\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theskateboarder.net/best-skate-shoes/|title=The 13 Best Skateboard Shoes of 2020|last=|first=|date=1019|website=Skateboarder|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> popular with skateboarders in the 70s.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.documentary.org/feature/and-now-word-about-sponsors-taking-corporate-route-funding-your-project|title=And Now, A Word About Sponsors: Taking the Corporate Route to Funding Your Project|last=Fairweather|first=Kathleen|date=2003|website=IDA (International Documentary Association)|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=2003|access-date=}}</ref> Although the deal with Vans was negotiated quickly, Orsi acknowledged most film financing involves a longer process of negotiation. In a 2003 interview with the International Documentary Association, Orsi said, \"Once we got the awards at Sundance, we had many suitors for a distribution deal. Vans consulted on everything with us. We were true partners.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.documentary.org/feature/and-now-word-about-sponsors-taking-corporate-route-funding-your-project|title=And Now, A Word About Sponsors: Taking the Corporate Route to Funding Your Project|last=Fairweather|first=Kathleen|date=2003|website=IDA (International Documentary  Association)|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n== Most Notable Awards & Recognition ==\nMost notable is Orsi's collaboration with documentary film director and skateboarder Stacey Peralta to win '''Sundance Festival's Audience and Best Director''' award for '''''Dogtown and Z-Boys''''',<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2002/04/26/movies/film-review-skating-on-top-of-the-world-during-an-endless-summer.html)|title=FILM REVIEW; Skating on Top of the World During an Endless Summer|last=Holden|first=Stephen|date=2002|website=New York Times|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> a documentary, narrated by Sean Penn, that explores the world of skateboarding, its impact on surf culture and the disturbing aftermath of lost stardom. Orsi again teamed with Peralta to produce '''''Riding Giants''''' (Studio Canal/Sony Classics), the first documentary to ever open the Sundance Film Festival and winner of the 2004 '''A.C.E. Eddie Award''' for '''Best Edited Documentary'''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.emmys.com/news/ace-eddies-named-top-editing-prizes-handed-out|title=A.C.E. Eddies Named Top Editing Prizes Handed Out|last=|first=|date=2005|website=Emmys.Com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> by editor Paul Crowder. In Riding Giants director Stacy Peralta pays tribute to the adventurous surfers riding the world's most daunting 20-foot high waves, only to yearn for even more challenging thrill rides.\n\nAdditionally Orsi worked with director and professional surfer Sam George to produce '''''Hawaiian: The Legend of Eddie Aikau''''' (ESPN''''')'''''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://finance.yahoo.com/news/espn-films-30-30-hawaiian-154949024.html|title=ESPN Films: \"30 for 30\" \"Hawaiian: The Legend of Eddie Aikau\" Wins Emmy Award|last=|first=|date=|website=Yahoo Finance/Marketwired|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=May 29, 2014|access-date=}}</ref>''',''' a biographical film of the big wave surfer Eddie Aikau who became the symbol of Aloha and celebration of Hawaiian culture. The documentary premiered on [[ESPN]] on October 1, 2013 and won an '''Emmy for Best Sports Documentary Series''', making it one of the few surf-related films to ever receive such recognition.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.westhawaiitoday.com/2014/05/29/hawaii-news/hawaiian-the-legend-of-eddie-aikau-wins-emmy-award/|title=Hawaiian: The Legend of Eddie Aikau|last=|first=|date=2020|website=West Hawaii Today|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The documentary that chronicles Aikau's emergence as a legendary surfer and lifeguard who saved lives but lost his own at sea also won awards for '''Best Picture and Best Director at the Malibu International Film Festival'''; '''Best Picture, Best Documentary and Audience Favorite at the Maui Film Festival''', as well as '''Best Documentary at Surfer Poll'''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.westhawaiitoday.com/2014/05/29/hawaii-news/hawaiian-the-legend-of-eddie-aikau-wins-emmy-award/|title=Hawaiian: The Legend of Eddi Akau|last=|first=|date=2020|website=West Hawaii Today|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nOrsi's foray into documentary filmmaking began when she teamed with director John Armstrong to produce '''''Bashkaus: Hard Labor in Siberia'''''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0650709/bio|title=Agi Orsi Bio|last=|first=|date=|website=IMDB|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>''',''' (Discovery Channel), a film that won a '''Gold Medal Living Book Award''' and the '''Grand Prize at the Telluride Mountain Film Festival'''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mountainfilm.org/festival/personalities/john-armstrong|title=John Armstrong|last=|first=|date=|website=John Armstrong|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> for chronicling the first joint US-Soviet river expedition in Russia's Altai Mountains during a thaw in the Cold War.\u00a0 Following that, Orsi teamed again with Armstrong to produce '''''Curtain of Ice''''' <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.worldcat.org/title/curtain-of-ice/oclc/27479917|title=Curtain of Ice|last=|first=|date=|website=World Cat|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>(Discovery Channel), documenting the first-on water crossing of the Bering Strait, the \"Curtain of Ice,\" reuniting Eskimos separated for decades during the US-Russia arms escalation. The documentary also tells the story of Jim Noyes, a paraplegic with a broken spine who finds a new purpose for living after making the crossing.\n\nDeparting from the adventure sports genre, Orsi served as supervising producer on '''''Amazing Journey: The Story of The Who''''',<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0462441/fullcredits/?ref_=tt_ov_st_sm|title=Amazing Journey: The Story of the Who|last=|first=|date=|website=IMDB|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> a 2007 documentary '''''nominated for a Grammy''' '''Award''''',<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.grammy.com/grammys/artists/who|title=The Who|last=|first=|date=|website=Grammy.Com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> co-directed by [[Murray Lerner]] and [[Paul Crowder (filmmaker)|Paul Crowder]], integrating archival footage of The Who's concerts at Monterrey and Woodstock and interviews with the stars of the English band known for its ear-shattering volumes and distortions, as well as its mixture of pop hits, traditional jazz, rock and R & B. The film's soundtrack features a compilation of the band's greatest hits, among them the single, \"My Generation,\" written by Peter Townshend. Included in the documentary is original footage, never seen before, of the 1970 Leeds University appearance in which The Who's performance disintegrated into \"chaotic noise\" as a result of amphetamine use, resulting in a fist fight between band members and the temporary expulsion of lead singer Roger Daltrey.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ultimateclassicrock.com/daltrey-walks-out-on-who/|title=When Roger Daltrey Walked Out, Then Right Back into the Who|last=Wawzenek|first=Bryan|date=|website=Ultimate Classic Rock|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nFar from the concert stage, Orsi went to downtown Los Angeles to produce '''''Lost Angels: Skid Row is My Home''''', a documentary that evolved from the 2009 movie \u201cThe Soloist.\u201d Starring Robert Downey Jr. and Jamie Foxx, The Soloist is based on stories LA Times columnist Steve Lopez wrote about a Julliard-educated homeless musician. In contrast to The Soloist's laser focus on the musician, Lost Angels weaves together the stories of several Skid Row residents and extras from The Soloist, including a cat lover who feeds stray cats as she wheels carts of trash up and down Skid Row, an Olympic athlete and track and field coach tormented by drug addiction, a gospel singer with a rare congenital disease and a transgender Vietnam Veteran.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/business/la-xpm-2011-oct-12-la-fi-ct-onlocation-20111012-story.html|title=On Location: \u2018Lost Angels\u2019 documentary focuses on L.A. skid row|last=Verrier|first=Richard|date=2011|website=Los Angeles Times|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.reellifewithjane.com/2013/05/review-lost-angels-skid-row-is-my-home/|title=Film Review & Perspective: \u2018Lost Angels: Skid Row Is My Home\u2019|last=Miraz|first=Jacqueline|date=May 20, 2013|website=Reel Life with Jane|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nThe documentary, released in 2009 by Paramount Pictures, was financed for $300,000 by DreamWorks and Universal Pictures and Participant Media, with contributions from the Hilton Foundation and Community Supportive Housing, takes a critical look at then Mayor Antonio Villaraigosa's Safer City Initiative which made it a crime to panhandle, sleep, sit or store personal items on sidewalks and other public spaces.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-homeless-losangeles/los-angeles-accused-of-criminalizing-homelessness-idUSTRE56E0MC20090715|title=Los Angeles accused of criminalizing homelessness|last=Gorman|first=Steve|date=2009|website=Reuters|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The film, narrated by actress Catherine Keener, points to the success of supportive housing with wrap-around mental health and employment services.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cinemalibrestudio.com/skidrowismyhome/get_involved.html|title=Lost Angels: Skid Row is my Home|last=|first=|date=|website=Cinema Libre Studio|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nLos Angeles earned recognition for the following awards: '''2011 Voice Award from SAMHSA''' (Substance Abuse and Mental Health Services Administration) and '''Ghetto Award-Radar Hamburg International Film Festival.''' The documentary was also an official selection for the Los Angeles Film Festival (Premiere), One World Human Rights Film Festival (Prague), Human Rights Film Festival (London), Oaxaca Film Festival, among others.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cinemalibrestudio.com/skidrowismyhome/assets/lost-angels-press-notes-FINAL.pdf|title=Lost Angels: Skid Row is My Home|last=|first=|date=|website=Cinema Libre Studio|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nOrsi also produced '''''Los Punks; We Are All We Have''''', a 2016 documentary financed by Vans that explores the punk rock scene blaring from backyards and dirt lots in East Los Angeles, Boyle Heights and South Los Angeles, where the mohawk-sporting musicians, some with troubled pasts\u2014suicide attempts, police arrests\u2014do not need corporate music conglomerates or concert venues to make a name for their hardcore selves. Los Punks, directed by punk rocker Angela Boatwright, premiered at the 2016 Slamdance Film Festival, where critics applauded its gritty depiction of homegrown East LA music bands\u2014Las Cochinas, Corrupted Youth, Rhythmic Asylum\u2014integrated with poignant personal stories.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/music/la-et-los-punks-movie-20160525-snap-story.html|title='Los Punks\u2019 documentary goes behind the scenes of L.A.'s underground punk rock scene|last=Roberts|first=Randall|date=May 26, 2016|website=LA Times|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n== Filmography ==\n\n'''''Los Punks; We Are All We Have''''' (2016)\u2014 Documentary feature, dir. Angela Boatwright\n\n[Official Selection: Slamdance Film Festival, East End Film Festival]\n\n\u25ca Producer\u2014 Agi Orsi Productions <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/music/la-et-los-punks-movie-20160525-snap-story.html|title=Los Punks\u2019 documentary goes behind the scenes of L.A.'s underground punk rock scene|last=Roberts|first=Randall|date=|website=Los Angeles Times|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n'''''Hawaiian: The Legend of Eddie Aikau''''' (2013)\u2014 Documentary Feature, dir. Sam George\n\n[Winner: Emmy Award for Best Sports Documentary Series]\n\n\u25ca Producer\u2014 ESPN \u201830 for 30\u2019<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tribecafilm.com/festival/archive/51471ed0c07f5d4659000002-hawaiian-the-legend-of-ed|title=Hawaiian: The Legend of Eddi Aikau|last=|first=|date=|website=Tribeca Film. Com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n'''''No Room for Rockstars''''' (2012)\u2014 Documentary Feature of the 2010 Warped Tour, dir. Parris Patton\n\n[Official Selection: Slamdance Film Festival, Hot Docs]\n\n\u25ca Producer\u2014 Agi Orsi Productions<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1996339/fullcredits/?ref_=tt_ov_st_sm|title=No Room for Rock Stars (Full Cast and Crew)|last=|first=|date=|website=IMDB|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n'''''Lost Angels: Skid Row is my Home''''' (2010)\u2014 Documentary feature, dir. Thomas Napper\n\n\u25ca Producer\u2014 Agi Orsi Productions<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cinemalibrestudio.com/skidrowismyhome/production_team.html|title=Los Angels: Production Crew|last=|first=|date=|website=Cinema Libre Studio|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n'''''Amazing Journey: The Story of the Who''''' (2007)\u2014 Documentary Feature,\n\n\u25ca Producer\u2014 Spitfire Films/Universal Pictures \u00a0 \u200bdir. Paul Crowder, Murray Lerner<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0462441/fullcredits/?ref_=tt_ov_st_sm|title=Amazing Journey: Story of the Who  (Full Cast and Crew)|last=|first=|date=|website=IMDB|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n'''''Riding Giants''''' (2004)\u2014 Documentary Feature, dir. Stacy Peralta\n\n[Opener: Sundance Film Festival]\n\n\u25ca Producer\u2014 Agi Orsi Productions/Studio Canal<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2004/07/09/movies/film-review-no-more-hunt-for-the-perfect-wave-the-thrill-is-finding-the-scariest.html|title=Riding Giants: No More Hunt for the Perfect Wave|last=Holden|first=Stephen|date=2004|website=New York Times|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n'''''Dogtown and Z-Boys''''' (2001)\u2014 Documentary feature, dir. Stacy Peralta\n\n[Winner: Sundance Audience Award, Sundance Directing Award]\n\n\u25ca Producer\u2014 Agi Orsi Productions/Sony Pictures Classics <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2002/04/26/movies/film-review-skating-on-top-of-the-world-during-an-endless-summer.html)|title=Review: Skating on Top of the World|last=Holden|first=Stephen|date=2002|website=New York Times|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n'''''Curtain of Ice''''' (1991)-Documentary Feature, dir. John Armstrong, narrator Hal Holbrook.\n\n(Winner: Telluride Mountain film prize for Best Adventure Film, CINE Golden Eagle,\n\nBronze Award at Houston World Fest, Apple Education Award at the Oakland Film Festival.)\n\nProducer-Agi Orsi Productions/Travel Channel.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mountainfilm.org/festival/personalities/john-armstrong|title=John Armstrong|last=Armtrong|first=John|date=|website=John Armstrong|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n'''''Bashkaus: Hard Labor in Siberia''''' (1990)\u2014 Documentary feature, dir. John Armstrong\n\n\u25ca Producer\u2014 Agi Orsi Productions/Discovery Channel<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0650709/bio|title=Agi Orsi Bio|last=|first=|date=|website=IMDB|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.deseret.com/1989/10/15/18828526/river-rafting-in-siberia-is-topic-of-documentary|title=River Rafting in Siberia is Topic of Documentary|last=|first=|date=1989|website=Desert News|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Uncategorized|date=April 2020|documentary filmmakers=female documentary makers|female documentary makers=|Agi Orsi=documentary film maker}}\n", "text_old": "'''Agi Orsi''' is an independent Los Angeles-based documentary filmmaker<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0650709/|title=Agi Orsi|last=|first=|date=|website=IMDB|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> who produces films for television and for theatrical release on music and sports subcultures, as well as socially relevant themes, such as the criminalization of homelessness and the challenges of living on the street with mental illness. The subjects of her productions include kayakers achieving a diplomatic triumph in a joint U-Soviet expedition,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.deseret.com/1989/10/15/18828526/river-rafting-in-siberia-is-topic-of-documentary|title=River Rafting in Siberia is Topic of Documentary|last=|first=|date=1989|website=Desert News|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0650709/bio|title=Agi Orsi Bio|last=|first=|date=|website=IMDB|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> rebellious Venice skateboarders carving their separate identity in a surf-dominated culture,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2001/film/reviews/dogtown-and-z-boys-1200466864/|title=Dogtown and Z-Boys|last=Harvey|first=Dennis|date=2001|website=Variety|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=2001|access-date=}}</ref> a courageous Hawaiian surfer remembered as the symbol of Aloha or kindness for risking his life to save others,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tribecafilm.com/festival/archive/51471ed0c07f5d4659000002-hawaiian-the-legend-of-ed|title=Hawaiian: The Legend of Eddie Aikau|last=|first=|date=|website=TribecaFilm.Com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> the backyard punk rock scene in East Los Angeles<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/music/la-et-los-punks-movie-20160525-snap-story.html|title=Los Punks\u2019 documentary goes behind the scenes of L.A.'s underground punk rock scene|last=Roberts|first=Randall|date=2016|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> where homegrown musicians, not music conglomerates, set the tone, and struggling Skid Row homeless building community and embracing hope despite widespread despair and drug abuse.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cinemalibrestudio.com/skidrowismyhome/production_team.html|title=Lost Angels: Production Team|last=|first=|date=2018|website=Cinema Libre Studio|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nOrsi is the Founder of Agi Orsi Productions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://open.spotify.com/playlist/26jh0hj7TQfsPtlGrOIjbn|title=Agi Orsi Productions-Riding Giants|last=|first=|date=|website=Spotify|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nIn addition to producing for theater and television, Orsi is a DGA Unit Production Manager on most of her documentaries.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://m.imdb.com/name/nm0650709/filmotype/production_manager?ref_=m_nmfm_2|title=Agi Orsi: Unit Production Manager|last=|first=|date=|website=IMDB|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n== Education ==\nA native of Budapest, Hungary, fluent in English, French and Hungarian, Orsi received her Masters in French Language and Civilization from Universit\u00e9 Panth\u00e9 on Sorbonne in Paris.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cinemalibrestudio.com/skidrowismyhome/production_team.html|title=Los Angels: Production Team|last=|first=|date=|website=Cinema Libre Studio|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> \u00a0\n\n== Philanthropy ==\nOrsi serves on the Board of Housing Works,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://housingworksca.org/team/|title=Board of Directors|last=|first=|date=|website=Housing Works|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> a non-profit organization committed to providing supportive housing for the homeless, and participates in film forums to promote independent documentary film making and mentor aspiring documentarians.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.workingfilms.org/reel-change-in-the-bay-area/|title=Reel Change: Managing Social Issue Film Campaigns|last=|first=|date=|website=Working Films|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n== Film Financing ==\nTo finance '''''Dogtown and Z-Boys''''', Orsi sought and obtained financing from Vans shoe manufacturing company, which manufactured deck shoes with \"sticky souls\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vans.com/history.html|title=A BRIEF HISTORY OF VANS:\n\u201cOFF THE WALL\u201d SINCE \u201866\nVans 50 Years (Off The Wall Since 1966)|last=|first=|date=|website=Vans Off the Wall|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> popular with skateboarders in the 70s.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.documentary.org/feature/and-now-word-about-sponsors-taking-corporate-route-funding-your-project|title=And Now, A Word About Sponsors: Taking the Corporate Route to Funding Your Project|last=Fairweather|first=Kathleen|date=2003|website=IDA (International Documentary Association)|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=2003|access-date=}}</ref> Although the deal with Vans was negotiated quickly, Orsi acknowledged most film financing involves a longer process of negotiation. In a 2003 interview with the International Documentary Association, Orsi said, \"Once we got the awards at Sundance, we had many suitors for a distribution deal. Vans consulted on everything with us. We were true partners.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.documentary.org/feature/and-now-word-about-sponsors-taking-corporate-route-funding-your-project|title=And Now, A Word About Sponsors: Taking the Corporate Route to Funding Your Project|last=Fairweather|first=Kathleen|date=2003|website=IDA (International Documentary  Association)|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n== Most Notable Awards & Recognition ==\nMost notable is Orsi's collaboration with documentary film director and skateboarder Stacey Peralta to win '''Sundance Festival's Audience and Best Director''' award for '''''Dogtown and Z-Boys''''',<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2002/04/26/movies/film-review-skating-on-top-of-the-world-during-an-endless-summer.html)|title=FILM REVIEW; Skating on Top of the World During an Endless Summer|last=Holden|first=Stephen|date=2002|website=New York Times|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> a documentary, narrated by Sean Penn, that explores the world of skateboarding, its impact on surf culture and the disturbing aftermath of lost stardom. Orsi again teamed with Peralta to produce '''''Riding Giants''''' (Studio Canal/Sony Classics), the first documentary to ever open the Sundance Film Festival and winner of the 2004 '''A.C.E. Eddie Award''' for '''Best Edited Documentary'''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.emmys.com/news/ace-eddies-named-top-editing-prizes-handed-out|title=A.C.E. Eddies Named Top Editing Prizes Handed Out|last=|first=|date=2005|website=Emmys.Com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> by editor Paul Crowder. In Riding Giants director Stacy Peralta pays tribute to the adventurous surfers riding the world's most daunting 20-foot high waves, only to yearn for even more challenging thrill rides.\n\nAdditionally Orsi worked with director and professional surfer Sam George to produce '''''Hawaiian: The Legend of Eddie Aikau''''' (ESPN''''')'''''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://finance.yahoo.com/news/espn-films-30-30-hawaiian-154949024.html|title=ESPN Films: \"30 for 30\" \"Hawaiian: The Legend of Eddie Aikau\" Wins Emmy Award|last=|first=|date=|website=Yahoo Finance/Marketwired|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=May 29, 2014|access-date=}}</ref>''',''' a biographical film of the big wave surfer Eddie Aikau who became the symbol of Aloha and celebration of Hawaiian culture. The documentary premiered on [[ESPN]] on October 1, 2013 and won an '''Emmy for Best Sports Documentary Series''', making it one of the few surf-related films to ever receive such recognition.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.westhawaiitoday.com/2014/05/29/hawaii-news/hawaiian-the-legend-of-eddie-aikau-wins-emmy-award/|title=Hawaiian: The Legend of Eddie Aikau|last=|first=|date=2020|website=West Hawaii Today|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The documentary that chronicles Aikau's emergence as a legendary surfer and lifeguard who saved lives but lost his own at sea also won awards for '''Best Picture and Best Director at the Malibu International Film Festival'''; '''Best Picture, Best Documentary and Audience Favorite at the Maui Film Festival''', as well as '''Best Documentary at Surfer Poll'''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.westhawaiitoday.com/2014/05/29/hawaii-news/hawaiian-the-legend-of-eddie-aikau-wins-emmy-award/|title=Hawaiian: The Legend of Eddi Akau|last=|first=|date=2020|website=West Hawaii Today|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nOrsi's foray into documentary filmmaking began when she teamed with director John Armstrong to produce '''''Bashkaus: Hard Labor in Siberia'''''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0650709/bio|title=Agi Orsi Bio|last=|first=|date=|website=IMDB|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>''',''' (Discovery Channel), a film that won a '''Gold Medal Living Book Award''' and the '''Grand Prize at the Telluride Mountain Film Festival'''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mountainfilm.org/festival/personalities/john-armstrong|title=John Armstrong|last=|first=|date=|website=John Armstrong|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> for chronicling the first joint US-Soviet river expedition in Russia's Altai Mountains during a thaw in the Cold War.\u00a0 Following that, Orsi teamed again with Armstrong to produce '''''Curtain of Ice''''' <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.worldcat.org/title/curtain-of-ice/oclc/27479917|title=Curtain of Ice|last=|first=|date=|website=World Cat|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>(Discovery Channel), documenting the first-on water crossing of the Bering Strait, the \"Curtain of Ice,\" reuniting Eskimos separated for decades during the US-Russia arms escalation. The documentary also tells the story of Jim Noyes, a paraplegic with a broken spine who finds a new purpose for living after making the crossing.\n\nDeparting from the adventure sports genre, Orsi served as supervising producer on '''''Amazing Journey: The Story of The Who''''',<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0462441/fullcredits/?ref_=tt_ov_st_sm|title=Amazing Journey: The Story of the Who|last=|first=|date=|website=IMDB|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> a 2007 documentary '''''nominated for a Grammy''' '''Award''''',<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.grammy.com/grammys/artists/who|title=The Who|last=|first=|date=|website=Grammy.Com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> co-directed by [[Murray Lerner]] and [[Paul Crowder (filmmaker)|Paul Crowder]], integrating archival footage of The Who's concerts at Monterrey and Woodstock and interviews with the stars of the English band known for its ear-shattering volumes and distortions, as well as its mixture of pop hits, traditional jazz, rock and R & B. The film's soundtrack features a compilation of the band's greatest hits, among them the single, \"My Generation,\" written by Peter Townshend. Included in the documentary is original footage, never seen before, of the 1970 Leeds University appearance in which The Who's performance disintegrated into \"chaotic noise\" as a result of amphetamine use, resulting in a fist fight between band members and the temporary expulsion of lead singer Roger Daltrey.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ultimateclassicrock.com/daltrey-walks-out-on-who/|title=When Roger Daltrey Walked Out, Then Right Back into the Who|last=Wawzenek|first=Bryan|date=|website=Ultimate Classic Rock|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nFar from the concert stage, Orsi went to downtown Los Angeles to produce '''''Lost Angels: Skid Row is My Home''''', a documentary that evolved from the 2009 movie \u201cThe Soloist.\u201d Starring Robert Downey Jr. and Jamie Foxx, The Soloist is based on stories LA Times columnist Steve Lopez wrote about a Julliard-educated homeless musician. In contrast to The Soloist's laser focus on the musician, Lost Angels weaves together the stories of several Skid Row residents and extras from The Soloist, including a cat lover who feeds stray cats as she wheels carts of trash up and down Skid Row, an Olympic athlete and track and field coach tormented by drug addiction, a gospel singer with a rare congenital disease and a transgender Vietnam Veteran.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/business/la-xpm-2011-oct-12-la-fi-ct-onlocation-20111012-story.html|title=On Location: \u2018Lost Angels\u2019 documentary focuses on L.A. skid row|last=Verrier|first=Richard|date=2011|website=Los Angeles Times|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.reellifewithjane.com/2013/05/review-lost-angels-skid-row-is-my-home/|title=Film Review & Perspective: \u2018Lost Angels: Skid Row Is My Home\u2019|last=Miraz|first=Jacqueline|date=May 20, 2013|website=Reel Life with Jane|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nThe documentary, released in 2009 by Paramount Pictures, was financed for $300,000 by DreamWorks and Universal Pictures and Participant Media, with contributions from the Hilton Foundation and Community Supportive Housing, takes a critical look at then Mayor Antonio Villaraigosa's Safer City Initiative which made it a crime to panhandle, sleep, sit or store personal items on sidewalks and other public spaces.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-homeless-losangeles/los-angeles-accused-of-criminalizing-homelessness-idUSTRE56E0MC20090715|title=Los Angeles accused of criminalizing homelessness|last=Gorman|first=Steve|date=2009|website=Reuters|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The film, narrated by actress Catherine Keener, points to the success of supportive housing with wrap-around mental health and employment services.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cinemalibrestudio.com/skidrowismyhome/get_involved.html|title=Lost Angels: Skid Row is my Home|last=|first=|date=|website=Cinema Libre Studio|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nLos Angeles earned recognition for the following awards: '''2011 Voice Award from SAMHSA''' (Substance Abuse and Mental Health Services Administration) and '''Ghetto Award-Radar Hamburg International Film Festival.''' The documentary was also an official selection for the Los Angeles Film Festival (Premiere), One World Human Rights Film Festival (Prague), Human Rights Film Festival (London), Oaxaca Film Festival, among others.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cinemalibrestudio.com/skidrowismyhome/assets/lost-angels-press-notes-FINAL.pdf|title=Lost Angels: Skid Row is My Home|last=|first=|date=|website=Cinema Libre Studio|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nOrsi also produced '''''Los Punks; We Are All We Have''''', a 2016 documentary financed by Vans that explores the punk rock scene blaring from backyards and dirt lots in East Los Angeles, Boyle Heights and South Los Angeles, where the mohawk-sporting musicians, some with troubled pasts\u2014suicide attempts, police arrests\u2014do not need corporate music conglomerates or concert venues to make a name for their hardcore selves. Los Punks, directed by punk rocker Angela Boatwright, premiered at the 2016 Slamdance Film Festival, where critics applauded its gritty depiction of homegrown East LA music bands\u2014Las Cochinas, Corrupted Youth, Rhythmic Asylum\u2014integrated with poignant personal stories.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/music/la-et-los-punks-movie-20160525-snap-story.html|title='Los Punks\u2019 documentary goes behind the scenes of L.A.'s underground punk rock scene|last=Roberts|first=Randall|date=May 26, 2016|website=LA Times|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n== Filmography ==\n\n'''''Los Punks; We Are All We Have''''' (2016)\u2014 Documentary feature, dir. Angela Boatwright\n\n[Official Selection: Slamdance Film Festival, East End Film Festival]\n\n\u25ca Producer\u2014 Agi Orsi Productions <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/music/la-et-los-punks-movie-20160525-snap-story.html|title=Los Punks\u2019 documentary goes behind the scenes of L.A.'s underground punk rock scene|last=Roberts|first=Randall|date=|website=Los Angeles Times|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n'''''Hawaiian: The Legend of Eddie Aikau''''' (2013)\u2014 Documentary Feature, dir. Sam George\n\n[Winner: Emmy Award for Best Sports Documentary Series]\n\n\u25ca Producer\u2014 ESPN \u201830 for 30\u2019<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tribecafilm.com/festival/archive/51471ed0c07f5d4659000002-hawaiian-the-legend-of-ed|title=Hawaiian: The Legend of Eddi Aikau|last=|first=|date=|website=Tribeca Film. Com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n'''''No Room for Rockstars''''' (2012)\u2014 Documentary Feature of the 2010 Warped Tour, dir. Parris Patton\n\n[Official Selection: Slamdance Film Festival, Hot Docs]\n\n\u25ca Producer\u2014 Agi Orsi Productions<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1996339/fullcredits/?ref_=tt_ov_st_sm|title=No Room for Rock Stars (Full Cast and Crew)|last=|first=|date=|website=IMDB|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n'''''Lost Angels: Skid Row is my Home''''' (2010)\u2014 Documentary feature, dir. Thomas Napper\n\n\u25ca Producer\u2014 Agi Orsi Productions<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cinemalibrestudio.com/skidrowismyhome/production_team.html|title=Los Angels: Production Crew|last=|first=|date=|website=Cinema Libre Studio|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n'''''Amazing Journey: The Story of the Who''''' (2007)\u2014 Documentary Feature,\n\n\u25ca Producer\u2014 Spitfire Films/Universal Pictures \u00a0 \u200bdir. Paul Crowder, Murray Lerner<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0462441/fullcredits/?ref_=tt_ov_st_sm|title=Amazing Journey: Story of the Who  (Full Cast and Crew)|last=|first=|date=|website=IMDB|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n'''''Riding Giants''''' (2004)\u2014 Documentary Feature, dir. Stacy Peralta\n\n[Opener: Sundance Film Festival]\n\n\u25ca Producer\u2014 Agi Orsi Productions/Studio Canal<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2004/07/09/movies/film-review-no-more-hunt-for-the-perfect-wave-the-thrill-is-finding-the-scariest.html|title=Riding Giants: No More Hunt for the Perfect Wave|last=Holden|first=Stephen|date=2004|website=New York Times|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n'''''Dogtown and Z-Boys''''' (2001)\u2014 Documentary feature, dir. Stacy Peralta\n\n[Winner: Sundance Audience Award, Sundance Directing Award]\n\n\u25ca Producer\u2014 Agi Orsi Productions/Sony Pictures Classics <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2002/04/26/movies/film-review-skating-on-top-of-the-world-during-an-endless-summer.html)|title=Review: Skating on Top of the World|last=Holden|first=Stephen|date=2002|website=New York Times|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n'''''Curtain of Ice''''' (1991)-Documentary Feature, dir. John Armstrong, narrator Hal Holbrook.\n\n(Winner: Telluride Mountain film prize for Best Adventure Film, CINE Golden Eagle,\n\nBronze Award at Houston World Fest, Apple Education Award at the Oakland Film Festival.)\n\nProducer-Agi Orsi Productions/Travel Channel.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mountainfilm.org/festival/personalities/john-armstrong|title=John Armstrong|last=Armtrong|first=John|date=|website=John Armstrong|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n'''''Bashkaus: Hard Labor in Siberia''''' (1990)\u2014 Documentary feature, dir. John Armstrong\n\n\u25ca Producer\u2014 Agi Orsi Productions/Discovery Channel<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0650709/bio|title=Agi Orsi Bio|last=|first=|date=|website=IMDB|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.deseret.com/1989/10/15/18828526/river-rafting-in-siberia-is-topic-of-documentary|title=River Rafting in Siberia is Topic of Documentary|last=|first=|date=1989|website=Desert News|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Uncategorized|date=April 2020}}\n", "name_user": "Marcywinograd", "label": "safe", "comment": "dates formatted", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Agi_Orsi"}
{"title_page": "James Ewing (pathologist)", "text_new": "[[File:Ewing.jpg|James Ewing|thumb]]\n\n'''James Stephen Ewing''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|ju\u02d0|\u026a|\u014b}}) (December 25, 1866, [[Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania|Pittsburgh]] \u2013 May 16, 1943, [[New York City]]) was an American [[Pathology|pathologist]]. He was the first Professor of [[pathology]] at [[Cornell University]] and became famous with the discovery of a form of malignant [[bone]] [[tumor]] that later became known as [[Ewing's sarcoma]].\n\n==Life==\nJames Ewing, was born in 1866 to a prominent family of Pittsburgh.  When he was 14 he was diagnosed with [[osteomyelitis]] and was bedridden for two years.<ref name=Index>Simon Cotterill for Cancer Index. [http://www.cancerindex.org/bone/ewing.htm About James Ewing, 1866 - 1943] Last modified: 16/03/99</ref> He first completed his B.A. in 1888 at [[Amherst College]] and then studied [[medicine]] at the [[Columbia University College of Physicians and Surgeons|College of Physicians and Surgeons of New York]], from 1888 to 1891.<ref name=BrandBio>Brand RA. Biographical sketch: James Stephen Ewing, MD (1844-1943). Clin Orthop Relat Res. 2012 Mar;470(3):639-41. {{PMID|22207564}} [https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3270161/ PMC 3270161]</ref>  He returned to the College of Physicians and Surgeons as instructor in [[histology]] (1893-1897), and clinical pathology (1897-1898). After a brief stint as a surgeon with the US Army, Ewing was appointed in 1899 the first professor of clinical pathology at the newly formed Medical College of [[Cornell University]] in New York, where he was the only full-time professor.<ref name=BrandBio/><ref name=NASbio/><ref>{{cite book|title=The Register|date=1915|publisher=Cornell University|page=110|edition=Volumes 15-18|accessdate=}}</ref>  In 1902, Ewing helped to establish one of the first funds for cancer research, endowed by [[Arabella Huntington|Mrs. Collis P. Huntington]].<ref name=NASbio/> With his discoveries using that research funding, Ewing became the most important experimental [[oncology|oncologist]] and helped to found, in 1907, the [[American Association for Cancer Research]], and in 1913, the American Society for the Control of Cancer, now the [[American Cancer Society]].<ref name=BrandBio/><ref name=NASbio/>  In 1906 Ewing, working with [[S.P. Beebe]] and collaborators, proved for the first time that a cancer ([[canine transmissible venereal tumor]] in dogs) could be transmitted from one animal to another.<ref name=BrandBio/><ref>Ewing, James & Beebe, S. P. (1906). A study of the so-called infectious lympho-sarcoma of dogs. Journal of Med. Research. 10:209.</ref><ref>Beebe, S. P., and James Ewing. (1906). \"A study of the biology of tumour cells. \"The British Medical Journal\": 1559-1560.</ref>\n\nIn 1910, Ewing had approached [[New York Hospital]] about establishing a clinical research facility; when this fell through, he established a collaboration with Memorial Hospital (which would become [[Memorial Sloan Kettering Cancer Center]]) with the help of industrialist and philanthropist [[James Douglas (businessman)|James Douglas]], who gave $100,000 to endow twenty beds for clinical research, equipment for working with [[radium]], and a clinical laboratory to Memorial for that purpose.<ref name=NASbio/>  Douglas' enthusiasm and funding for development of [[radiation therapy]] for cancer inspired Ewing to become one of the pioneers in developing this treatment.<ref name=NASbio/>  Ewing soon took over effective leadership of clinical and laboratory research at Memorial.<ref name=NASbio/>\n\nIn 1919 Ewing published the first edition of ''Neoplastic Diseases: A Text-Book on Tumors''.<ref>Ewing, James. (1919). Neoplastic Diseases: A Textbook on Tumors. Philadelphia, W. B. Saunders, and London. Fourth edition 1940.</ref> The book, which is translated into numerous languages, becomes a cornerstone of modern oncology by establishing a systematic and comprehensive basis for diagnosing human cancer.<ref name=NASbio/> In 1921 he published his first work on a new kind of malignant [[osteoma]] (cancer of the [[bone]]), which later received his name: [[Ewing's sarcoma]].<ref name=BrandBio/><ref>Ewing, James. (1922). Neoplastic diseases: a treatise on tumors. WB Saunders Company.</ref><ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Pritchard | first1 = J. E. | year = 1927 | title = EWING'S SARCOMA: A REPORT OF A CASE | url = | journal = Canadian Medical Association Journal | volume = 17 | issue = 10| page = 1164 }}</ref>\n\nIn 1931 Ewing was formally appointed president of the hospital<ref name=BrandBio/> and was featured on the cover of Time Magazine as \"Cancer Man Ewing\";<ref>Time Magazine [http://www.time.com/time/covers/0,16641,1101310112,00.html Cover], January 12, 1931</ref> the accompanying article described his role as one of the most important cancer doctors of his era.<ref>Cancer Crusade. Jan 12, 1931. Time Magazine 17(2):26</ref>  He worked at the Memorial until his retirement, in 1939.<ref name=BrandBio/>\n\nUnder his leadership, Memorial became a model for other cancer centers in the United States, combining patient care with clinical and laboratory research,<ref name=EwingLecture>{{cite journal|last1=Wilkins|first1=Sam A. Jr.|title=James Ewing Society, 1940-1969: Presidential Address|journal=Cancer|volume=25|issue=2|url=http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/store/10.1002/1097-0142(197002)25:2%3C321::AID-CNCR2820250207%3E3.0.CO;2-R/asset/2820250207_ftp.pdf?v=1&t=imbfy6ah&s=eba11907ae69c486cdb6c017017da73258a6291e|pages=321\u2013323|date=25 Feb 1970|pmid=4905156|doi=10.1002/1097-0142(197002)25:2<321::AID-CNCR2820250207>3.0.CO;2-R}}{{Dead link|date=January 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> and it was said of him that \"The relationship of Ewing to the Memorial Hospital can best be expressed in the words of Emerson, 'Every institution is but the lengthening\nshadow of some man.' Dr. Ewing is the Memorial Hospital\".<ref name=NASbio>James B. Murphy [http://www.nasonline.org/publications/biographical-memoirs/memoir-pdfs/ewing-james.pdf James Ewing Biographical Memoir] National Academy of Sciences Washington D.C., 1951.</ref>\n\nIn 1951, The James Ewing Hospital, a 12-story building on First Avenue between 67th and 68th Streets, opened; it was intended to treat cancer among New York City's poor.<ref>New developments in cancer, CA: A Cancer Journal for Clinicians, Volume 1, Issue 2, pages 64\u201367, January 1951.</ref>\n\n==Bibliography==\nA collection of his correspondence is held at the National Library of Medicine.<ref>[https://www.nlm.nih.gov/hmd/manuscripts/msc.html Manuscripts at NLM]</ref>\n\n* Zantinga, AR; Coppes, MJ: James Ewing (1866-1943): \"the chief\". ''Medical and Pediatric Oncology'', New York, 1993, 21 (7): 505-510.\n* Huvos, AG: James Ewing: cancer man. ''Annals of Diagnostic Pathology'', April 1998, 2 (2): 146-148.\n* Ewing, J: ''Clinical pathology of Blood: A Treatise on the General Principles and Special Applications of Hematology.'' Philadelphia and New York, 1901.\n* Ewing, J: ''Neoplastic Diseases: A Textbook on Tumors.'' Philadelphia, W. B. Saunders, and London, 1919. Fourth edition 1940.\n* Ewing, J: ''Causation, Diagnosis and Treatment of Cancer.'' Baltimore, 1931.\n* Ewing, J: ''Blood''. Philadelphia. 1910.\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ewing, James}}\n[[Category:1866 births]]\n[[Category:1943 deaths]]\n[[Category:American pathologists]]\n[[Category:American oncologists]]\n[[Category:Cornell University faculty]]\n[[Category:Scientists from Pittsburgh]]\n[[Category:Deaths from bladder cancer]]\n[[Category:Amherst College alumni]]\n[[Category:Deaths from cancer in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Columbia University College of Physicians and Surgeons alumni]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Ewing.jpg|James Ewing|thumb]]\n\n'''James Stephen Ewing''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|ju\u02d0|\u026a|\u014b}}) (December 25, 1866, [[Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania|Pittsburgh]] \u2013 May 16, 1943, [[New York City]]) was an American [[Pathology|pathologist]]. He was the first Professor of [[pathology]] at [[Cornell University]] and became famous with the discovery of a form of malignant [[bone]] [[tumor]] that later became known as [[Ewing's sarcoma]].\n\n==Life==\nJames Ewing, was born in 1866 to a prominent family of Pittsburgh.  When he was 14 he was diagnosed with [[osteomyelitis]] and was bedridden for two years.<ref name=Index>Simon Cotterill for Cancer Index. [http://www.cancerindex.org/bone/ewing.htm About James Ewing, 1866 - 1943] Last modified: 16/03/99</ref> He first completed his B.A. in 1888 at [[Amherst College]] and then studied [[medicine]] at the [[Columbia University College of Physicians and Surgeons|College of Physicians and Surgeons of New York]], from 1888 to 1891.<ref name=BrandBio>Brand RA. Biographical sketch: James Stephen Ewing, MD (1844-1943). Clin Orthop Relat Res. 2012 Mar;470(3):639-41. {{PMID|22207564}} [https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3270161/ PMC 3270161]</ref>  He returned to the College of Physicians and Surgeons as instructor in [[histology]] (1893-1897), and clinical pathology (1897-1898). After a brief stint as a surgeon with the US Army, Ewing was appointed in 1899 the first professor of clinical pathology at the newly formed Medical College of [[Cornell University]] in New York, where he was the only full-time professor.<ref name=BrandBio/><ref name=NASbio/><ref>{{cite book|title=The Register|date=1915|publisher=Cornell University|page=110|edition=Volumes 15-18|accessdate=}}</ref>  In 1902, Ewing helped to establish one of the first funds for cancer research, endowed by [[Arabella Huntington|Mrs. Collis P. Huntington]].<ref name=NASbio/> With his discoveries using that research funding, Ewing became the most important experimental [[oncology|oncologist]] and helped to found, in 1907, the [[American Association for Cancer Research]], and in 1913, the American Society for the Control of Cancer, now the [[American Cancer Society]].<ref name=BrandBio/><ref name=NASbio/>  In 1906 Ewing, working with [[S.P. Beebe]] and collaborators, proved for the first time that a cancer ([[canine transmissible venereal tumor]] in dogs) could be transmitted from one animal to another.<ref name=BrandBio/><ref>Ewing, James & Beebe, S. P. (1906). A study of the so-called infectious lympho-sarcoma of dogs. Journal of Med. Research. 10:209.</ref><ref>Beebe, S. P., and James Ewing. (1906). \"A study of the biology of tumour cells. \"The British Medical Journal\": 1559-1560.</ref>\n\nIn 1910, Ewing had approached [[New York Hospital]] about establishing a clinical research facility; when this fell through, he established a collaboration with Memorial Hospital (which would become [[Memorial Sloan Kettering Cancer Center]]) with the help of industrialist and philanthropist [[James Douglas (businessman)|James Douglas]], who gave $100,000 to endow twenty beds for clinical research, equipment for working with [[radium]], and a clinical laboratory to Memorial for that purpose.<ref name=NASbio/>  Douglas' enthusiasm and funding for development of [[radiation therapy]] for cancer inspired Ewing to become one of the pioneers in developing this treatment.<ref name=NASbio/>  Ewing soon took over effective leadership of clinical and laboratory research at Memorial.<ref name=NASbio/>\n\nIn 1919 Ewing published the first edition of ''Neoplastic Diseases: A Text-Book on Tumors''.<ref>Ewing, James. (1919). Neoplastic Diseases: A Textbook on Tumors. Philadelphia, W. B. Saunders, and London. Fourth edition 1940.</ref> The book, which is translated into numerous languages, becomes a cornerstone of modern oncology by establishing a systematic and comprehensive basis for diagnosing human cancer.<ref name=NASbio/> In 1921 he published his first work on a new kind of malignant [[osteoma]] (cancer of the [[bone]]), which later received his name: [[Ewing's sarcoma]].<ref name=BrandBio/><ref>Ewing, James. (1922). Neoplastic diseases: a treatise on tumors. WB Saunders Company.</ref><ref>Pritchard, J. E. (1927). EWING'S SARCOMA: A REPORT OF A CASE. Canadian Medical Association Journal, 17(10 Pt 1), 1164.</ref>\n\nIn 1931 Ewing was formally appointed president of the hospital<ref name=BrandBio/> and was featured on the cover of Time Magazine as \"Cancer Man Ewing\";<ref>Time Magazine [http://www.time.com/time/covers/0,16641,1101310112,00.html Cover], January 12, 1931</ref> the accompanying article described his role as one of the most important cancer doctors of his era.<ref>Cancer Crusade. Jan 12, 1931. Time Magazine 17(2):26</ref>  He worked at the Memorial until his retirement, in 1939.<ref name=BrandBio/>\n\nUnder his leadership, Memorial became a model for other cancer centers in the United States, combining patient care with clinical and laboratory research,<ref name=EwingLecture>{{cite journal|last1=Wilkins|first1=Sam A. Jr.|title=James Ewing Society, 1940-1969: Presidential Address|journal=Cancer|volume=25|issue=2|url=http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/store/10.1002/1097-0142(197002)25:2%3C321::AID-CNCR2820250207%3E3.0.CO;2-R/asset/2820250207_ftp.pdf?v=1&t=imbfy6ah&s=eba11907ae69c486cdb6c017017da73258a6291e|pages=321\u2013323|date=25 Feb 1970|pmid=4905156|doi=10.1002/1097-0142(197002)25:2<321::AID-CNCR2820250207>3.0.CO;2-R}}{{Dead link|date=January 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> and it was said of him that \"The relationship of Ewing to the Memorial Hospital can best be expressed in the words of Emerson, 'Every institution is but the lengthening\nshadow of some man.' Dr. Ewing is the Memorial Hospital\".<ref name=NASbio>James B. Murphy [http://www.nasonline.org/publications/biographical-memoirs/memoir-pdfs/ewing-james.pdf James Ewing Biographical Memoir] National Academy of Sciences Washington D.C., 1951.</ref>\n\nIn 1951, The James Ewing Hospital, a 12-story building on First Avenue between 67th and 68th Streets, opened; it was intended to treat cancer among New York City's poor.<ref>New developments in cancer, CA: A Cancer Journal for Clinicians, Volume 1, Issue 2, pages 64\u201367, January 1951.</ref>\n\n==Bibliography==\nA collection of his correspondence is held at the National Library of Medicine.<ref>[https://www.nlm.nih.gov/hmd/manuscripts/msc.html Manuscripts at NLM]</ref>\n\n* Zantinga, AR; Coppes, MJ: James Ewing (1866-1943): \"the chief\". ''Medical and Pediatric Oncology'', New York, 1993, 21 (7): 505-510.\n* Huvos, AG: James Ewing: cancer man. ''Annals of Diagnostic Pathology'', April 1998, 2 (2): 146-148.\n* Ewing, J: ''Clinical pathology of Blood: A Treatise on the General Principles and Special Applications of Hematology.'' Philadelphia and New York, 1901.\n* Ewing, J: ''Neoplastic Diseases: A Textbook on Tumors.'' Philadelphia, W. B. Saunders, and London, 1919. Fourth edition 1940.\n* Ewing, J: ''Causation, Diagnosis and Treatment of Cancer.'' Baltimore, 1931.\n* Ewing, J: ''Blood''. Philadelphia. 1910.\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ewing, James}}\n[[Category:1866 births]]\n[[Category:1943 deaths]]\n[[Category:American pathologists]]\n[[Category:American oncologists]]\n[[Category:Cornell University faculty]]\n[[Category:Scientists from Pittsburgh]]\n[[Category:Deaths from bladder cancer]]\n[[Category:Amherst College alumni]]\n[[Category:Deaths from cancer in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Columbia University College of Physicians and Surgeons alumni]]\n", "name_user": "Rjwilmsi", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eLife:Journal cites:,", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/James_Ewing_(pathologist)"}
