fia: The Government's Secret File on Organized Crime.'' HarperCollins, 2009. {{ISBN|0061363855}}.\n*Volkman, Ernest. ''Gangbusters: The Destruction of America's Last Mafia Dynasty''. Faber & Faber, 1998. {{ISBN|0380732351}}\n\n===Newspaper articles===\n*[https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9804E5D61030F931A15752C0A9659C8B63&n=Top%2fReference%2fTimes%20Topics%2fSubjects%2fO%2fOrganized%20Crime New York Times: Ex-Crime Boss Testifies In Gotti Trial] by William Glaberson\n*[https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=950CEEDB153FF93AA15753C1A9649C8B63&n=Top%2fReference%2fTimes%20Topics%2fSubjects%2fO%2fOrganized%20Crime New York Times: Former Crime Boss Testifies] by Benjamin Weiser\n*[https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9C05EED7123EF935A3575AC0A9649C8B63&n=Top%2fReference%2fTimes%20Topics%2fSubjects%2fO%2fOrganized%20Crime New York Times: Guilty Plea In Mafia Case] by Benjamin Weiser\n*[https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=950DE3D8173AF93BA35751C1A96E958260&n=Top%2fReference%2fTimes%20Topics%2fSubjects%2fO%2fOrganized%20Crime New York Times: Reputed Crime Boss Enters a Guilty Plea]\n*[https://www.nytimes.com/2010/05/02/nyregion/02mafia.html New York Times: After Mob, Joe DeFede, Ex-Crime Boss, Is Scraping By]\n*New York Daily News: [http://webcache.googleusercontent.com/search?q=cache:qaIhyO1AWz4J:articles.nydailynews.com/2002-10-30/news/18205351_1_luchese-shakedown-mob+Joe+Defede+died&cd=5&hl=en&ct=clnk&gl=us Little Joe Sings About Shakedowns]{{dead link|date=April 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} by Robert Gearty (October 30, 2002)\n*[http://www.nydailynews.com/news/ny_crime/galleries/rats_mob_informants/rats_mob_informants.html Mob informants \"Peter \"Fat Pete\" Chiodo\"] New York Daily News\n*[http://www.laborers.org/AP_Mob_2-27-85.html Associated Press Sketches of 9 Arrested], an Associated Press article\n* Magnuson, Ed. {{cite news|url=http://www.time.com/time/nation/article/0,8599,145082,00.html|title=Hitting the Mafia|accessdate=2006-11-15 | work=Time | date=June 24, 2001 | first=Ed | last=Magnuson}} ''Time''.com January 24, 2001.\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.bop.gov/iloc2/LocateInmate.jsp Federal Bureau of Prisons Inmate Locator Website]\n\n{{Lucchese crime family}}\n{{Lucchese crime family (1963)}}\n{{American Mafia}}\n\n[[Category:Lucchese crime family|*]]\n[[Category:American mobsters of Italian descent|*]]\n", "name_user": "Wiki13565", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eVincent Papa", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_past_Lucchese_crime_family_mobsters"}
{"title_page": "Tarvaris Jackson", "text_new": "{{pp-vandalism|small=yes}}\n{{short description|American football quarterback}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2019}}\n{{Infobox NFL player\n|image=Tarvaris Jackson at 2014 Seahawks Super Bowl parade.jpg\n|image_size=\n|caption=Jackson at the Seahawks' post-<BR>[[Super Bowl XLVIII]] parade in 2014.\n|number=7\n|position=[[Quarterback]]\n|birth_date={{Birth date|1983|4|21|mf=y}}\n|birth_place=[[Montgomery, Alabama]]\n|death_date={{death date and age|2020|4|12|1983|4|21|mf=y}}\n|death_place = Alabama\n|height_ft = 6\n|height_in = 2\n|weight_lbs = 225\n|high_school = [[Sidney Lanier High School|Montgomery (AL) Lanier]]\n|college=[[Alabama State Hornets football|Alabama State]]\n|draftyear=2006\n|draftround=2\n|draftpick=64\n|pastteams=\n* [[Minnesota Vikings]] ({{NFL Year|2006}}\u2013{{NFL Year|2010}})\n* [[Seattle Seahawks]] ({{NFL Year|2011}})\n* [[Buffalo Bills]] ({{NFL Year|2012}})\n* Seattle Seahawks ({{NFL Year|2013}}\u2013{{NFL Year|2015}})\n|pastcoaching = \n* [[Alabama State Hornets football|Alabama State]] (2018)<br>Quality control & quarterbacks coach\n* [[Tennessee State Tigers football|Tennessee State]] (2019)<br>Quarterbacks coach\n|highlights=\n* [[Super Bowl|Super Bowl champion]] ([[Super Bowl XLVIII|XLVIII]])\n* Second-team All-[[Southwestern Athletic Conference|SWAC]] (2005)\n* [[SWAC Championship Game]] MVP (2004)\n|statlabel1=[[Touchdown|TD]]\u2013[[Interception|INT]]\n|statvalue1=39\u201335\n|statlabel2=Passing yards\n|statvalue2=7,263\n|statlabel3=Completion %\n|statvalue3=59.6\n|statlabel4=[[Passer rating|QB Rating]]\n|statvalue4=78.5\n|statlabel5=[[Rush (gridiron football)|Rushing yards]]\n|statvalue5=636\n|statlabel6=[[Touchdown|Rushing TDs]]\n|statvalue6=6\n|nfl=JAC566507\n|pfr=J/JackTa00\n}}\n\n'''Tarvaris Jackson''' (April 21, 1983 \u2013 April 12, 2020) was an [[American football]] [[quarterback]]. Born and raised in [[Montgomery, Alabama]], Jackson played [[college football]] at [[Arkansas Razorbacks football|Arkansas]] and [[Alabama State Hornets football|Alabama State]], and in the [[National Football League]] (NFL) for the [[Minnesota Vikings]], [[Seattle Seahawks]], and [[Buffalo Bills]].\n\nThe Vikings selected Jackson in the second round of the [[2006 NFL Draft]], and Jackson played for the Vikings from 2006 to 2010. A reserve quarterback for much of his time with the Vikings, Jackson was starting quarterback for the [[2007 Minnesota Vikings season|2007 season]] and part of the [[2008 Minnesota Vikings season|2008 season]], after which Jackson started the Vikings' [[2008-09 NFL playoffs#NFC: Philadelphia Eagles 26, Minnesota Vikings 14|Wild Card playoff game]]. In 2011, Jackson signed with the Seahawks and was starting quarterback for [[2011 Seattle Seahawks season|the 2011 season]]. Jackson was then traded to the Bills before the [[2012 NFL season]] but never played a game.  Jackson returned to the Seahawks in 2013. He was the backup quarterback for [[Russell Wilson]] during [[Super Bowl XLVIII]] over the [[Denver Broncos]].\n\n==Early life and college career==\nJackson was born and raised in Montgomery, Alabama, and graduated from [[Sidney Lanier High School]] of Montgomery in 2001.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.montgomeryadvertiser.com/story/sports/college/rankinfile/2016/02/29/montgomery-native-tarvaris-jackson-talks-lanier-alabama-state-football/81114924/ |title=Montgomery native Tarvaris Jackson talks Lanier, ASU football |website=The Montgomery Advertiser |language=en |access-date=June 26, 2019}}</ref> Jackson then enrolled at the [[University of Arkansas]] and played three games for the [[Arkansas Razorbacks football]] team as a freshman but suffered a season-ending injury. Consequently, Jackson received a medical [[Redshirt (college sports)|redshirt]] for the season.<ref name=\"Seahawks bio\">{{cite web|title=Tarvaris Jackson |url=http://www.seahawks.com/team/roster/Tarvaris-Jackson/JAC566507 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110928024705/http://www.seahawks.com/team/roster/Tarvaris-Jackson/JAC566507 |url-status=dead |archive-date=September 28, 2011 |publisher=Seattle Seahawks |accessdate=November 13, 2014 }}</ref> Jackson finished 2001 with 3 of 9 passes completed for 53 yards and 1 interception and rushed 14 yards on 7 carries.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/players/tarvaris-jackson-1/gamelog/2001 |title=Tarvaris Jackson 2001 Game Log |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=June 26, 2019}}</ref> In 2002, Jackson played 8 games. He completed 14 of 39 passes for 143 yards, 1 touchdown, and 2 interceptions and rushed -16 yards in 14 carries.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/players/tarvaris-jackson-1/gamelog/2002 |title=Tarvaris Jackson 2002 Game Log |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=June 26, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"sports ref\">{{cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/players/tarvaris-jackson-1.html|title=Tarvaris Jackson|work=sports-reference.com|accessdate=June 12, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn 2003, after trailing on the depth chart to future first round draft pick [[Matt Jones (wide receiver)|Matt Jones]], Jackson transferred to [[Alabama State University]] and led the [[Alabama State Hornets football|Hornets]] to an 8-5 record, [[Southwestern Athletic Conference]] (SWAC) Eastern Division title, and berth in the [[SWAC Championship Game]].<ref name=\"Seahawks bio\"/> He completed 160 of 316 passes for 2,342 yards, 18 touchdowns, and 13 interceptions and rushed 444 yards on 91 carries including 5 touchdowns.<ref name=\"CBS draft\">{{cite web|author=NFLDraftScout.com|url=http://www.cbssports.com/nfl/draft/players/historical/1107218|title=Tarvaris Jackson Player Profile|publisher=CBS Sports|accessdate=June 12, 2013}}</ref> As a junior in 2004, Jackson won SWAC Championship MVP in Alabama State's second 10-win season in school history.<ref name=\"Seahawks bio\"/> With 11 starts in 12 games, Jackson passed for 2,556 yards, 20 touchdowns, and 9 interceptions. He had 67 carries for 215 yards and 3 touchdowns.<ref name=jstate>[http://www.espn.com/nfl/player/stats/_/id/9650/type/college \"Tarvaris Jackson Stats.\"] ''[[ESPN.com]].'' Retrieved November 6, 2017.</ref> In his senior season in 2005, Jackson was named team captain and was a second-team All-SWAC selection. He threw for 2,655 yards, 25 touchdowns, and 5 interceptions. He rushed for 271 yards and 2 touchdowns on 95 carries.<ref name=jstate/>\n\n===College statistics===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n! rowspan=\"2\"|Year !! rowspan=\"2\"|Team !!  colspan=\"7\" |Passing !! colspan=\"4\" |Rushing\n|-\n! {{tooltip|Cmp|Passes completed}} !! {{tooltip|Att|Passes attempted}} !! {{tooltip|Pct|Completion percentage}} !! {{tooltip|Yds|Passing yards}} !! {{tooltip|Y/A|Yards per passing attempt}} !! {{tooltip|TD|Passing touchdowns}} !! {{tooltip|Int|Interceptions}} !! {{tooltip|Att|Rushing attempts}} !! {{tooltip|Yds|Rushing yards}} !! {{tooltip|Avg|Yards per rushing attempt}} !! {{tooltip|TD|Rushing touchdowns}}\n|-\n|[[2001 NCAA Division I-A football season|2001]] || [[2001 Arkansas Razorbacks football team|ARK]]\n| 3 || 9 ||33.3 ||53 || 5.9 || 0 || 1 || 7 || 14 || 2.0 || 0\n|-\n|[[2002 NCAA Division I-A football season|2002]]|| [[2002 Arkansas Razorbacks football team|ARK]]\n| 14 || 39 ||35.9 ||143 || 3.7 || 1 || 2 || 14 || -16 ||-1.1 || 0\n|-\n|[[2003 NCAA Division I-AA football season|2003]] || [[Alabama State Hornets football|ASU]]\n| 135 ||261 ||51.7 ||1,984 || 7.6 || 18 ||9 || 92 || 454 || 4.9 || 5\n|-\n|[[2004 NCAA Division I-AA football season|2004]] || ASU\n| 183 ||350 ||52.3 ||2,562 || 7.3 || 20 ||9 || 67 || 215 || 3.2 || 3\n|-\n|[[2005 NCAA Division I-AA football season|2005]] || ASU\n| 181 ||296 ||61.1 ||2,655 || 9.0 || 25 ||5 || 95 || 271 || 2.9 || 3\n|- class=\"sortbottom\" style=\"background:#eee;\"\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total !! 516 !! 955 !! 54 !! 7,397 !! 6.69 !!  64 !! 26 !! 275 !! 938 !! 3.14 !! 11\n|}\n\n==Professional career==\n\n===2006 NFL Draft===\n{{NFL predraft\n|    height ft = 6\n|    height in = 2\n|       weight = 226\n|         dash = 4.69\n|    ten split = 1.63\n| twenty split = 2.78\n|      shuttle = 4.10\n|   cone drill = 7.41\n|     vertical = 31{{frac|1|2}}\n|     broad ft = 8\n|     broad in =11 \n|        bench = 22\n|    wonderlic = 19\n|     arm span = 31\n|    hand span = 9{{frac|3|8}}\n|         note = All values were taken at the [[NFL Scouting Combine]],<ref name=\"draft scout\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nfldraftscout.com/ratings/dsprofile.php?pyid=55979&draftyear=2006&genpos=qb|title=Tarvaris Jackson|work=NFL Draft Scout|publisher=The Sports Xchange|accessdate=June 12, 2013}}</ref> except bench press, arm span, hand span, and Wonderlic that were taken at Alabama State [[Pro Day]];<ref name=\"CBS draft\"/> see also {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060519103659/http://www.nfl.com/draft/profiles/2006/jackson_tarvaris |date=May 19, 2006 |title=NFL prospect profile }}.\n}}\n\nVikings scouts and personnel had reportedly been watching him closely in secret over his senior season, particularly liking his performance in the [[East-West Shrine Game]]. They were also impressed by his workout at the [[NFL Combine|scouting combine]] (among the top 5 quarterbacks in ball speed and the 40-yard dash). Several NFL teams, including the Vikings, had arranged secret workouts with him too. Jackson was selected with the last pick in the 2nd round (64th overall) of the [[2006 NFL Draft]], while he was projected to go much later, in the sixth or seventh round.<ref name=\"draft scout\"/> The Vikings traded two 3rd round picks to get the 2nd round pick with which they drafted Jackson, fearing he might get picked sooner than anticipated. Jackson's early selection caused some surprise, as he was the 5th quarterback taken and the 1st [[Division I (NCAA)|Division I-AA]] player selected (the previous I-AA quarterback drafted was [[Spergon Wynn]] in 2000). He was also the first quarterback from Alabama State to be drafted into the NFL since Ricky Jones in 1992. Even Jackson was surprised by the pick, saying, \"I was more focused on [getting drafted in] the third round and even that was stretching it\".<ref>[http://www.onnidan.com/05-06/news/april/alst0429.htm Jackson's Reaction]. Jackson's reaction after getting drafted.</ref> Most pre-draft publications did not even have him listed as one of the top 10 eligible quarterbacks, while he was the 5th selected. On July 26, 2006, Jackson signed a four-year deal with Minnesota, including a $1 million signing bonus.<ref>\"[http://www.cbc.ca/cp/football/060726/f072680.html Vikings sign quarterback Tarvaris Jackson to four-year contract]\". Originally published on July 26, 2006. Retrieved on April 16, 2007.</ref>\n\nVikings coach [[Brad Childress]] was quoted days before the draft as saying he was interested in finding a \"developmental guy\", a \"diamond in the rough\" quarterback of the future, raw talent he could teach a system.<ref>[https://archive.is/20070318124007/http://www.shns.com/shns/g_index2.cfm?action=detail&pk=FBN-VIKINGS-04-26-06 Childress Quotes before draft]. Childress quotes before the draft.</ref> Both new coach Childress and Vikings former quarterback [[Brad Johnson (American football)|Brad Johnson]] had had success developing quarterbacks in the past, including [[A. J. Feeley]] and [[Donovan McNabb]].\n\nThe day after the draft, Childress was quoted by the ''[[St. Paul Pioneer Press]]'' as saying: \"I think you judge quarterbacks a little bit differently...When you see what you want at the quarterback position, you need to go get it. And that's exactly what I see with Tarvaris Jackson is a guy that's a piece of clay, that has all the skills in terms of, No. 1, what's he look like throwing the football?...He's got a great throwing motion; he's athletic.  He has all those things that we're looking for, and he's wired right. That's important for a quarterback. I think he's a flatline guy. I think he's a sponge. You're talking about a guy that never had a coach there as a quarterback coach. So what can he do with coaching?\"<ref>\"That's a good question,\" many people reply, noting that Jackson is Seattle's only Black Mormon.  [http://vikings.scout.com/2/526690.html Childress Quotes after draft] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060828071130/http://vikings.scout.com/2/526690.html |date=August 28, 2006 }}.</ref> Jackson's agent, Joel Segal, said: \"After the draft, there were two clubs that expressed disappointment and were mad they didn't get him. They were planning to take (Jackson) very high in the third round, and were lamenting the fact that the Vikings beat them\".\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n| colspan=\"10\" align=\"center\" |  ''Pre-draft measureables''\n|-\n!Wt\n![[40-yard dash|40y]]\n![[20-yard shuttle|20ss]]\n![[3 cone drill|3-cone]]\n![[Vertical jump|Vert]]\n![[Bench Press|BP]]\n![[Wonderlic]]\n|-\n| ALIGN=\"center\" |226&nbsp;lb*\n| ALIGN=\"center\" |4.75s*<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/nfl/draft06/news/story?id=2380236|title=Scout: Young's 40 time of 4.58 slower than expected|date=March 23, 2006|publisher=|accessdate=July 1, 2016}}</ref>\n| ALIGN=\"center\" |4.38s*\n| ALIGN=\"center\" |7.40s*\n| ALIGN=\"center\" |31{{frac|1|2}}\"*\n| ALIGN=\"center\" |22*<ref>[http://www.packers.com/news/stories/2006/04/27/1/ Packers.com \u00bb News \u00bb Stories \u00bb April 27, 2006: Gil Brandt's Analysis By Position: Quarterbacks<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071012204351/http://www.packers.com/news/stories/2006/04/27/1/ |date=October 12, 2007 }}</ref>\n| ALIGN=\"center\" |19 <ref>{{cite web|url=http://nflcombineresults.com/playerpage.php?f=Tarvaris&l=Jackson&i=7407|title=Tarvaris Jackson - QB - Alabama State - 2006 NFL Combine Results|publisher=|accessdate=July 1, 2016}}</ref>\n|}\n(''* represents [[NFL Combine]]'')\n\n===Minnesota Vikings===\n\n====2006 season====\nJackson's 2006 pre-season [[passer rating]] was 106.1, 15th in the league out of 110 quarterbacks who performed. Only one quarterback from his draft class ([[Jay Cutler (American football)|Jay Cutler]]) did better. He also showed great scrambling skills averaging 11.3 yards in rushing (the only Viking other than [[Brad Johnson (American football)|Brad Johnson]] to average more than 3.3 yards in rushing). [[ESPN]] analyst [[Mike Tirico]] referred to Jackson as a right-handed [[Michael Vick]]. His pre-season performance was enough to surpass second and third-string quarterbacks [[Mike McMahon (American football)|Mike McMahon]] and [[J. T. O'Sullivan]] on the depth chart. After the pre-season, McMahon and O'Sullivan were cut from the team and [[Brooks Bollinger]] was brought in, whom Jackson then competed against for the number two spot.\n\nOn September 25, 2006, Jackson had minor knee surgery to repair the [[Meniscus (anatomy)|meniscus]] in his knee. He returned to limited practice after two weeks, and then came back to play his first NFL game with the Vikings in week 13 against the [[2006 Chicago Bears|Chicago Bears]]<ref>[http://www.twincities.com/mld/twincities/sports/15727620.htm HOME - TwinCities.com<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> in the fourth quarter after Johnson was benched for throwing four interceptions and backup quarterback Brooks Bollinger was injured. Jackson completed three of his four passes before fumbling the ball to Chicago and the Bears then ran the clock out. Following this game when Jackson was asked if he was ready to take over as starter he said \"Not really...We still have a chance to make the playoffs, so we're still trying to do that. So it's obvious that Brad is still our quarterback so we can stay on that.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Vikings Staring at a Quarterback Controversy|url=http://www.sportsnetwork.com/default.asp?c=sportsnetwork&page=/nfl/news/ABN4052702.htm|author=Benoit, Andy|publisher=The Sports Network|accessdate=May 9, 2007}}{{dead link|date=March 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nIn Week 15, Johnson started the game but was benched in the fourth quarter when the Vikings had been underperforming the entire game losing by a score of 26-7 at the time Jackson went in late in the third quarter against the [[2006 New York Jets|New York Jets]]. Although Johnson had not thrown an interception that game and had a respectable passer rating of 94.2 in the game, the Minnesota fans jeered Johnson throughout the game and chanted \"We want Jackson!\" at numerous points because Johnson had only thrown nine touchdowns all season (in 14 games) and had a career worst 71.9 passer rating throughout the season. Jackson received a standing ovation as he trotted out onto the field. A landmark in Jackson's career happened that game when Jackson completed his first touchdown pass to [[Mewelde Moore]]. Jackson threw 177 yards, one touchdown, and ran three times for 20 yards while the Jets protected their large lead. He also threw an interception in the red zone.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/200612170min.htm |title=New York Jets at Minnesota Vikings - December 17th, 2006 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=June 26, 2019}}</ref>\n\nJackson was named the starting quarterback for Minnesota towards the end of his rookie season.  Jackson's first game was a week 16 night game against the [[2006 Green Bay Packers|Green Bay Packers]] at [[Lambeau Field]].  Game conditions were very poor.  A steady rain fell throughout the evening and the kickoff temperature was only 36 degrees Fahrenheit. The Vikings lost by a score of 9-7 with the only Vikings score coming from an interception for a touchdown by defensive back [[Fred Smoot]]. The offense set a franchise low record of only three first downs the whole game, did not get close enough to the end zone to even attempt a field goal, and only had 27 passing yards gained against the NFL's 19th ranked defense (ranked 26th against the pass). Jackson had a passer rating of 36.5, had a 50% completion rate (10-20 for 50 yards), one interception, and one fumble.  Packers quarterback Brett Favre only managed a slightly better 52% completion rate (26-50) and threw two interceptions. He threw for 285 yards with no touchdowns.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/200612210gnb.htm |title=Minnesota Vikings at Green Bay Packers - December 21st, 2006 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=June 26, 2019}}</ref>\n\n====2007 season====\nJackson did not live up to the Vikings' expectations in 2007 despite finishing 8-4 as a starter.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/J/JackTa00/gamelog/2007/ |title=Tarvaris Jackson 2007 Game Log |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=June 26, 2019}}</ref> Jackson had nine touchdowns and 12 interceptions, along with a 159 yards per game, causing the Vikings to have the second-worst passing offense in the NFL.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/2007/index.htm |title=2007 NFL Standings & Team Stats |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=June 26, 2019}}</ref> His 70.8 passer rating was 28th among NFL quarterbacks.  Jackson missed three games because of injuries, which included a strained groin, a concussion and a fractured index finger. The Vikings failed to make the playoffs.  Analysts put the Vikings' 8-8 record on the successful running of [[Chester Taylor]] and rookie [[Adrian Peterson]], which took the pressure off of Jackson and the defense.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/min/2007.htm |title=2007 Minnesota Vikings Statistics & Players |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=June 26, 2019}}</ref>\n\nLater in the season, opponents decided to focus all their defensive efforts on stopping Peterson and the Vikings running game, while daring Jackson to beat them in the passing game.  The [[2007 Washington Redskins|Washington Redskins]] successfully utilized five [[defensive lineman]] or four [[linebackers]] against the Vikings, leaving only two or three defensive backs in pass coverage.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20071225070431/http://www.startribune.com/sports/vikings/12791702.html Washington D focuses all its attention on Peterson]</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/12/27/AR2007122702318.html|title=Wrinkles Changed Playoff Complexion|first=Jason|last=Reid|date=December 28, 2007|publisher=|accessdate=July 1, 2016|via=washingtonpost.com}}</ref>  And the 49ers blitzed their [[cornerback]]s 20 percent of the time instead of covering receivers with them.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.startribune.com/sports/vikings/12522941.html?elr=KArksi8cyaiU9PmP:QiUiD3aPc:_Yyc:aUU|title=Patrick Reusse: Fans shouldn't go overboard on Jackson yet|publisher=|accessdate=July 1, 2016}}</ref><ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20110723221658/http://www.wtov9.com/sports/14824511/detail.html Vikings Enjoying Quite A Turnaround]</ref>  On the season's last game against the [[2007 Denver Broncos|Denver Broncos]], Jackson led the Vikings to two fourth quarter drives to tie the game and send it into overtime. In overtime, however, Jackson fumbled on the second play and the Vikings lost the game.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/200712300den.htm |title=Minnesota Vikings at Denver Broncos - December 30th, 2007 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=June 26, 2019}}</ref> Jackson showed slow improvement over the season: he played a large role when the Vikings went on a five-game winning streak in November, but also showed his inexperience in several ill-judged interceptions, jump passes, and turnovers.  After the season, Childress would not say if Tarvaris Jackson would be the starter in 2008, explaining that he wanted to \"evaluate the total body of work\" first.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20071226171506/http://www.startribune.com/sports/vikings/12806557.html Childress noncommittal over quarterback's long-term future]</ref>\n\n====2008 season====\nThere was a lot of media coverage on Jackson the summer of 2008. The Vikings returned seven players that were in the [[2008 Pro Bowl]] (only three teams had more), and spent $60 million in guaranteed contract money upgrading their team with [[Jared Allen]], traded from the [[Kansas City Chiefs]], and free agents [[Bernard Berrian]] and [[Madieu Williams]]. Several analysts believed better quarterback play was all that was needed to make the Vikings one of the top contending teams in the NFL, and with the [[Green Bay Packers]] losing [[Brett Favre]] the [[NFC North Division]] was up for grabs.  [[Sport's Illustrated]]'s [[Paul Lionel Zimmerman|Paul Zimmerman]] predicted the Vikings would win the Super Bowl.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2008/writers/dr_z/06/20/vikings/index.html|title=Dare I pick Minnesota to win it all?|publisher=|accessdate=July 1, 2016}}</ref>\n\nHead coach Brad Childress decided to stay with Jackson as the starting quarterback and brought in [[Gus Frerotte]] to be his backup. It was widely reported in the off-season that Jackson had a new swagger, handled situations in practice well where he looked lost in the previous years, and had an improved grasp of the Vikings offensive system.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20080526142945/http://www.startribune.com/sports/vikings/19160244.html?location_refer=Vikings QB Jackson acting the part]</ref>  Childress threw a \"Coaching 101\" clinic for media reporters in which he played a tape of Jackson showing the progress he made in 2007 through a series of missed passes or poor decisions that he made in early games but executed properly in later contests and concluded with some tape of him hitting a target net with every 15-yard pass he threw during an offseason drill.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20081014115851/http://blogs.twincities.com/Vikings/2008/05/coaching_101_clinic.html Coaching 101 clinic]</ref>  Offensive coordinator [[Darrell Bevell]] repeatedly told the press that although it was Jackson's third year with the Vikings it was really his second year playing, and NFL quarterbacks improve the most between their first and second years.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20080727125711/http://blogs.twincities.com/Vikings/2008/05/bevell_on_tjack.html Bevell on T-Jack]</ref>  Jackson had another good preseason, until he injured his knee again in the second preseason game which kept him from playing the last two preseason games.\n\nIn the first game of the regular season against the [[2008 Green Bay Packers|Green Bay Packers]], Jackson threw a game-ending interception and in the second game the Vikings made five field goal attempts and no touchdowns against the [[2008 Indianapolis Colts|Indianapolis Colts]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/200809080gnb.htm |title=Minnesota Vikings at Green Bay Packers - September 8th, 2008 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=June 26, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/200809140min.htm |title=Indianapolis Colts at Minnesota Vikings - September 14th, 2008 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=June 26, 2019}}</ref> The Vikings lost both games by close margins, and Jackson's 64.8 passer rating ranked him 26th in the NFL. Childress said in the second post-game press conference that Jackson would still definitely be the starter next week, but on Monday after a coaches' meeting he changed his mind and benched Jackson for the remainder of the year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.nfl.com/|title=Official Blog of the National Football League|publisher=|accessdate=July 1, 2016}}</ref>\n[[File:20090104 Chester Taylor.JPG|thumb|left|250px|Jackson (7) with the Vikings.]]\nAfter being relegated to backup after the loss to the Colts, Jackson saw his next significant action in Week 14 against [[2008 Detroit Lions|Detroit]], where he played the entire second half in place of an injured [[Gus Frerotte]]. With the Vikings trailing 6-3 at halftime to the winless Lions, Jackson completed eight of ten passes for 105 yards and a touchdown, an 11-yard strike to tight end [[Visanthe Shiancoe]] that would be the game-winning score for the Vikings.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.twincities.com/2008/12/07/tarvaris-jackson-steps-in-for-gus-frerotte-leads-minnesota-vikings-to-comeback-victory/|title=Tarvaris Jackson steps in for Gus Frerotte, leads Minnesota Vikings to comeback victory \u2013 Twin Cities|publisher=|accessdate=July 1, 2016}}</ref>  The following week, with Frerotte still injured, Jackson was the starting quarterback against the [[2008 Arizona Cardinals|Arizona Cardinals]] and he played arguably the best game of his career.  Jackson completed 11 of 17 passes for 163 yards and, most impressively, threw four touchdown passes and no interceptions.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/200812140crd.htm |title=Minnesota Vikings at Arizona Cardinals - December 14th, 2008 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=June 26, 2019}}</ref> Jackson earned NFC Offensive Player of the Week honors for his performance as well as the [[FedEx Air & Ground NFL Players of the Week|FedEx Air Player of the Week]] award.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/2008/week_15.htm |title=2008 NFL Week 15 Leaders & Scores |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=June 26, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe Vikings lost 24-17 to the [[2008 Atlanta Falcons|Atlanta Falcons]] in Week 16 despite Jackson's performance.  He completed 22 of 36 passes for 233 yards with two touchdowns and no interceptions.  He also rushed for 76 yards (which matched the total of Pro-Bowl running back [[Adrian Peterson]]).<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/200812210min.htm |title=Atlanta Falcons at Minnesota Vikings - December 21st, 2008 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=June 26, 2019}}</ref>  With the Vikings in a win-and-in situation against the [[2008 New York Giants|New York Giants]] in Week 17, Jackson overcame an interception in the end zone by leading the Vikings on a touchdown drive (a 54-yard strike to [[Bernard Berrian]]) and the game-winning field goal drive on the following possessions.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/200812280min.htm |title=New York Giants at Minnesota Vikings - December 28th, 2008 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=June 26, 2019}}</ref> The Vikings defeated the Giants 20-19 and earned the NFC North title.\n<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.twincities.com/2008/12/27/minnesota-vikings-wrap-up-nfc-north-championship-on-final-play-of-regular-season-next-up-philadelphia-eagles/|title=Minnesota Vikings wrap up NFC North championship on final play of regular season. Next up: Philadelphia Eagles \u2013 Twin Cities|publisher=|accessdate=July 1, 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe Vikings season ended in the Wild Card Round of the playoffs with a loss to the [[2008 Philadelphia Eagles|Philadelphia Eagles]]. Jackson went 15-for-35 for 164 yards in the game with one interception.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/200901040min.htm |title=Wild Card - Philadelphia Eagles at Minnesota Vikings - January 4th, 2009 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=June 26, 2019}}</ref>\n\n====2009 season====\nJackson went into the 2009 season in competition for a starting job with [[Sage Rosenfels]], who the Vikings had acquired from the [[Houston Texans]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/news/story?id=3939155 |title=Vikings acquire Rosenfels, give QB new contract |date=February 27, 2009 |website=ESPN.com |language=en |access-date=June 26, 2019}}</ref> The Vikings also pursued former [[New York Jets]] and [[Green Bay Packers]] quarterback [[Brett Favre]], who had retired after the end of the 2008 season. Favre announced that he would not join the Vikings prior to [[training camp]], however, and Jackson and Rosenfels split duties in the early part of camp.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20090731104335/http://www.sportingnews.com/blog/The_Trenches/entry/view/28956/vikings_favre_will_stay_retired The Sporting News]</ref> Jackson was the second quarterback to play in the opening preseason game, and was expected to start the second preseason game against the [[Kansas City Chiefs]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ballhype.com/article/minnesota_vikings_qb_tarvaris_jackson_gets_chance_to/|title=Home - Future PLC|publisher=|accessdate=July 1, 2016}}</ref>\n\nThat changed, however, when Favre announced that he would play for the Vikings after all, signing with the team on August 19.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=4406963|title=Purple reign: Indecisive Favre signs with Vikings|date=August 19, 2009|publisher=|accessdate=July 1, 2016}}</ref> Jackson, Rosenfels, and 2008 third-stringer [[John David Booty]] were believed to be competing for two roster spots, and for the primary backup job. Many observers believed the Vikings would attempt to trade Jackson.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bleacherreport.com/articles/240097-with-favre-on-board-who-will-be-the-odd-man-out|title=With Favre on Board, Who Will Be the Odd Man Out?|first=Brett|last=Stott|publisher=|accessdate=July 1, 2016}}</ref>\n\nJackson helped his case with a strong performance in Favre's debut game against the [[2009 Kansas City Chiefs|Kansas City Chiefs]], throwing for 202 yards and two touchdowns in backup work.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://scores.espn.go.com/nfl/recap?gameId=290821016|title=Chiefs vs. Vikings - Game Recap - August 21, 2009 - ESPN|publisher=|accessdate=July 1, 2016}}</ref> Ultimately, the Vikings elected to keep Jackson and Rosenfels on the active roster, with Jackson as the primary backup to Favre.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gridironfans.com/forums/latest-nfl-headlines/107377-vikings-qb-tarvaris-jackson-backup-vs-cleveland.html|title=Fantasy Football Forum|accessdate=July 1, 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120310113848/http://gridironfans.com/forums/latest-nfl-headlines/107377-vikings-qb-tarvaris-jackson-backup-vs-cleveland.html|archivedate=March 10, 2012}}</ref>\n\nJackson entered the Vikings' first two games of the season in [[garbage time]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nfl.com/gamecenter/2009091304/2009/REG1/vikings@browns|title=Watch Minnesota Vikings vs. Cleveland Browns [09/13/2009] - NFL.com|publisher=|accessdate=July 1, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/blog/nfcnorth/post/_/id/3595/third-and-one-vikings-2|title=Third and one: Vikings|publisher=|accessdate=July 1, 2016}}</ref> He also was used as a decoy in [[Punt (gridiron football)|punt]] coverage during week two.\n\n====2010 season====\nThe Vikings re-signed Jackson on Monday, April 19 as they waited for Favre to decide whether he would return for another season, which he did.  Jackson was a restricted free agent who was given a one-year tender worth $1.176 million. Jackson backed up Favre for the 2010 season.\n\nJackson took over for an injured Favre in Week 8 against the [[2010 New England Patriots|New England Patriots]]. Jackson threw for one touchdown in the loss.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201010310nwe.htm |title=Minnesota Vikings at New England Patriots - October 31st, 2010 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=June 26, 2019}}</ref> Jackson took over for an injured Favre yet again in Week 13 against the [[2010 Buffalo Bills|Buffalo Bills]]. Jackson threw two touchdown passes to [[Sidney Rice]] in the 38-14 win, but also threw three interceptions.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201012050min.htm |title=Buffalo Bills at Minnesota Vikings - December 5th, 2010 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=June 26, 2019}}</ref> Jackson started on December 13, against the [[2010 New York Giants|New York Giants]] in place of the injured Favre.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201012130min.htm |title=New York Giants at Minnesota Vikings - December 13th, 2010 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=June 26, 2019}}</ref> In that game, Jackson suffered a turf toe injury and missed the rest of the season.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.duluthnewstribune.com/sports/2304817-vikings-sign-qb-jackson-out-turf-toe |title=Vikings sign QB; Jackson out with turf toe |website=Duluth News Tribune |language=en |access-date=June 26, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn March 3, 2011, the Vikings declined to tender Jackson a contract offer to play for them in the 2011 season. Under league rules, Jackson became an [[unrestricted free agent]].\n\n===Seattle Seahawks===\nJackson officially signed a two-year contract with Seattle Seahawks on July 29, 2011<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.seahawks.com/news/articles/article-1/Seahawks-Sign-Rookie-Veterans-and-Draft-Pick-to-Roster/7fe2920f-0f50-4029-a6c1-77eefde2eb0b |title=Seahawks Sign Rookie, Veterans and Draft Pick to Roster |date=July 29, 2011 |website=Seahawks.com |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140318002841/http://www.seahawks.com/news/articles/article-1/Seahawks-Sign-Rookie-Veterans-and-Draft-Pick-to-Roster/7fe2920f-0f50-4029-a6c1-77eefde2eb0b |archive-date=March 18, 2014 |url-status=dead |access-date=July 1, 2016}}</ref> and was announced as the starting quarterback shortly after.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.seahawks.com/news/articles/article-1/Carroll-hands-the-ball-to-T-Jack/c7e3f5c1-cbc1-412f-a859-c84c7bc00a15 |title=Carroll hands the ball to T-Jack |date=July 30, 2011 |website=Seahawks.com |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140318002303/http://www.seahawks.com/news/articles/article-1/Carroll-hands-the-ball-to-T-Jack/c7e3f5c1-cbc1-412f-a859-c84c7bc00a15 |archive-date=March 18, 2014 |url-status=dead |access-date=July 1, 2016}}</ref> In Seattle, he had been reunited with offensive coordinator [[Darrell Bevell]] and wide receiver [[Sidney Rice]] both members of the Vikings during his time there. Along with [[wide receiver]] [[Mike Williams (wide receiver, born 1984)|Mike Williams]], Jackson was appointed to offensive team captain, which was previously owned by [[Matt Hasselbeck]], who signed with the [[Tennessee Titans]]. Despite having a below-average year compared to other quarterbacks in the league, Jackson had the best year of his career, finishing with 3,091 yards passing, throwing 14 touchdowns and 13 interceptions.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/J/JackTa00/gamelog/2011/ |title=Tarvaris Jackson 2011 Game Log |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=June 26, 2019}}</ref> During the off-season, the Seahawks acquired former [[Green Bay Packers]] quarterback [[Matt Flynn]] and drafted Wisconsin quarterback [[Russell Wilson]] to compete with Jackson for the 2012 starting quarterback position.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/09000d5d827af666/article/seahawks-qb-matt-flynn-agree-to-threeyear-26m-contract |title=Seahawks, QB Matt Flynn agree to three-year, $26M contract |website=NFL.com |language=en |access-date=June 26, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/2012/draft.htm |title=2012 NFL Draft Listing |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=June 26, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Buffalo Bills===\n[[File:Tarvaris Jackson 2013.jpg|thumb|Jackson in 2013.]]\nOn August 26, 2012, Jackson was traded to the [[Buffalo Bills]] for a conditional seventh round draft pick.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap1000000055085/article/tarvaris-jackson-to-be-traded-to-buffalo-bills|title=Tarvaris Jackson to be traded to Buffalo Bills|last=Sessler|first=Mark|date=August 26, 2012|accessdate=August 27, 2012}}</ref> The third-string quarterback for the season, Jackson did not see any game action in 2012.<ref name=\"Seahawks bio\"/><ref name=\"Seattle likely\">{{cite web|title=Tarvaris Jackson to Seattle likely|url=http://espn.go.com/nfl/story/_/id/9375100/seattle-seahawks-likely-sign-tarvaris-jackson|publisher=ESPN|accessdate=June 12, 2013|date=June 12, 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn February 15, 2013, the Bills re-signed Jackson to a one-year, $2.25 million deal.<ref>{{cite web|work=BuffaloBills.com|url=http://www.buffalobills.com/news/article-2/QB-Tarvaris-Jackson-re-signs-with-Bills/9383cbef-ea1a-47e5-8fd8-f84bf4d925fc|title=QB Tarvaris Jackson re-signs with Bills|date=February 15, 2013|first=Chris|last=Brown|accessdate=March 31, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|work=NBCSports.com|url=http://profootballtalk.nbcsports.com/2013/02/19/tarvaris-jackson-deal-has-base-value-of-225-million/|title=Tarvaris Jackson deal has base value of $2.25 million|first=Mike|last=Florio|date=February 19, 2013|accessdate=March 31, 2013}}</ref> He was released on June 10, 2013.<ref>{{cite web|last=Rosenthal|first=Gregg|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap1000000210671/article/tarvaris-jackson-released-by-buffalo-bills|title=Tarvaris Jackson released by Buffalo Bills|publisher=[[National Football League]]|date=June 10, 2013|accessdate=June 10, 2013}}</ref> [[ESPN]] reported on June 12 that Jackson was likely to re-sign with the [[Seattle Seahawks]] for the 2013 season.<ref name=\"Seattle likely\"/>\n\n===Seattle Seahawks (second stint)===\nOn June 13, 2013, Jackson signed a one-year deal with the [[Seattle Seahawks]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Wesseling|first=Chris|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap1000000212193/article/tarvaris-jackson-seattle-seahawks-sign-contract|title=Tarvaris Jackson, Seattle Seahawks sign contract|publisher=[[National Football League]]|date=June 13, 2013|accessdate=August 25, 2013}}</ref> Jackson competed with [[Brady Quinn]] for the backup quarterback spot behind starter [[Russell Wilson]]. To coincide with the signing of Jackson, the [[Seattle Seahawks]] released quarterback [[Jerrod Johnson]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://blog.seattlepi.com/football/2013/06/14/seahawks-officially-sign-tarvaris-jackson-release-jerrod-johnson/ |title=Seahawks officially sign Tarvaris Jackson, release Jerrod Johnson |last=Quinton |first=Sean |date=June 14, 2013 |website=Seattle Seahawks & NFL News |language=en-US |access-date=June 26, 2019}}</ref> The Seahawks released quarterback Brady Quinn and made Jackson the official backup quarterback to Wilson.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap1000000237020/article/brady-quinn-loses-seattle-seahawks-backup-qb-fight |title=Brady Quinn loses Seattle Seahawks' backup QB fight |last=Hanzus |first=Dan |date=August 31, 2013 |website=NFL.com |language=en |access-date=June 26, 2019}}</ref> Jackson appeared in three games of the 2013 regular season producing 151 passing yards and a touchdown.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/J/JackTa00/gamelog/2013/ |title=Tarvaris Jackson 2013 Game Log |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=June 26, 2019}}</ref> During [[Super Bowl XLVIII]] against the [[2013 Denver Broncos season|Denver Broncos]], Jackson came in relief of [[Russell Wilson]] during the fourthquarter, marking the first time in 13 years any backup quarterback has played in a Super Bowl. The Seahawks won their first Super Bowl in franchise history as they defeated the Broncos 43\u20138.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201402020den.htm |title=Super Bowl XLVIII - Seattle Seahawks vs. Denver Broncos - February 2nd, 2014 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=June 26, 2019}}</ref> Following the season, Jackson signed a one-year deal to stay with the Seahawks. The Seahawks made it to [[Super Bowl XLIX]], but failed to repeat as Super Bowl champions as they fell to the [[New England Patriots]] by a score of 28\u201324.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201502010sea.htm |title=Super Bowl XLIX - Seattle Seahawks vs. New England Patriots - February 1st, 2015 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=June 26, 2019}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the 2015 season, Jackson became an unrestricted free agent.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000636138/article/report-tarvaris-jackson-will-hit-free-agency |title=Report: Tarvaris Jackson will hit free agency |website=NFL.com |language=en |access-date=June 26, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n\n===Arrest in alleged domestic violence incident===\nOn June 24, 2016, Jackson was arrested in [[Kissimmee, Florida]].  In July 2016, Jackson said he did not have money to pay for an attorney and requested a public defender.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/sports/seahawks/report-ex-seahawk-qb-tarvaris-jackson-says-hes-broke/ |title=Ex-Seahawk QB Tarvaris Jackson says he\u2019s broke, asks for public defender, is denied |date=July 1, 2016 |website=The Seattle Times |language=en-US |access-date=June 26, 2019}}</ref> On August 3, 2016, the Florida Assistant State Attorney dropped the case.<ref name=\"FL DA\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.startribune.com/ex-vikings-qb-tarvaris-jackson-won-t-be-prosecuted-for-alleged-assault/389081991/ |title=Ex-Vikings QB Tarvaris Jackson won't be prosecuted for alleged assault |last=Gonzalez |first=Jason |publisher=Star Tribune |access-date=May 30, 2017}}.</ref>\n\n===Coaching===\nIn 2018, Jackson took a graduate assistant role at Alabama State, his alma mater.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://247sports.com/nfl/seattle-seahawks/Article/Tarvaris-Jackson-moves-on-from-NFL-career-to-coaching-114238157/ |title=Tarvaris Jackson moves on from NFL career to coaching |website=247 Sports |language=en-US |access-date=June 26, 2019}}</ref> In 2019, Jackson was named quarterbacks coach for [[Tennessee State Tigers football|Tennessee State]].<ref>http://www.tsutigers.com/football/roster/2019-20/7633/tarvaris-jackson/</ref>\n\n===Death===\nJackson was killed on April 12, 2020, in a car accident in Alabama. The [[Alabama Law Enforcement Agency]] said that Jackson was involved in a single-car crash at 8:50 p.m.<ref>{{cite tweet |user=RapSheet |title=Former #Seahawks QB Tarvaris Jackson died last night in a car accident in Alabama, a spokesperson for his employer Tennessee State tells me. Jackson, 36, was TSU\u2019s QB coach. Along with Seattle, he also played for the #Vikings and #Bills. |number=1249692214713880576 |date=April 13, 2020 |accessdate=April 13, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Pattra |first1=Kevin |title=Former NFL QB Tarvaris Jackson dies in car crash |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000001109122/article/former-nfl-qb-tarvaris-jackson-dies-in-car-crash |website=NFL.com |accessdate=13 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/story/_/id/29029379/former-vikings-seahawks-qb-tarvaris-jackson-dies-car-accident|title=Ex-NFL QB Tarvaris Jackson dies in car crash|date=13 April 2020|website=ESPN.com|first=Courtney|last=Cronin|language=en|access-date=13 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n! rowspan=\"2\"|Year !! rowspan=\"2\"|Team !! rowspan=\"2\"|{{tooltip|G|Games played}} !! rowspan=2 | {{tooltip|GS|Games started}} !! colspan=\"9\" |Passing !! colspan=\"4\" |Rushing !! colspan=\"2\" |Sacked !! colspan=\"2\" |Fumbles\n|-\n! {{tooltip|Cmp|Passes completed}} !! {{tooltip|Att|Passes attempted}} !! {{tooltip|Pct|Completion percentage}} !! {{tooltip|Yds|Passing yards}} !! {{tooltip|Y/A|Yards per passing attempt}} !! 